<FILEID>AP-NR-03-06-89 0257EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-RushdieDebate     03-06 0731</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Rushdie Debate,0753</SECOND>
<HEAD>Second Thoughts And Gritted Teeth On `The Satanic Verses'</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Monday AMs report.</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BARR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   No one in Britain outside of the Moslem community
has endorsed the Iranian death sentence against Salman Rushdie, but
some are supporting the author of ``The Satanic Verses'' through
gritted teeth.
   ``An insidious outbreak of `yes-but' has entered the public
debate on the rights and rightness of his case,'' the Observer
newspaper said in an editorial Sunday.
   The debate even popped up at a Writers' Day conference organized
by British Pen, the association of poets, essayist and novelists.
   Most wrote supportive greetings to Rushdie in a book that was
left open for messages, but one entry said: ``Personal freedom is
constrained by personal responsibility. You are shown to be wanting
in the latter.''
   Below it, another writer asserted: ``Freedom is freedom. It does
not imply restraint.''
   The liberal Observer said it was disturbed by statements by Prime
Minister Margaret Thatcher and Foreign Secretary Sir Geoffrey Howe
last week that the book was offensive, and by the opinion of Lord
Jakobovits, Britain's chief rabbi, that such books should be banned.
   They are not alone in their criticisms.
   ``Mr. Rushdie's life has to be defended at all costs, but not
necessarily his book,'' The Daily Telegraph, a conservative
newspaper, said in an editorial last week.
   A cartoon in The Sunday Express showed Rushdie dressed like
Iran's Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini, with a flowing beard of pound
notes labeled ``my royalties,'' and threatening the foreign
secretary. ``Blasphemy, Sir Geoffrey,'' the caption said. ``I shall
call upon the authors of the world to spear you with their pens.''
   Rushdie has been in hiding since Feb. 14, when Khomeini sentenced
him to death. Iranian clergymen have offered a bounty of as much as
$5.2 million.
   Mrs. Thatcher said Saturday that Britain still insists Iran
repudiate the death sentence before diplomatic relations can be
normalized. Britain has withdrawn its diplomats from Tehran.
   The Majlis, Iran's legislature, has set Tuesday as a deadline for
breaking diplomatic relations unless Britain ``clarifies'' its
position on the book.
   Iran's official news agency said Sunday that ``the withdrawal of
all copies of `The Satanic Verses' and banning of its reprinting by
the British government would certainly bring London closer to the
implementation of the Iranian conditions.''
   Many of those in Britain who criticize the book stop short of
calling for it to be banned.
   Hartley Shawcross, a prominent attorney and a former chairman of
the Press Council, wrote to The Times that Rushdie had committed ``a
deplorable abuse of the freedom which he shares with the rest of us,
but which we must nonetheless defend.''
   ``The Rushdie book has done incalculable harm to the interests of
all people, not with any intention of contribution to scholarship
but in order to sensationalize a novel in the hope of securing its
better sale,'' Shawcross wrote.
   In its editorial, The Telegraph said that ``free speech to some
degree depends on responsibility in exercising it.''
   ``A civilized society is unwise to insist that all abuses of
freedom of expression within the law, regardless of the damage done,
form part of the ark of the covenant and so are sacrosanct,'' the
newspaper said.
   Auberon Waugh, fuming over Rushdie's past criticisms of British
imperialism and racial prejudice, wrote in The Spectator magazine:
   ``Perhaps the real debate is not so much whether Rushdie should
be executed ... but just how much we should exert ourselves, as
deeply stained white imperialists, to protect him from his own
people.''
   ``I really do not think it unreasonable in the circumstance of
Rushdie's having made several million pounds through insulting
Islam, to suggest that he should pay for any police protection he
may judge advisable,'' said Waugh, a columnist for The Spectator and
The Sunday Telegraph.
   A letter to The Times from Jeremy Treglown, editor of The Times
Literary Supplement, argued that Rushdie's critics might want a
broader revision of the literary canon.
   ``Milton's pamphlets and Dryden's and Pope's satires, which
caused deep and violent feeling in those they attacked, should
obviously have been toned down. Many readers have been made
uncomfortable by the moral insights of Jane Austen and Dickens _
clear cases for sensitive editing,'' Treglown wrote.
   ``Wouldn't we be easier in our minds if there were no books at
all?''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
