<FIRST>u a BC-History 1stLd-Writethru b0233 03-06 0581</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-History, 1st Ld - Writethru, b0233,0598</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: In BC-History, sent in advance as b0233 for use today, CORRECTS
graf starting `In 1983, in a case,' four sted two convicted.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Today In History</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Today is Monday, March 6, the 65th day of 1989. There are 300
days left in the year.
   Today's Highlight in History:
   On March 6, 1836, the Alamo in San Antonio, Texas, fell to
Mexican forces after a 13-day siege. All 187 defenders of the
mission compound _ including Davy Crockett and James Bowie _ were
killed.
   On this date:
   In 1806, poet Elizabeth Barrett Browning was born in Durham,
England.
   In 1834, the city of York in Upper Canada was incorporated as
Toronto.
   In 1853, Verdi's opera ``La Traviata'' premiered in Venice, Italy.
   In 1857, in its ``Dred Scott'' decision, the U.S. Supreme Court
held that Scott, a slave, could not sue for his freedom in a federal
court.
   In 1933, a nationwide bank holiday declared by President Franklin
D. Roosevelt went into effect.
   In 1935, retired Supreme Court Justice Oliver Wendell Holmes Jr.
died in Washington.
   In 1944, U.S. bombers staged a daylight raid against Berlin
during World War II.
   In 1957, the former British African colonies of the Gold Coast
and Togoland became the independent state of Ghana.
   In 1967, the daughter of Josef Stalin, Svetlana Alliluyeva,
appeared at the U.S. Embassy in India and announced her intention to
defect to the West.
   In 1981, Walter Cronkite signed off for the last time as
anchorman of ``The CBS Evening News.''
   In 1982, author-philosopher Ayn Rand died in New York at age 77.
   In 1983, in a case that drew much notoriety, a woman in New
Bedford, Mass., said she had been gang-raped atop a pool table in a
tavern called Big Dan's. Four men were later convicted in connection
with the case.
   In 1983, the pro-environment, anti-nuclear ``Greens'' party won
seats in West Germany's lower house of parliament for the first time.
   In 1987, 189 people died when water rushed through the open bow
doors of the ``Herald of Free Enterprise,'' causing the British
ferry to capsize off the Belgian port of Zeebrugge.
   Ten years ago: A jury was empaneled in Oklahoma City in the case
of nuclear plant worker Karen G. Silkwood, who was contaminated with
plutonium through what Silkwood's family charged was the negligence
of her employer, Kerr-McGee Corp., shortly before her death in a
1974 car crash. Although the jury ruled against Kerr-McGee, an
appeals court in 1985 ordered a re-trial.
   Five years ago: Democratic presidential hopeful Gary Hart won
Vermont's preference vote by a wide margin over Walter F. Mondale,
following victories over Mondale in the New Hampshire primary and
Maine caucuses.
   One year ago: The board of trustees at Gallaudet University in
Washington D.C., the world's only liberal arts college for the deaf,
chose a hearing woman, Elisabeth Ann Zinser, school president over
two deaf candidates. Outraged students shut down the campus, forcing
Zinser's ouster and the selection of a deaf president in her place.
   Today's Birthdays: TV personality Ed McMahon is 66. Conductor
Sarah Caldwell is 65. CIA director William Webster is 65. The
chairman of the Federal Reserve, Alan Greenspan, is 63. The first
woman in space, Soviet cosmonaut Valentina Tereshkova, is 52. Actor
Ben Murphy is 47. Opera singer Dame Kiri Te Kanawa is 45.
Actor-director Rob Reiner is 42.
   Thought for Today: ``Caveat actor.'' Let the doer beware. _ Latin
proverb.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
