<FIRST>u i AM-Dante'sThreat 1stLd-Writethru a0772 03-06 0303</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dante's Threat, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0772,0305</SECOND>
<HEAD>Group Threatens Medieval Poet's Monument For Islam Slight</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf to CORRECT mayor's name</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RAVENNA, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group has threatened to blow up a
monument to Dante Alighieri because the medieval poet's famed
``Divine Comedy'' places the prophet Mohammed in hell, officials
said Sunday.
   Mayor Mauro Dragone said he ordered increased security around the
monument to the poet, who died in Ravenna in 1321, after receiving a
threatening letter from a group calling itself ``Guardians of the
Revolution.''
   ``It is an initiative taken in a prudent way because I am more
inclined to think that the letter, which also was sent to a local
newspaper, is a joke orchestrated in bad taste or a provocation,''
Dragone was quoted as saying by the Italian news agency ANSA.
   However, the mayor said he warned police and demanded stepped up
security because he believes the potential danger from such threats
should not be underestimated.
   He said the letter also demanded that he repudiate ``the false
poet Dante'' and declare publicly ``that Dante lied and that these
verses can no longer be read or studied.''
   The ``Divine Comedy'' is considered a literary masterpiece that
established the Tuscan dialect as the literary language of Italy.
The work, a poem of more than 14,000 lines in 100 cantos, recounts a
poet's journey through hell, purgatory and heaven. It places
Mohammed in the ninth pit of hell.
   It comes in the midst of the controversy over ``The Satanic
Verses'' by author Salman Rushdie, a native Indian now living in
Briton. Iranian clerics have offered a $5.2 million reward for
Rushdie's death because they say the book blasphemes Islam by
portraying Mohammed's wives as prostitutes and suggesting that
Mohammed, not God, was the source for the Koran, Islam's holy book.
</TEXT>
