<HEAD>Names in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY14</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sir Yehudi Menuhin, honored for
promoting German-Jewish reconciliation, made a plea for dialogue
between Israel and Palestinians.
   ``The chances for positive change are closer than we believe,''
the 72-year-old virtuoso violinist said Sunday during an address to
West Germany's Societies for Christian-Jewish Cooperation.
   Earlier, Menuhin was awarded the Buber-Rosenzweig medal for his
outspoken efforts to promote dialogue between Jews and Christians.
The award, established in 1968, commemorates the Jewish philosophers
Martin Buber and Franz Rosenzweig.
   The award cited his performances in Germany immediately after
World War II, including giving concerts for fellow Jews and others
who survived the Nazi Holocaust.
   Menuhin said he hoped talks between Arabs and Jews could produce
agreement on one state for both peoples.
   ``It may be the modest and lonely view of one man, but I believe
there are only two possibilities: either two independent states, and
that means a divided Jerusalem, or a united Jerusalem that would
mean at the very least a united, bi-national state.Israel must
follow this second path if it wants to survive.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>KEWANEE, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President and Barbara Bush top this year's
list of the nation's best mannered people, but their predecessors _
the Reagans _ have been left off it for the first time.
   The Bushes ``exemplify the new age of kinder and gentler manners
that will prevail in the 1990s,'' said Marjabelle Stewart, who
speaks and writes about etiquette.
   Mrs. Stewart said nominations for the fifth-annual best-mannered
list came from journalists, television crew members, make-up
artists, chauffeurs, maitre d's and others.
   This year's list includes Oakland Athletics pitcher Dennis
Eckersley, who demonstrates ``good sportsmanship on and off the
field and is a fine example to the youth of our nation,'' she said.
   Others were CBS newsman Charles Kuralt; Dr. Andrew Ross of
Children's Square USA in Council Bluffs, Iowa, who started an
etiquette program at the orphanage; NBC's ``Today'' show weatherman
Willard Scott; talk-show host Arsenio Hall, and Secretary of State
James Baker III.
   Former President Reagan and his wife, Nancy, dropped off the list
after topping it for the past four years.
   ``It's not that they are not beautifully mannered,'' said Mrs.
Stewart.
   She said they are no longer as highly visible as they were when
they were in the White House, adding, ``Isn't life fickle?''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Isabelle Adjani read from ``The Satanic Verses'' in
an acceptance speech at France's 14th annual Cesar film awards in a
gesture of support for novelist Salman Rushdie.
   Ms. Adjani received the best actress award Saturday night for
playing the title role in ``Camille Claudel,'' the sculptress and
lover of sculptor Auguste Rodin. It was her third best actress
Cesar, France's Oscar.
   ``You should know what I have suffered. ... In the artist's
condition there is something extreme,'' she read from the novel in
her speech. ``Angels are easy to calm. Human beings ... can doubt
everything.''
   Rushdie has been in hiding in Great Britain since Ayatollah
Khomeini called for his death for the novel, saying it blasphemes
Islam.
   There was little overt reaction from the audience to the
recitation.
   ``Camille Claudel'' received five Cesars, including best film,
photography, decor and costumes.
   Jean-Paul Belmondo, who said in advance he would refuse an award,
was named best actor for his role in ``Itineraire d'un Enfant Gate''
(Itinerary of a Spoiled Child). Belmondo, 55, has said the audience
reaction to his work was enough reward.
   The West German film ``Baghdad Cafe,'' directed by Percy Adlon,
was voted best foreign film.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Empress Dowager Nagako, widow of Emperor Hirohito,
celebrated her 86th birthday today with only a family luncheon
scheduled because of the mourning period for her husband, the Togu
Palace said.
   Those attending the luncheon were her eldest son, Emperor Akihito
and his wife, Empress Michiko; and the empress dowager's younger
son, Prince Hitachi and his wife, Princess Hanako, according to a
palace official who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   The imperial family is observing a year of mourning for Hirohito,
who died of cancer Jan. 7 at age 87, the official said.
   The official declined to discuss the health of the empress
dowager, who has used a wheelchair and has made few public
appearances in recent years. She did not attend her husband's
funeral last month.
   Quoting the Imperial Household Agency, Kyodo News Service said
the empress dowager is suffering from pains in the back and knees,
but her condition has remained stable and her appetite is good.
   Kyodo said she spends her days watching television and reading,
apart from observing prayers for her late husband twice a day.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Entertainers including Tammy Wynette, Pia
Zadora and Ray Charles helped stir up pledges of more than $37
million to the National Easter Seal Society during its 18th annual
telethon.
   ``We found that the American public was very supportive. We had
an even stronger turnout than we expected,'' said John Garrison,
head of the non-profit organization. This year's pledges exceeded
the goal of $36 million and last year's mark of $35 million, he said.
   The 20-hour telethon was broadcast live on local television
stations nationwide over the weekend. Singer Pat Boone was host for
the ninth year and was joined by his daughter Debbie in singing a
medley of their hits.
   The star of the show was 10-year-old Joy Hall, the National
Easter Seal child. Joy, who was born with cerebral palsy, has
already appeared on the ``Today'' show and will be a guest star on
the NBC series ``Amen'' later this year.
