<FIRST>r w PM-Congressmen-Shooting     03-06 0537</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Congressmen-Shooting,530</SECOND>
<HEAD>Once Pages Together, Congressmen Are Linked By Memory Of 1954 Shooting</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BARKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Once congressional pages together, Paul
Kanjorski and Bill Emerson both realized their dream of being
elected to the U.S. House.
   As if that were not unusual enough, both also were witnesses to
the rarest of events: an attack by gunmen on the Congress of the
United States.
   Kanjorski, D-Pa., and Emerson, R-Mo., stood together on the House
floor last Wednesday to mark the 35th anniversary of an event they
said will always seem fresh in their minds.
   The two were 16-year-old pages and roommates on March 1, 1954,
the day that four neatly dressed Puerto Ricans walked into the
public galleries, unfurled a flag, shouted ``Free Puerto Rico!'' and
began shooting randomly from large automatic pistols.
   House Speaker Joseph W. Martin Jr. _ who had been counting heads
in a quorum call on a bill dealing with migrant laborers _ banged
the gavel.
   A few congressmen fell, bleeding. Some raced for the doors. Some
hid under the tables.
   ``As one who has never been particularly age-conscious, I stand
in awe of the fact that this event occurred 35 years ago, and I
remember it as though it were yesterday,'' Emerson said last week.
   Kanjorski had just gotten out of his seat on the Democratic side
in the rear of the chamber when the shooting started.
   ``When the shots started to be fired, they sounded like
firecrackers going off,'' Kanjorski said last week. ``There were a
lot of them and they were different-sounding because there were
several weapons that were being used. The only thing that made it
clear they weren't firecrackers is that I got sprinkled with some of
the marble that flaked off.''
   Emerson thought the noise was firecrackers, too, ``but when I
looked up, I could see fire coming out of the end of the barrels of
those guns.''
   Wounded were Reps. Alvin Bentley, R-Mich.; Ben Jensen, R-Iowa;
George Fallon, D-Md.; Kenneth Roberts, D-Ala.; and Clifford Davis,
D-Tenn. All recovered.
   Before it was over, a photographer snapped a picture of Kanjorski
and Emerson carrying one of them off on a stretcher.
   As bad as the moment was, the news photo gave Kanjorski and
Emerson temporary celebrity status among their peers, and linked
them together in time.
   ``All through our lives we have been very close friends,''
Kanjorski said. He classified the odds of both becoming congressmen
as ``remote,'' even though he said both dreamed about the
possibility.
   One of the attackers died in 1979, and the other three were given
presidential clemency the same year after 25 years in prison.
   Emerson was elected to Congress in 1980, Kanjorski four years
later.
   ``I might say it was a great pleasure for me personally when my
friend Paul Kanjorski joined us here two terms ago,'' Emerson said.
``He and I were roommates and colleagues of that era, and it was
great to see an old buddy come back to Congress.
   ``I have often thought it (the shooting) was a terrible thing to
have happened, but since it did, I was glad I was here to observe
that little anecdote in American history,'' Emerson said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890306-0019 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-06-89 0301EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-BushandTower     03-06 0796</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush and Tower,780</SECOND>
<HEAD>Even Republicans Say Tower Nomination Handled Poorly</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERENCE HUNT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP White House Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The White House struggle to save John Tower's
nomination has turned into the first major test of President Bush's
political mettle and is being watched as a barometer of how he'll
deal with a Congress dominated by Democrats.
   Republican strategists say the stakes are high for Bush, in
office only six weeks.
   ``He's got to fight. To let the Democrats shove him around or to
knuckle under to them this early in his presidency would only give
them more feeling that they could go after him down the road,'' said
Lyn Nofziger, who was the first political director for President
Ronald Reagan.
   Mitchell Daniels, another White House political director under
Reagan, said Bush should make clear that there will be political
consequences for anyone who opposes the administration.
   ``If he just sort of smiles and forgets it, I think it's the same
as putting up a `kick me' sign,'' Daniels said.
   ``He's got to put this in the memory bank and, as he has
opportunities out of public view, he's got to get even'' as he makes
decisions and doles out political favors over the next four years,
said Daniels.
   While the White House still talked about victory, Nofziger and
Daniels said there was virtually no chance Tower could win
confirmation as secretary of defense, with the Democrats holding a
55-45 majority in the Senate.
   Even among Republicans, there is a feeling that the White House
has not done a good job with the Tower nomination. The former Texas
senator has been buffeted by accusations of excessive drinking,
womanizing and conflict of interest with defense contractors.
   ``Up until now, the Brits have had better scandals,'' said Rep.
Lynn Martin, an Illinois Republican. ``This one is understandable _
drinking and sex.''
   The White House has not tried to pressure Congress by drumming up
a groundswell of public support for Tower.
   ``The public's uncomfortable with the rumors,'' Daniels said.
``There's no pro-drunkenness caucus out there.''
   In a speech last week, Bush observed, ``This is a tough town _ a
lot of rumors out there.'' He has spoken out on Tower's behalf
numerous times, discounting the allegations against his nominee as
mere innuendo.
   A White House official said Bush is not trying to mobilize a
national campaign on Tower's behalf because it is not the kind of
issue that can generate much public support. Instead, he said, Bush
is struggling to find a few votes in the Senate.
   ``This is a battle with an audience of about eight people,'' said
the official, who declined to be identified by name.
   ``I don't see any point in making this personal,'' Bush said
recently. ``There's no point making this into a fight.''
   Looking ahead to relations with Congress after the Tower affair,
Bush said, ``We're going to have to work together on a lot of other
issues.''
   Andrew Card, a top lieutenant to Bush, said the president
``understands politics and he knows that most people don't hold
grudges and can move from one issue to the next without a lot of
bias.''
   By the traditional rules of politics, Tower's nomination should
have been safe. As a former senator, he was a member of the
congressional club, the beneficiary of special courtesies and favors.
   However, the normal scenario turned into chaos for Tower when
Paul Weyrich, a conservative activist, testified publicly about
Tower's drinking.
   ``What Paul Weyrich did was to present an uneasy group of
senators who really didn't like John Tower anyway with a fig leaf,''
said Stephen Hess, a Brookings Institution specialist on the
presidency.
   ``George Bush makes ethics and personal conduct almost a hallmark
of his administration and gets hoisted on his own petard,'' Hess
said.
   The White House has acknowledged shortcomings in handling Tower's
nomination, blaming some of the problems on incompetence and
inexperience among the new staff.
   Nofziger traces the mishandling back to December, even before
Tower was actually nominated.
   ``They let the naming of him dangle for two months. Secondly,
after they named him they didn't do anything. They just let it sit
there,'' Nofziger said.
   ``When the negative stuff came out they didn't seem to put
together a campaign to support him,'' Nofziger added. ``The only
support that I see is coming out of the White House and Republican
senators.
   ``Just as this thing is beginning to heat up,'' he added,
``George Bush goes off to the Far East and takes with him his chief
of staff and half his staff, leaving nobody to stay behind and fight
the good fight.''
   It was on Bush's first full day in Tokyo that the Senate Armed
Services Committee voted along party lines 11-9 against Tower's
nomination.
</TEXT>
