<FIRST>r i PM-BRF--Kadar     03-06 0177</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Kadar,0181</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Hungarian Party Chief Stays Away From Central Committee Session</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Janos Kadar, who headed the ruling
Communist Party for 32 years until his ouster last year, will not
attend Tuesday's meeting of the party's governing Central Committee,
a newspaper reported.
   Vasarnapi Hirek (Sunday News) quoted party spokesman Laszlo Major
as saying Kadar would not attend because he has not fully recovered
from hand surgery _ but there is speculation he may be staying away
for other than health reasons.
   The 76-year-old Kadar, who now holds the newly created post of
party president, also missed the committee's last meeting.
   In the last years of Kadar's rule, Hungary's economy fell into
decline and independent groups agitating for multiparty democracy
began to gain wide influence.
   Reformers who advocate allowing opposition candidates to compete
in elections have now obtained a foothold in the heights of the
Communist Party.
   The reformers include politicians thrown out of the leadership
when Kadar was installed as party chief in 1956, the year Soviet
tanks quashed the Hungarian uprising.
</TEXT>
