<FILEID>AP-NR-03-06-89 0204EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Japan-Markets 2ndLd-Writethru a0816 03-06 0287</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0816,0291</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Falls, Stocks Lose Ground</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with three grafs to UPDATE with dollar and Nikkei closings.
PIcks up 4th pvs, `Dealers said ...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar fell against the Japanese yen, while
share prices also lost ground on the Tokyo Stock Exchange at the end
of the trading day Monday.
   The dollar opened at 127.55 yen and moved higher to peak at
127.68 yen before closing the day slightly lower at 127.63 yen. It
was down 0.49 yen from last Friday's 128.12-yen finish.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225
selected issues, a 73.63-point loser last week, also shed 123.24
points, or 0.38 percent, for 31,876.86 points by the end of the
trading day.
   Dealers said trading was directionless in the absence of major
market-affecting news, but concern over possible Japanese discount
rates hikes was sending the dollar and Nikkei lower
   ``There is talk of rate hikes here and market participants are
taking a wait-and-see attitude,'' said a dealer at a major Japanese
securities firm. ``Otherwise, trading is directionless.''
   He added that the currency fluctuated in wide ranges last week
because of technical adjustments and economic news, including a West
German decision not to raise its interest rates.
   ``This week, people are waiting for a conference Wednesday by
Bank of Japan Gov. Satoshi Sumita and the release of U.S.
unemployment figures due out Friday,'' the dealer said, speaking on
condition of anonymity.
   In stock trading, the Nikkei fell as investors moved to the
sidelines ahead of the settlement of March futures contracts
scheduled for Tuesday, dealers said.
   They said brokerage firms, including Nomura and Daiwa Securities,
were among the losers in the early trading.
</TEXT>
