<FILEID>AP-NR-03-06-89 0430EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-SnakebiteRescue     03-06 0432</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Snakebite Rescue,0446</SECOND>
<HEAD>Snake Expert Won't Receive Overseas Antivenins Unless Condition Worsens</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT MIMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A reseacher bitten by a deadly viper has
stabilized and won't receive antivenins obtained from Iran, England
and the Soviet Union with help from the White House unless his
condition worsens, doctors say.
   William E. Haast, 78, remained in serious but stable condition
today at the University of Utah Health Sciences Center. Spokesman
John Dwan said Sunday Haast had been moved out of intensive care
into a regular nursing unit.
   ``His condition has not changed,'' Dwan said. ``He's resting
comfortably, and he's had lots of friends visiting him.''
   Haast likely would remain hospitalized for at least two to three
more weeks, Dwan said. He checked into the hospital Wednesday.
   Haast, director of the Miami Serpentarium Laboratories at the
university's Research Park, was bitten Tuesday on the left hand by a
Pakistani pit viper, also known as a saw-scaled viper.
   Haast has been bitten 148 times by snakes and is immune to the
venom of dozens, but he had no immunity to the viper. It is one of
1,000 poisonous snakes kept at his lab, where venom is extracted for
research and the manufacture of antivenins.
   The serpentologist's case drew the attention of Stephen Studdert,
special assistant to President Bush, who coordinated the acquisition
of antivenins from the three countries and expedited their shipment
to Utah. All the shipments had arrived by Sunday.
   ``None have been used, because there are sometimes serious
reactions to antivenins and (doctors) don't want to give them to him
unless they have to,'' Dwan explained. The reactions could include
lung and kidney problems, he said.
   Nevertheless, Dwan said ``we want to express our appreciation to
everyone who has worked so hard in obtaining the antivenins.''
   The viper's venom attacks its victim's ability to produce
fibrinogen, an element of blood that regulates coagulation. A lack
of fibrinogen can cause uncontrolled bleeding.
   Haast's fibrinogen level was near zero Wednesday. Doctors were
replacing it with transfusions and it appeared Haast's body had
begun to produce the substance.
   His fibrinogen level improved to about one-third of normal by
Sunday, still ``dangerously low,'' Dwan said.
   Haast had been treated earlier with antivenins from the San Diego
Zoo and from a lab in Los Angeles, but they did not work as well as
expected.
   Studdert said the Iranian government apparently did not interfere
with the shipment of the antivenin despite the strained relations
with the United States. Iranian leader Ayatollah Khomeini has often
called the United States the ``great Satan.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890306-0031 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-06-89 0439EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-SovietPentecostals     03-06 0514</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet Pentecostals,0529</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pentecostals Reportedly Allowed To Leave Soviet Union As Jews</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of Soviet Pentecostals are leaving
their country for the United States under the guise of being Jewish
emigres, a newspaper reported.
   The emigration of Pentecostals, who claim to suffer
discrimination in their homeland, apparently has the blessing of
government officials in several countries who are assisting their
passage, The Buffalo News reported Sunday.
   ``We're not sure of the reason why the Soviets have allowed the
Pentecostals to leave,'' said Serge Duss, a refugee specialist with
the World Relief agency in Rome.
   ``The Soviets have turned a blind eye, the Israelis have turned a
blind eye, but the important thing is they are getting out of the
country.''
   ``It's not a secret,'' said the Rev. Alexander Shevchuk of New
York City, himself a Soviet emigre.
   Refugee workers say Pentecostals renounce their Soviet
citizenship in Moscow, obtain visas from the Dutch or American
embassy and come to refugee camps in Italy.
   A spokesman at the Dutch embassy in Moscow who spoke on condition
he remain anonymous denied to The Associated Press his country was
issuing visas identifying Pentecostals as Jews. Officials at the
U.S. embassy didn't comment immediately.
   The State Department's annual review of human rights last month
found signs of significant reform in Soviet policies during the past
year, including increased emigration for Pentecostals as well as
Jews, Armenians and ethnic Germans.
   Shevchuk has traveled throughout the United States raising funds
to support Pentecostals in Italian refugee camps. He led a
contingent of American Pentecostals to Italy in late Feburary to
arrange sponsors for the refugees.
   One of the pastors accompanying him, Rev. Paul Schenck of New
Covenent Tabernacle Church in the Buffalo suburb of Tonawanda, said
he hopes to sponsor 100 refugees.
   ``We want to literally sponsor a colony,'' Schenck said. ``We
want to do for the Russian Pentecostals what Brighton Beach did for
the Russian Jews,'' he said, referring to the New York City
neighborhood where many Jewish emigres have settled.
   Up to 300 other Pentecostals will be placed in other churches in
upstate New York. About 120 Pentecostals are already living near
Rochester, he said.
   Refugee workers say more than 2,000 Pentecostals left the Soviet
Union last year and up to 10,000 may emigrate this year.
   Soviet Pentecostals, who number about 700,000, believe in
everyday manifestations of the Holy Spirit, speak in tongues and
practice faith healing. They claim to have been forced into the
Soviet countryside and denied good schooling and jobs.
   ``When we were singing Christmas carols, they caught us and put
us in jail,'' said Peter Malischuk, 27, an artist staying in the
Italian town Olevano Romano with his wife and two children.
``Everyone was fined and laid off from work.''
   Victor Povorzynk, 40, a furniture maker staying with his wife and
three children in the village of Ladispoli, said he was drafted into
the military and refused to take the military oath.
   ``They put me in a psychiatric hospital and then sentenced me to
four years in jail,'' Povorzynk said.
</TEXT>
