<FIRST>r a PM-AryanWoodstock     03-06 0353</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Aryan Woodstock,0364</SECOND>
<HEAD>Racist Gathering Was a Bore</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NAPA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A concert billed as an ``Aryan Woodstock''
for skinheads and white supremacists turned out to be ``boring and
uncomfortable'' because of rain, a lack of food and a court-ordered
ban on music.
   About 100 people representing half a dozen white supremacist
groups gathered Saturday at a private ranch about 40 miles north of
San Francisco, but were far outnumbered by about 400 protesters and
500 police officers.
   ``They talked about girls. They gropingly discussed `white
power.' They pranced about with Nazi flags and insignia, but they
never discussed the ideology of fascism or of anything else,'' wrote
Cherie Seymour, a former reporter who gained entrance to the event.
   Seymour, who did not specify how she managed to attend the rally
in the heart of California's wine country, described the event in an
article in today's editions of the San Francisco Chronicle.
   ``It was simply boring _ and uncomfortable,'' she said. ``The
great majority had brought neither rain gear nor food. Morale hit
bottom when police refused to let the daughter of white supremacist
Tom Metzger return with $100 worth of pizzas.''
   The event originally was touted as something to bring together
thousands of white supremacist youths. The skinhead bands Midtown
Boot Boys from Oklahoma, the Hammerheads from Wisconsin annd
Kakenkreuz from Detroit were expected to perform.
   But Napa County Superior Judge W. Scott Snowden ruled Friday that
rally organizers couldn't have music without a permit.
   So participants spent most of the day glaring at reporters and
protesters from a hill.
   The gathering was held out of view of the public, which was not
allowed entrance to the ranch. There were a few clashes between
white supremacists and protesters but no arrests or major violence.
   ``What you find is that the people of Napa rallied against this
group that has no purpose other than hate. I was real proud of the
way people stood up,'' said Mayor Ed Solomon.
   Early Sunday, the last five white supremacists left the property.
   Sheriff Gary Simpson estimated the cost of law enforcement at
about $400,000.
</TEXT>
