<FIRST>r a PM-Klan-Mississippi     03-06 0329</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Klan-Mississippi,0341</SECOND>
<HEAD>Klan Holds Recruitment Rally in City of ``Mississippi Burning''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT NAYLOR JR.</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sixteen Ku Klux Klan members marched
for ``white power'' and a Klan leader criticized the movie
``Mississippi Burning,'' about the slayings of three civil rights
workers here in the 1960s.
   About 100 spectators watched the march and recruitment rally with
a few people heckling the marchers. About 20 law enforcement
officers also kept watch.
   No incidents were reported in the march or during another march
by about 20 Klan members later Sunday in Meridian, about 40 miles to
the east.
   Jordan Gollub, the Grand Dragon for Mississippi, said the march
was held in Philadelphia because of the movie, which he said
presented a ``negative, hateful image of the Klan.
   ``Hollywood is run by Jews and integrationists,'' said Gollub, a
Jew by birth.
   The movie, which has received seven Oscar nominations, is loosely
based on the 1964 slayings of three civil rights workers whose
bodies were found in an earthen dam near Philadelphia, a town of
about 7,500 in central Mississippi.
   James Earl Chaney, 21, who was black, and Andrew Goodman, 20, and
Michael Schwerner, 24, who were white, were shot to death. The
federal government eventually convicted eight people of violating
the civil rights of the three men, but no one was ever charged with
murder.
   The Klan marchers included 10 men and six women, with 10 wearing
purple, green, gold and white robes.
   Police cars preceded and followed the marchers through
Philadelphia's small downtown area and six patrolmen walked with the
group.
   Philadelphia Police Chief Arden Gentry said his entire 16-member
police force was on duty along with Neshoba County Sheriff Glen
Waddell, one deputy and two county constables. At least one FBI
agent from Meridian also was present.
   ``We knew we were probably one of the best known cities for our
size in the country, and we didn't know what to expect,'' Gentry
said.
</TEXT>
