<FIRST>r a PM-Circumcision     03-06 0483</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Circumcision,0500</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pediatrics Group Alters Stand on Circumcision</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: A 6 a.m. EST embargo has been broken, this story is for immediate
use</HEAD>
<HEAD>padhofilfonsbc</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL DRISCOLL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The American Academy of Pediatrics today for the
first time noted evidence of medical benefits of circumcisions for
newborns, but the 37,000-member organization stopped short of an
all-out endorsement.
   The academy said the decision is best made by parents in
consultation with their physicians.
   ``In addition to the medical aspects, other factors will affect
the parents' decisions, including esthetics, religion, cultural
attitudes, social pressures and tradition,'' the group said in a
statement.
   Circumcision, removal of a band of skin encircling the tip of the
penis, is the nation's most commonly performed surgical procedure,
but it appears to be on the decline.
   The practice is a controversial issue worldwide. The first
International Symposium on Circumcision was held last week in
Anaheim, Calif., sponsored by the National Organization of
Circumcision Information Resource Centers and the Institute for the
Advancement of Human Behavior.
   The symposium concluded that the medical need for circumcision is
very rare and that ordinarily it should not be done, said Billy
Boyd, a participant and co-founder of The Victims Speak, a group
working against circumcision.
   ``Parents do not have the right to consent to unnecessary medical
procedures on their children,'' and physicians have an obligation to
refuse to remove normal body parts, the symposium said in a policy
statement presented to the California Medical Association.
   The right to an intact body supercedes religious or cultural
practices that include circumcision, said Donna Macris, vice
president of the board of directors of the Circumcision Information
Resource Centers.
   Since 1971, when the pediatrics academy first took a stand on the
issue, it had maintained that no absolute medical necessity existed
for routine circumcision of newborns.
   But in its statement today, it said the procedure ``has potential
medical benefits and advantages.''
   It recommended that physicians explain and discuss the benefits
and risks of circumcision with parents.
   Informed consent should be obtained before the procedure is done,
said the academy, based in suburban Elk Grove Village.
   The group said it was influenced partly by studies at Army
hospitals in 1985 that concluded that among the 200,000 males
studied, there was an 11-fold increase in urinary tract infections
in uncircumcised as compared with circumcised infants.
   However, the academy said all-out endorsement was not merited, in
part because the study may have been flawed, thus ``conclusions
regarding the relationship of urinary tract infection to
circumcision are tentative.''
   The academy also addressed the issue of pain caused by
circumcision.
   It said infants undergoing circumcision without anesthesia appear
to experience pain.
   But, the academy said, ``reported experience with local
anesthesia in newborn circumcision is limited, and the procedure
(anesthesia) is not without risk.''
   More studies are needed before routine local anesthesia can be
endorsed, the group said.
</TEXT>
