<FIRST>r a PM-Eastern-Travelers     03-06 0649</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Eastern-Travelers,0674</SECOND>
<HEAD>Whether Honeymooning Or Divorcing, Eastern Debacle Leaves Sour Taste</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Eastern, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Note language in 7th graf, ``I picked ...''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILL LESTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Travelers snared in the Eastern Airlines strike winced at the
sour taste of labor wars _ no matter if it was a honeymooning couple
trapped at New York's LaGuardia Airport or an unhappy mother leaving
her marriage behind.
   Eastern Airlines severely underestimated the impact of organized
labor's effort to bring business to a halt and thousands of
travelers paid the price, acknowledged Eastern President Phil Bakes,
whose apologies were little consolation on those caught in the labor
unrest.
   Carlos and Ileana Rodriguez of Fairlawn, N.J., got married
Saturday night and had planned to take a Sunday morning flight to
Puerto Rico.
   They spent the first day of their honeymoon in the LaGuardia
terminal because there were no pilots to fly the plane.
   ``This is ridiculous,'' said an angry Rodriguez. ``I'm very
disappointed and disgusted with the whole ordeal.''
   Amid the chaos of Miami International Airport, Alana Riley sat
disconsolately on the carpet as her 3-year-old son, David, played
nearby. She said she was in the process of moving from Jamaica to
New Orleans.
   ``I picked a hell of a time to move,'' she said. ``I'm divorcing
on top of it all. It's just real hectic to be traveling with a
3-year-old.''
   The frustration and confusion was replayed at airports around the
country on the second day of the Machinists union strike, supported
by nearly 95 percent of pilots.
   A few kept their sense of humor.
   Salomeja Valukas, of New Haven, Conn., was trying to depart
LaGuardia for Miami, and came to the airport despite warnings it
would be bad.
   ``What can I do?'' she wondered. ``There are worse things in
life. I went through the war in Europe.''
   Lou Garber, vice president of Garber Travel in Brookline, Mass.,
said his agency had rerouted hundreds in recent days.
   ``It's becoming increasingly difficult to find alternative
routings, but we've been working on it for days and are
accomplishing the task,'' he said.
   Most airlines offered varying degrees of help, except for TWA,
said Eastern spokesman Jim Ashlock.
   ``TWA is not helping at all; American takes passengers on
standby; Pan American takes passengers on standby; United has been
helping depending on availability of space, either booking them on
or placing them on standby; Delta ... USAir and Piedmont have the
same policy,'' he said.
   Eastern targeted some of its high-profile routes, but was unable
to muster the pilots to fly many planes. Continental planes made
special trips to Puerto Rico to pick up stranded cruise tourists.
   ``We are placing the emphasis on protecting the cruise
passengers, the Caribbean routes and the Northeast Shuttle,'' said
Eastern spokesman Robin Matell.
   He admitted the airline was not finding lodging for all those
left behind.
   ``We've been able to put many in hotels, but this is Grand Prix
weekend and the hotels are totally booked,'' said Matell in Miami.
   Other events this weekend during a peak of South Florida tourist
activity were the Honda Classic PGA event in neighboring Broward
County, the Florida Derby and baseball spring training.
   At Miami International Airport, the strike advanced the confusion
to a new dimension, with anxious travelers peppering harried Eastern
employees in Spanish, French, English and Haitian Creole.
   ``Nobody knows nothing,'' complained 33-year-old Charlie Rink of
Philadelphia. ``There's nobody walking around, talking to people to
explain things. They need a trouble shooter.''
   Bakes apologized at a news conference Sunday.
   ``We want to apologize for the inconvenience you've
experienced,'' he said. ``It's been a mess.''
   Nobody had to tell Alana Riley, plopped on the floor at Miami
International, her efforts to move far away from Jamaica quite
stymied.
   ``I feel for the employees at Eastern,'' she said. ``But I've not
cared for Eastern Airlines' service for the last two years.''
</TEXT>
