<FIRST>r i PM-Afghanistan     03-06 0284</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Afghanistan,0295</SECOND>
<HEAD>Radio Says Emergency Convoy Attacked By Insurgents</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY GANNON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Afghan guerrillas attacked a
Kabul-bound emergency convoy and set fire to 15 vehicles, but the
rest of the trucks arrived safely in the Afghan capital over the
weekend, Radio Kabul said.
   The more than 550 trucks with 6,000 tons of food and fuel from
the Soviet Union were hit as they traveled south on the strategic
Salang Highway from Hairatan, a village on the Soviet border, the
state-run radio Sunday.
   The broadcast, monitored in Islamabad, said 13 tank trucks and
two trucks carrying wheat were set on fire by attacking rebels.
   ``The opposition continued to launch attacks on convoys of food
and fuel, snatching the bread from the table of our innocent
people,'' Radio Kabul said.
   ``Heavy losses and casualties were inflicted on the criminals,''
the radio broadcast said without elaborating.
   A spokesman for the rebel force Jamiat-i-Islami, which claims
control of much of the area on either side of the Salang Highway,
said today that he knew nothing of the weekend convoy.
   However, the spokesman said his group's policy is to allow
emergency food, but not military hardware, to pass.
   The Soviet Union withdrew the last of its forces Feb. 15 after
nine years of military intervention. More than 100,000 Soviet
soldiers were sent into the central Asian state to prop up the
Marxist government.
   Western analysts and guerrilla leaders headquartered in Pakistan
say Afghan President Najib's government will soon fall to the rebels.
   In weekend fighting around the country, Radio Kabul said 68
rebels were killed by government troops and scores injured and
captured. It gave no casualty toll for government forces.
</TEXT>
