<DOCNO> AP890306-0042 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-06-89 0852EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-India-Sikhs     03-06 0310</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-India-Sikhs,0322</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Orders Release of 188 Sikhs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge today ordered the release of 188
Sikhs jailed in a northern city since a 1984 army raid on the
holiest Sikh shrine during which 1,200 people were killed, a senior
government official said.
   Among those to be freed is Gurcharan Singh Tohra, head of the
Sikh temple management committee. The body, which controls most Sikh
shrines and temple funds, is considered the most powerful Sikh
organization.
   The prisoners' release is part of a package announced last week
by Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi to try to end ethnic violence that
has wracked the northwestern state of Punjab for seven years.
   Militants are fighting for an independent homeland.
   In June 1984, then Prime Minister Indira Gandhi ordered the army
to raid the Golden Temple in Amritsar to rout Sikh militants inside.
   Four months later, she was assassinated by two Sikh bodyguards in
retaliation for the raid.
   Most of those killed in the raise were Sikhs and authorities
arrested about 300 people, many of them pilgrims held for
questioning but never charged.
   Jodhpur District Judge Khemchandra Sharma, acting on a request by
prosecutors, today ordered the release of 188 of the prisoners
jailed in Jodhpur, said a Home Ministry official, who spoke on
condition of anonymity. The prisoners will be taken back to Amritsar
on Tuesday, the official said. Jodhpur is in Rajasthan state,
southwest of Punjab.
   Authorities had already released 118 prisoners, the official said.
   At least 2,400 people were killed by Sikh militants last year,
more than double the number in 1987. More than 340 people have died
this year.
   Sikhs make up 2 percent of India's population, but they are a
slight majority in the northern Punjab state. Militants claim Sikhs
are discriminated against by Hindus, who comprises 82 percent of the
national population.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
