<DOCNO> AP890306-0043 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-06-89 0720EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Venezuela     03-06 0527</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Venezuela,0551</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gov't Orders Schools To Reopen, Sporadic Gunfire Reported</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT GLASS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government declared it has regained
control after the country's bloodiest riots in decades and ordered
elementary schools to reopen today. It also gave a new, lower death
toll.
   A nighttime curfew remained in effect in the capital and the
country was still under martial law, which allows soldiers to search
houses without warrants and detain suspects indefinitely without
charge.
   Isolated gunfire was heard in the capital early Sunday, but there
have been no significant disturbances since Friday.
   The rioting, which began Feb. 27, was sparked by increases in bus
fares and other price increases mandated under an austerity plan
demanded by foreign creditors.
   In a nationwide television broadcast, an aide to President Carlos
Andres Perez revised downward the government's tally of the number
of dead and wounded from the rioting, which began Feb. 27.
   He said 246 people were killed _ down from Perez's previous
estimate of at least 300. Figueredo said 1,800 people were injured,
compared to earlier reports of at least 2,000.
   No explanation was given for the new figures, which were much
lower than newspaper reports putting the death toll as high as 600
and the number of wounded at several thousand.
   Two Caracas hospitals alone reported treating 2,300.
   Figueredo said during Saturday night's broadcast that the
government was starting to reopen schools because unrest has ``been
controlled and the situation ... has returned to complete
normality.''
   He said classes would resume today for kindergarten through sixth
grade and begin later in the week for older students.
   It was unclear when universities would reopen. Universities have
traditionally been centers of protest of government economic
policies.
   The riots and looting broke out after sharp rises in bus fares,
gasoline and other basic consumer goods and services.
   With its oil-based economy, Venezuela enjoyed prosperity during
the 1970s but saw its fortunes sharply decline with the price of oil
in 1981.
   The country's $33 billion foreign debt makes it Latin America's
fourth-largest debtor nation behind Brazil, Mexico and Argentina.
   People filed into the Caracas central morgue Sunday trying to
find missing relatives.
   Azucena Correa, spokeswoman for a newly formed Committee for the
Missing, said her group had a list of hundreds of people who could
not be located. She said many were assumed to be in military
custody, and she accused authorities of holding back information.
   ``We've gone to the interior minister, we've gone to the police,
but so far nothing,'' she said.
   ``We even have the names of children, some under the age of 7,
who haven't been seen in their homes since the violence began,'' Ms.
Correa added.
   The auxiliary Roman Catholic bishop of Caracas, Monsignor Jorge
Sabino Uroza said Sunday that the riots were a product of poverty
and frustration, and said powerful business interests and government
leaders shared the blame.
   Celebrating Mass at Caracas' Central Cathedral, Uroza said
``there are those that sacked stores, and they should seek pardon;
but there are also those, especially economic and political sectors,
that have sacked the country for years. They should also seek
pardon.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890306-0044 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-06-89 0715EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r p PM-AlaCongressional     03-06 0638</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Ala Congressional,0655</SECOND>
<HEAD>Black Seeks Historic Victory In Mostly White Deep South District</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KENDAL WEAVER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTGOMERY, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tuskegee Mayor Johnny Ford enters
Tuesday's Democratic primary runoff with a historic bid: to become
the state's first black congressman this century, and in a district
that is three-fourths white.
   Ford is considered the underdog in seeking to become the 25th
black in the 435-member U.S. House and the first from a Deep South
district where whites are in the vast majority.
   ``The members are watching it very closely,'' said Amelia Parker,
executive director of the Congressional Black Caucus in Washington,
D.C. A Ford victory, she said, ``would be an extraordinary message
at this point in the history of our country.''
   Despite the symbolism, Ford and his opponent, Secretary of State
Glen Browder, have sought to keep race out of the campaign for the
3rd Congressional District seat in mostly rural east Alabama.
   The runoff winner will face state Sen. John Rice of Opelika, who
was a Democrat until he switched to Republican ranks last year.
   Ford, 46, worked for Robert Kennedy's ill-fated 1968 presidential
campaign, but he later formed political ties to then-President Nixon
and former Gov. George Wallace, supporting Wallace in his 1974
gubernatorial bid. Ford has enlisted the aid of Jesse Jackson in
seeking a strong black voter turnout, but has said repeatedly that
race is not an issue.
   ``I am very confident we will win support from people of both
races who are interested in the best qualified candidate regardless
of the color of the candidate's skin,'' he said.
   Browder, also 46, a former professor who narrowly led Ford in a
splintered Democratic field Feb. 14, is considered the frontrunner.
He has the support of organized labor and has gained recognition for
advocating campaign finance reform. He has not targeted Ford or made
race a factor in the three-week campaign.
   ``Both candidates realize that going into such a short time-frame
there is no advantage in going after your opponent,'' said Browder's
campaign manager, Dave Cooley. ``Race is certainly not an issue in
our campaign.''
   ``Race is not as much an issue as it has been in the past,'' said
state Sen. Jim Preuitt of Talladega, a conservative who ran a close
third in the primary and has since blasted Browder as a liberal who
``sold his soul to big labor bosses.''
   ``He doesn't want to be known as just a black candidate,'' said
Robert Anderson, a white high school principal from Notasulga who is
co-chairman of Ford's campaign. ``But he understood that just to
make the runoff was historic.''
   The last time a black reached a Democratic runoff for a
congressional seat in the state was in 1978, but Chris McNair lost
to Richard Shelby in west Alabama's 7th District. Shelby now sits in
the U.S. Senate.
   In the House, Reps. Ron Dellums, D-Calif., and Alan Wheat, D-Mo.,
are the only blacks to represent districts with majority white
populations on the scale of Alabama's 3rd District. In the Deep
South, Rep. Mike Espy won a Mississippi district that was about
evenly split racially in 1986 and won re-election easily last year
with strong white support.
   Robert Bush, Espy's administrative assistant, said Ford entered
the race with ``a proven track record with white politicians that
Mike Espy didn't have.''
   Ford has been mayor of Tuskegee since 1972 and helped found state
and national conferences of black mayors as well as a multi-racial
organization called the World Conference of Mayors.
   The 3rd District seat was vacated by the death in December of
Rep. Bill Nichols. He had kept the seat Democratic for 22 years with
generally conservative, defense-oriented politics.
   Rice, 37, is expected to get support from white conservative
voters who backed Nichols, but he is a relative newcomer in state
politics.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
