<FIRST>r a PM-IllegalAliens     03-06 0262</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Illegal Aliens,0269</SECOND>
<HEAD>Authorities Arrest 52 Undocumented Aliens</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fifty-two illegal immigrants, many of them
holding plane tickets, were arrested at a suspected ``drop house''
where they apparently were waiting out a crackdown on immigrant
smuggling, authorities said.
   The action Sunday night brought the number of undocumented aliens
arrested over the weekend to 89. The Immigration and Naturalization
Service has been concentrating its efforts for the past week on
stopping the use of commercial airlines for smuggling illegal aliens
to destinations nationwide.
   Officers discovered the immigrants after receiving an anonymous
tip from a caller who alleged a diabetic woman was being kept at the
house against her will, Lt. Roger Fox said.
   The report turned out to be false, but police discovered the
group of adult aliens, mostly from Brazil, and notified the INS, Fox
said.
   The aliens were holding airline tickets for destinations
including Chicago, New York and St. Louis, Fox said.
   The aliens were taken to INS detention facilities downtown, Fox
said.
   Authorities estimated there are between 30 and 40 ``drop houses''
where paid smugglers keep illegal aliens in the Los Angeles area
before sending them on to residences elsewhere.
   ``We're looking for all the drop houses in Los Angeles, so we can
put the local end of the operation out of business,'' said John
Brechtel, assistant INS director for investigations.
   Twenty-six aliens were arrested at Los Angeles International
Airport and 11 were arrested at Ontario International Airport 30
miles east of here in sweeps staged late Saturday and early Sunday,
according to an INS official.
</TEXT>
