<DOCNO> AP890306-0052 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-06-89 0900EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-MysteryInformant     03-06 0649</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Mystery Informant,0668</SECOND>
<HEAD>Murder Charge Dropped Because Police Can't Produce Informant</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN COOPERMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The man that detectives most want to bring to trial
for allegedly killing one of their colleagues is free because police
played fast and loose in getting a search warrant for a drug raid,
prosecutors say.
   Three detectives have been suspended while perjury charges are
considered.
   The case has focused attention on how easy, and tempting, it is
for police officers to obtain search warrants by citing fictitious
informants.
   Defense lawyers contend the practice, though illegal, is routine
in Boston and many other cities across the nation. But prosecutors
and police say if the use of confidential informants is curbed, they
will lose a key weapon in the war against drugs.
   Judge Jack B. Weinstein, who has spent 22 years on the U.S.
District Court bench in New York City, said judges have little
choice but to trust police when they say they have an informant.
   ``Assuming that they were trying to trick me, how would I know
it?'' Weinstein said. ``The informant isn't subject to cross
examination, I don't even see the informant. I have to rely on the
U.S. attorney and the law enforcement agencies. If they wanted to
deceive me, it would be easy to do so.''
   In the Boston case, a Superior Court judge dismissed all charges
against Albert Lewin two weeks ago after police failed to produce a
mysterious informant _ identified only as John _ who supposedly
tipped them off to a cocaine dealer in the city's Dorchester section.
   On Feb. 17, 1988, as four detectives prepared to break into the
dealer's apartment, two shots were fired from inside the apartment.
One pierced the door and felled 36-year-old detective Sherman
Griffiths, a veteran member of the elite anti-drug task force.
   When the detectives finally knocked down the steel-reinforced
door,the apartment was empty. They rushed down a back staircase and
arrested Lewin and three other people on a lower floor.
   Prosecutors later dropped charges against the other three in
return for testimony against the 33-year-old Lewin, who maintains he
is innocent.
   From the outset, a weakness in the prosecution's case was that
Lewin did not match the informant's description of the crack dealer
who occupied the apartment and presumably fired the fatal shot.
   According to the affidavit police submitted to obtain the search
warrant, John said the dealer was Hispanic and about 5-foot-6. Lewin
is a 6-foot Jamaican.
   In pretrial hearings last month, Lewin's attorney said John was a
vital defense witness, and Judge Charles M. Grabau ordered
detectives Carlos Luna, Hugo R. Amate and Paul G. Schroeder to bring
him into court.
   When the detectives said they were unable to find the informant,
Grabau threw out the charges and lambasted the detectives, saying he
believed they had willfully disobeyed his orders.
   Last week, Francis O'Meara, assistant district attorney for
Suffolk County went back into court to make an extraordinary
accusation. He said the detectives had lied to him and the court
about the informant, either to strengthen the case against Lewin or
to protect the search warrant.
   And O'Meara contended the charges against Lewin should not be
dropped. He said the actual informant was not John _ who may or may
not exist _ but another man, identified in court as ``Y.''
   Lewin's lawyer maintains that ``Y'' is still not the right man.
   The judge is scheduled to consider reinstating the charges this
week. In the interim, the state attorney general is considering
perjury charges against the suspended detectives.
   None of the three officers could be reached for comment. One is
on vacation in South America and the other two did not respond to
repeated messages asking them to call.
   Deputy Superintendent James W. Wood, supervisor of the three, has
repeatedly said he accepts full responsibility for the actions of
the team.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
