<FIRST>r a PM-DoubleLife     03-06 0569</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Double Life,0585</SECOND>
<HEAD>Teen Scholarship Winner Awaits Trial for Husband's Slaying</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eva Garcia was praised as a model student last
December whose perserverance over inner-city hardship won her a free
college education that was to make her a teacher.
   But police allege the 18-year-old senior lived a secret life that
came to a head just weeks before when she secretly married and then
conspired to murder a man more than 20 years her elder.
   ``She seemed to be the kind of kid we were meant to help,'' said
Frank Raispis, a fellow of the Foundation for Excellence in
Teaching, a private Chicago institution that awarded Ms. Garcia and
14 other teen-agers college scholarships.
   ``She was overcoming all this adversity and putting on a bright
face. ... We said if we could only help one kid, this has to be the
one.''
   Now, Ms. Garcia is in Cook County Jail, facing charges of
conspiracy and murder and a possible death sentence.
   The young woman burst into tears last November when she learned
she was named one of the Academy of Educators Scholars, whose
members get a free college education, good summer jobs and up to
$10,000 after college in exchange for returning to teach in
inner-city schools.
   But police suspect they were tears of frustration over her secret
marriage just days earlier to 41-year-old Louie Weber. Police say
Ms. Garcia feared her marriage was an impossible hurdle to her
future as a scholarship student and teacher. They say Ms. Garcia
also had a 19-year-old boyfriend in Mexico she was considering
marrying.
   Police say the young woman and her husband, with whom she had
never lived, went to dinner on Nov. 26. Then, investigators believe,
she suggested a walk in a park on Chicago's South Side.
   Minutes later, they say, two men appeared. One of them raised a
handgun, fired once and killed Weber with a shot in the head, police
say.
   Paul Rutherford, 18, and Richard Rubalcava, 25, have been charged
with conspiracy and murder along with Ms. Garcia. Police allege that
the young woman offered Rutherford $1,000 to kill Weber and that
Rutherford hired Rubalcava as the triggerman.
   ``These people looked like they were in love,'' said Jerry
Colhane, 37, a friend of Weber's. ``I'll never figure it out. I
can't see a person being married this short amount of time and this
happening. I mean, there's always divorce. This is America.''
   Despite her secret marriage, Ms. Garcia had continued to live at
home with her strict great-aunt and great-uncle. Her mother as a
teen-ager handed Eva over to the relatives to raise, friends say.
She never met her father.
   Ms. Garcia always did well in school, getting mostly A's and B's,
despite her fractured home life.
   Then she met Weber, a self-employed truck driver, in November
1987. In order to carry on the secret romance, Ms. Garcia began to
skip classes, missing 50 days in one semester.
   To explain her absences, Ms. Garcia told one teacher her father
had been murdered in Cuba and she had flown to Miami for the burial,
and that her great-aunt later died of an illness so she had to stay
home to care for her great-uncle.
   The teacher later cited to the scholarship committee these family
deaths as examples of the adversity Ms. Garcia had to overcome.
   Ms. Garcia gave up her scholarship after her arrest Jan. 21.
</TEXT>
