<FIRST>r a PM-AIDSDrugs     03-06 0336</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AIDS Drugs,0342</SECOND>
<HEAD>Group To Import Unapproved Drugs For AIDS Patients</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An AIDS patient-advocacy group plans to import
prescription drugs that have not been approved by the U.S. Food and
Drug Administration for treatment of AIDS patients, according to a
report published today.
   The New York-based People with AIDS Health Group plans to get the
drugs from sympathetic doctors in England, West Germany, France and
Japan, according to the report in The New York Times.
   The group will then distribute the drugs to any U.S. patient with
acquired immune deficiency syndrome who has a note or a prescription
for the drug from a doctor in this country, the newspaper said.
Patients' costs would be limited to the cost of the drug.
   Derek Hodel, executive director of People with AIDS, estimated
that hundreds of thousands of AIDS patients may take advantage of
the program.
   Last year, the FDA announced a policy that allows people with
life-threatening illnesses to import personal supplies of unapproved
drugs. Until now, those taking advantage of the policy had to find
doctors in other countries to prescribe the drugs or else import
only over-the-counter remedies, the Times said.
   Dr. Frank Young, commissioner of the FDA, told the Times he could
not say whether the FDA would try to stop the People with AIDS
effort.
   AIDS patient advocates have criticized the FDA, saying it has
been overly cautious about approving AIDS drugs. AIDS patients say
they do not have time to wait for more tests on drugs deemed
controversial by the FDA, but the federal agency says it has a
responsibility to protect Americans from drugs that could be useless
or harmful.
   The health group said the drug that is most important to them is
fluconazole, a product of Pfizer Inc. that is used to treat
cryptococcal meningitis afflicting about 10 percent to 15 percent of
AIDS patients. The company is seeking FDA approval of the drug,
which has been approved for sale in England, France, Denmark and
Ireland.
</TEXT>
