<HEAD>Governor's Wife Expected Home After Month At Alcohol Treatment Center</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BROOKLINE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kitty Dukakis is ``raring to go''
following four weeks of treatment at a Rhode Island alcoholism
center, according to a former aide.
   ``I understand that she'll be back in Boston later in the week,''
said Paul Costello, press aide to Mrs. Dukakis during the the
presidential campaign of her husband, Gov. Michael S. Dukakis.
   Mrs. Dukakis, 52, entered Edgehill Newport in Newport, R.I., on
Feb. 5 because of excessive drinking following the governor's failed
presidential bid, Dukakis said Feb. 6. Most patients undergo a
28-day rehabilitation program sometimes followed by three days of
observation on the premises.
   ``She's in good physical shape, in terrific spirits and she's
raring to go,'' Costello, who is now a public relations executive in
Washington, told the Boston Sunday Herald.
   Costello said Mrs. Dukakis will probably share her efforts
against alcoholism with the public because ``she likes to use her
life as a way to help others.''
   ``And I think she'll do that, through her book or in her speaking
engagements, which she'll resume rather rapidly,'' he said.
   Costello said the governor has talked with his wife every night
during her stay at Edgehill. He has visited her every weekend.
   Exhaustion, stress and the letdown of the campaign loss caused
Mrs. Dukakis' underlying chemical dependency to flare into episodes
of excessive drinking, the governor has said.
   When she entered the Newport facility, Dukakis saluted her
courage and asked the public to respect her privacy and support her
recovery.
   S. Stephen Rosenfeld, the governor's chief of staff, declined to
comment Sunday on when Mrs. Dukakis is expected to return home,
saying the family wanted privacy.
   Edgehill, a 160-bed facility, was founded in 1980 by businessman
Chester Kirk, a recovering alcoholic. It serves more than 1,000
patients a year.
