<SECOND>PM-BRF--Israel-Oldenburg,0174</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Sculptor Wins Wolf Prize</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American pop art sculptor Claes Oldenburg has
won the $100,000 Wolf Prize in the Arts, the Israel-based Wolf
Foundation announced today.
   It praised the artist's works ``for all the simplicity of their
subject matter ... (which) invite the observer to reflect on life's
processes.''
   Oldenburg, 60, explores the ironic and humorous aspects of common
objects that he grossly distorts in scale and shape. He is noted for
his soft sculptures of stuffed cloth and giant objects of such
everyday items as electrical plugs, baseball bats and clothespins.
   The Swedish-born sculptor became an American citizen in 1953.
   Israeli President Chaim Herzog will present the prize in the
Knesset, or parliament, in May, the foundation said.
   The Wolf prizes for medicine, chemistry, mathematics, physics,
agriculture and the arts were established by Ricardo Wolf, a
German-born chemist who emigrated to Cuba before World War II. He
was Cuban ambassador to Israel and lived here until his death in
1981.
