<SECOND>PM-Israel, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0482,0529</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Killed, 10 Reported Wounded In Clashes</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with two Palestinians killed, 10
wounded, army now saying 130 sted 150 Palestinians detained. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALLYN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soldiers fatally shot two Palestinians today,
and 10 others were reported wounded in clashes today with
stone-throwing protesters during a general strike in the occupied
West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   It was the highest daily death toll in nearly a month in the
15-month Palestinian uprising and brought the total number of
Palestinians killed in the rebellion to 390. Seventeen Israelis have
also died.
   A Palestinian security prisoner also died in a Gaza prison today
and police were investigating the circumstances, army radio
reported. Some Arab reports suggested the 32-year-old victim had
been ill.
   A hospital official said 19-year-old Ahmed Ramadan El Azani of
Gaza's Beit Lahiya village died at Shifa Hospital in Gaza City after
being struck in the chest by a bullet.
   Arab reports said the gunfire was in response to stone-throwing
riots in the area. Soldiers placed a curfew on Beit Lahiya's 7,000
residents after the violence.
   The second Palestinian killed today was Ibrahim Mohammed Al
Jaber, 24, from Salem village near the West Bank city of Nablus, who
was shot three times in the face during a search and arrest raid by
troops, Arab reports said.
   The army confirmed two fatalities in Beit Lahiya in Gaza and
Salem and the wounding of one youth in the West Bank as he threw
rocks at an Israeli bus bringing Palestinian workers to Israel. The
other reports were being checked, the army said.
   The army also confirmed the Salem raid but said it was
investigating the circumstances.
   Ten Palestinians aged 15 to 30 were wounded in the legs during
stoning riots that erupted in Salem and four other places in the
West Bank and Gaza Strip, the Arab reports said.
   The clashes came as Palestinians shut shops, stayed home from
jobs and halted public transportation in a strike called by
underground leaders of the Palestinian revolt.
   A small bomb exploded at a soldiers' post north of Tel Aviv,
Israel radio reported. No one was injured and 20 Arabs in the area
were detained for questioning, the radio said.
   The Israeli army said it freed 130 Palestinian detainees from
Ketziot prison in southern Israel in honor of this week's Moslem
Holiday, Isra Al Meraj. The day marks prophet Mohammed's holy
pilgrimage from Mecca to Jerusalem, where Moslems believe he
ascended to heaven.
   Earlier reports said 150 detainees would be freed.
   In Tel Aviv on Sunday, Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir defiantly
rejected a U.S. claim that Jewish settlements constructed in the
occupied lands are an obstacle to Middle East peace.
   In a speech to colleagues in his right-wing Likud bloc, Shamir
also denounced Israeli activists of the Peace Now movement for
meeting with Palestinians in the occupied territories. Shamir
accused the activists of sabotaging Israel's political and security
interests.
   Peace Now activist Zeev Sternhell today told army radio that
Shamir's remarks were ``vulgar defamation.''
</TEXT>
