<FIRST>r i PM-DeadlyLiquor 1stLd-Writethru a0465 03-06 0479</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Deadly Liquor, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0465,0492</SECOND>
<HEAD>Home-made Liquor Kills 130 in India</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede New Delhi</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS thruout to UPDATE with new death toll; ADD quotes, details;
no pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BARODA, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities said today at least 130 people
died and 151 were critically ill after hundreds of laborers drank an
illegal home-made liquor in the only Indian state where the sale of
alcohol is banned.
   Doctors said hospitals were unable to cope with the rush of
victims, and that there was little chance the most seriously injured
of the 251 hospitalized victims would survive.At least 25 people
were blinded by the tainted brew.
   The local government announced police arrested three people who
supplied the liquor. Several policemen were suspended for failing to
avert the tragedy, the government said.
   Baroda is a major industrial center in Gujarat, the only Indian
state where it is illegal to sell alcohol. The city, 560 miles
southwest of New Delhi, is home to 2.5 million people.
   According to the United News of India, the son of one supplier
and the son of a prominent local politician were among those killed
by the moonshine.
   The boot-leg liquor is normally a mixture of ethyl alcohol, alum
and natured spirits. But this time, industrial methyl alcohol was
mixed to the brew known locally as ``lattha,'' which is sold in
plastic sacks for the equivalent of 10 cents. Methyl alcohol
paralyzes the central nervous system.
   Most survivors were too ill to speak, but one told the Press
Trust of India news agency the only difference he noticed was that
the liquor was ``sweeter than normal.''
   Press Trust said many of the victims became dizzy and complained
of nausea and stomach aches before losing consciousness.
   A doctor at the state-run Sir Siyaji General Hospital, which was
treating most of the victims, said conditions at the facility were
precarious, with groaning victims crowded against each other on the
floor, on stretchers, and occasionally three to a bed.
   ``We do not have enough bottles of glucose to even administer
first aid to the victims,'' the doctor said, speaking on condition
of anonymity. ``There are no free stretchers to bring in more
patients, because people are already sleeping on them.''
   Gujarat's chief minister, Amarsinh Chaudhary, ordered an
investigation and promised action against the police officials who
failed to avert the disaster, the Times of India reported.
   The newspaper said most of the victims were poor laborers who
bought the liquor Saturday morning after receiving their monthly
wages. The first deaths were reported about midnight Saturday, it
said.
   As news of the deaths emerged, police fanned out across Baroda
with loudspeakers blaring warnings about the liquor.
   About 300 people have died in seven illicit liquor cases in
Gujarat during the last decade, United News said. Two of the
previous cases occurred in Baroda, with others reported in Ahmedabad
and Surat.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
