<FIRST>r w PM-Scotus-Witness     03-06 0454</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Witness,450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Bars Lawsuit Against Former New York Federal Prosecutor in
Shooting</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today barred a lawsuit
against a former federal prosecutor who refused police protection to
a witness gunned down before she could testify.
   The justices, without comment, let stand a ruling that the
prosecutor was not legally responsible to protect the woman, killed
in New York City along with three CBS employees who tried to come to
her aid.
   Former assistant U.S. Attorney Stephen Schlessinger was sued by
the family of Lena Margaret Barbera.
   She was abducted from a rooftop parking area in Manhattan on
April 12, 1982, and later was shot to death along with the CBS
workers.
   Irwin Margolies, president of Candor Diamond Corp., was convicted
of murder along with the hit man, Donald P. Nash.
   The government had been investigating alleged fraud in Margolies'
business. Ms. Barbera, an accountant there, agreed to cooperate in
the investigation.
   Prosecutors agreed to allow her to plead guilty to one count of
fraud and recommend she not serve any jail sentence.
   In December 1981, Schlessinger allegedly told Margolies' lawyer,
Henry Ostericher, that Barbera and another unnamed woman working at
Candor were cooperating with the government.
   Court papers suggested Schlessinger was trying to put pressure on
Margolies to confess to fraud.
   Soon after the Schlessinger-Ostericher conversation, another
former Candor employee, Jenny Soo Chin, disappeared. Ms. Chin, a
close friend of Ms. Barbera, apparently was suspected by Margolies
of being the other witness cooperating with prosecutors.
   Ms. Chin's body never was found but there was testimony that Nash
displayed a photograph of her corpse to Margolies as proof he had
killed her.
   Ms. Barbera then requested police protection for herself for the
second time, and Schlessinger again denied it.
   The suit against Schlessinger accused him of violating her rights
by negligetly and recklessly denying her protection that could have
saved her life.
   The 2nd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals threw out the suit in
December 1987.
   The appeals court said prosecutors have qualified immunity from
suit when their conduct does not violate clearly established rights
of individuals.
   ``We cannot say that it was clearly established that the
government had created or assumed a special relationship with
Barbera,'' the appeals court said. ``It would have been speculative
at best to conclude that Barbera was entitled to police protection
or that the government was otherwise obliged to safeguard her from
those against whom she was going to testify.''
   Just last month, the Supreme Court ruled in a Wisconsin case that
the government has no constitutional duty to protect individuals
from private violence or abuse.
   The New York case is Barbera vs. Schlessinger, 87-2034.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
