<FIRST>r w PM-Scotus-SexAbuse     03-06 0378</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Sex Abuse,340</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Orders More Hearings in Pennsylvania Sexual Abuse Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today ordered more hearings
in the case of three Pennsylvania school officials sued by a former
student who says she was sexually abused by her high school band
instructor.
   The justices said a federal appeals court should review its
ruling that the school officials sued by Kathleen Stoneking, a
former student at Bradford Area High School, are not entitled to
qualified legal immunity.
   The justices said the appeals court ruling should be restudied in
light of their Feb. 22 decision in a Wisconsin case that government
has no constitutional duty to protect individuals from private abuse
or violence.
   Whether that decision controls the Pennsylvania case is not
clear, however, since the lawsuit alleges that a state employee _
not a private citizen _ administered the abuse.
   Ms. Stoneking was graduated from high school in 1983. Her 1987
lawsuit contends that school principal Frederick Smith, assistant
principal Richard Miller and school district superintendent
Frederick Shuey violated her rights by failing to protect her.
   The suit alleges that beginning in Ms. Stoneking's sophomore
year, band instructor Edward Wright sexually harassed and abused
her, and forced her to engage in various sex acts with him.
   The suit alleges that the school officials named as defendants
knew of complaints against Wright involving other female students.
It states that the school officials either knew or recklessly failed
to discover that Wright was sexually abusing female band members.
   Wright was suspended in 1986, and later resigned. He pleaded
guilty to criminal charges, including indecent assault, that same
year.
   The three officials sued by Ms. Stoneking sought to have the case
thrown out before reaching a trial. They said they were entitled to
qualified immunity _ a legal doctrine shielding public officials
from liability when their conduct ``does not violate clearly
established statutory or constitutional rights of which a reasonable
person would have known.''
   A federal judge refused to throw out the case, and that ruling
was upheld on a 2-1 vote by the 3rd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals
last Sept. 12.
   The school officials then sought help from the Supreme Court.
   The case is Smith vs. Stoneking, 88-802.
</TEXT>
