<FIRST>r a PM-RapeSentence     03-06 0481</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Rape Sentence,0495</SECOND>
<HEAD>Residents Outraged By Lenient Sentence For Convicted Rapist</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAULT STE. MARIE, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge who gave a rapist a
lenient sentence because he said he didn't want to keep him from his
goal of becoming a police officer has provoked outrage in this
normally peaceful Upper Peninsula community.
   Two weeks ago, Visiting Alger County Circuit Judge Charles Stark
set aside his original verdict in the rape case and instead
convicted David Caballero under a youthful offenders act for
attacking a fellow college student.
   The move spared Caballero jail time. He was ordered to spend
three years on probation and pay $975 in court costs and $200
compensation to the victim. If he complies with the terms, his
record will be expunged. His court file has been suppressed.
   Stark said he took the action partly because Caballero, 21, was a
criminal justice major and the conviction would have prevented him
from achieving his goal of becoming a police officer.
   The judge issued the original rape conviction Jan. 10, after a
bench trial. If the judge had not revised it, Caballero would have
faced a minimum five-year prison sentence for two counts of
first-degree criminal sexual conduct.
   Chippewa County Prosecutor Patrick Shannon said he will appeal
the sentence.
   Stark's action has prompted more irate calls to the Sault Ste.
Marie Evening News editorial offices than any story in recent
memory, said the newspaper's editor, Ken Fazzari.
   ``I think they would lynch the judge if they had him right
here,'' Fazzari said.
   The victim was hospitalized for emotional stress after the
incident and transferred from Lake Superior State University to a
college out of state. She said she was devastated by the lenient
sentence.
   The state Holmes Youthful Trainee Act allows for special
treatment of a defendant whose crime occurred before age 20.
   Stark convicted Caballero Jan. 10 of two counts of rape in the
Dec. 18, 1987, attack. Stark said he couldn't convince prosecutors
to consider a lesser charge that would have allowed for reduced jail
time. He invoked the youthful offenders act even though Caballero
already was 20 years old when the rape occurred.
   ``This was a very unhappy choice for us,'' the judge said.
   Caballero has left Lake Superior State and is studying criminal
justice at the University of Michigan at Dearborn, said his
attorney, David Goldenberg.
   The victim said Caballer followed her around at a small campus
party and insisted on walking her back to her dormitory room at 3
a.m.
   When they arrived, Caballero placed himself ``so that as soon as
I unlocked and opened the door, he could get in.''
   ``I said, `I appreciate your walking me back here, but you're not
allowed in here,''' the Detroit Free Press quoted her as saying.
Caballero then followed her into the room, forced her onto her bed
and tore off her clothing, she said.
</TEXT>
