<FILEID>AP-NR-03-06-89 1116EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Scotus-Beating     03-06 0592</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Beating,590</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Orders Pa. Beating Death Award Reconsidered</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today ordered a federal
appeals court to consider freeing a Pennsylvania city and one of its
police officers from paying a $66,000 award over a 1981 beating
death.
   The justices said the appeals court should restudy the case in
light of their Feb. 22 decision in a Wisconsin case.
   In that ruling, the high court said government officials have no
constitutional duty to protect individuals from private violence or
abuse.
   In the Pennsylvania case, a federal jury awarded $66,000 to Mamie
Horton, whose son Douglas Powdrill was beaten to death at the Cash
Club in New Kensington, Pa., on Nov. 10, 1981.
   The jury found that the city and Police Sergeant William Dlubak
violated Powdrill's right by failing to protect him.
   The Cash Club, a private social club, was managed by Charles
``Pope'' Flenory, a retired New Kensington policeman and a friend of
Dlubak.
   Flenory allegedly summoned Dlubak to the club to frighten
Powdrill into confessing that Powdrill stole some records from the
club's disc jockey.
   Powdrill tearfully pleaded with Dlubak to take him out of the
club but the officer refused, according to court records.
   Dlubak allegedly told Flenory, ``I guess you can take care of
this yourself.''
   After Dlubak left, Powdrill and Milton Patrick, who also was
suspected in the theft of the records, were beaten severely by club
employees. Patrick survived but Powdrill died.
   While the beatings were going on, friends of Powdrill arrived at
the club and then went to the police station a block away to ask for
help.
   The two officers who arrived at the club to investigate left
within a few minutes, after talking to Flenory.
   Mrs. Horton alleged that the police department for years had
failed to investigate beatings and other criminal activities at
Flenory's club.
   She sued the city and Dlubak under a federal civil rights law,
and the jury awarded $65,899 to Mrs. Horton.
   The 3rd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals, which upheld the award
last August, noted that New Kensington had a ``hands-off'' policy
toward complaints of drunkenness at the city's private clubs.
   The policy said, ``When a call is received from a private club,
where the complaint is intoxication, the club should be tactfully
encouraged to handle its own problem. Such a club is not a public
place and arrests are invalid.''
   The 3rd Circuit court said Dlubak's handling of the case was in
line with that policy, and therefore the city can be held liable for
violating Powdrill's rights.
   The appeals court said city officials argued that ``although
Dlubak could reasonably foresee serious harm befalling Powdrill, he
owed Powdrill no duty. We disagree.''
   The Supreme Court has ruled that cities may be sued successfully
in such cases when someone's rights are violated in accord with a
municipal policy or custom.
   In the appeal acted on today, New Kensington officials said
Dlubak ``did not create or exacerbate the allegedly dangerous
condition. At most he can be charged with failing to exercise due
care in investigating a crime, the burglary at the Cash Club.''
   The city's appeal said there was no evidence Dlubak relied on the
so-called hands-off policy toward private clubs when he left the
matter in Flenory's control.
   In a criminal case stemming from the incident, Ronald DeVaughn, a
disc jockey at the club, pleaded guilty to murder and was sentenced
to 15 to 20 years in prison.
   The case is New Kensington vs. Horton, 88-816.
</TEXT>
