<FIRST>r a PM-CruseTrial 1stLd-Writethru a0469 03-06 0710</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cruse Trial, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0469, a0498,0725</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Stands Trial In 1987 Shooting Rampage That Killed Six</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 5 grafs to UPDATE with jury selection beginning,
picking up 5th graf pvs, `In a...'.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By IKE FLORES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BARTOW, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The trial of a retired librarian will hinge
on whether a jury believes he was temporarily insane when he fired
on children, shoppers and police officers during a seven-hour siege,
killing six people.
   Lawyers for William B. Cruse, 61, planned to argue that alcohol
and psychiatric problems caused him to open fire with a
semiautomatic rifle, a shotgun and a revolver outside his home in
the coastal community of Palm Bay and at two adjacent shopping
centers.
   Jury selection began today, with Circuit Judge John Antoon
convening a pool of more than 100 people from which to select a
12-member jury and several alternates.
   The shooting spree April 23, 1987, led to 36 felony charges that
could send Cruse to the electric chair: six counts of first-degree
murder, 28 of attempted murder and two of kidnapping.
   The trial was moved 75 miles west to Bartow after a telephone
survey suggested that many people in central Florida's Brevard
County believed Cruse guilty.
   In a videotaped interview after his arrest, Cruse calmly told
police he believed neighbors, strangers and supermarket employees
were constantly spreading rumors that he was homosexual. He said he
had to stop it.
   ``I just wanted people to leave me alone,'' he said in the tape
shown publicly for the first time Thursday during a hearing. ``I had
to do something to stop them. I know I'm not queer.''
   But he added, ``I was drunk and crazy and I just don't remember
hurting anyone.''
   Seemingly meek, Cruse has a reputation as an arrogant demanding
prisoner at Brevard County Jail, where he has been held without bond
since his arrest.
   He quit eating at one point, claiming that jailers were trying to
poison him, and he had to be force-fed through a tube in his nose
for several days.
   Most of the time, he was kept in the jail's medical unit, not ill
or suicidal, but because officers feared he might be killed by other
inmates.
   ``He is not a very likable person,'' said Sheriff Jake Miller.
   A court-appointed attorney announced an insanity defense early
on, and lawyers for the public defender's office now handling the
case have been proceeding along those lines. Cruse was found
competent to stand trial.
   Under Florida law, a person can be found innocent by reason of
insanity if they are unaware of their actions or unable to
distinguish between right and wrong at the time.
   Investigators have said Cruse confessed shortly after his arrest.
In the videotape of his interrogation, Cruse acknowledged firing his
guns, which he seaid he took to the shopping centers to make people
stop talking about him.
   ``I just suppose I wanted to scare some people,'' he said. ``I
hope I made an impression on them.''
   Prosecutors say that after cooking dinner for his wife, Malahat,
who suffers from Parkinson's disease, he left their modest home and
fired on neighborhood children, wounding a teen-age boy playing
basketball.
   As investigators later reconstructed the crime, the gunman then
drove to the nearby Palm Bay Shopping Center and opened fire, first
with one weapon and then another, leaving the parking lot of a
supermarket littered with bodies.
   Three shoppers were killed and others wounded in the first
outburst.
   The gunman then drove across a busy highway to the Sabal Palm
Square shopping center, left his car and killed the first police
officer to arrive. He wounded a second policeman, reloaded his
revolver and fatally shot that officer between the eyes.
   The gunman then moved to the another supermarket, blasted out the
storefront glass and burst in, spraying the store with bullets as
some 100 customers and employees ran from the store or hid. One
customer was killed.
   He found a clerk hiding in a store restroom and took her hostage.
   Police closed in and tried to persuade him to surrender. After
the clerk escaped, police fired tear gas and stormed the store.
Cruse stumbled out and was captured as he tried to flee, authorities
said.
</TEXT>
