<FIRST>r a PM-FlagArt     03-06 0401</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Flag Art,0410</SECOND>
<HEAD>Veterans March On Art Institute To Protest Flag On Floor</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SHERI PRASSO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A state senator vowed to have a museum official
arrested and 600 people marched on the Art Institute of Chicago to
protest an exhibit featuring an American flag spread on the floor.
   Republican Sen. Walter Dudycz of Chicago said he will go to Cook
County Circuit Court on Tuesday to press charges of desecrating the
flag against Joyce Fernandez, director of exhibitions and events at
the art institute. County courts were closed today for a state
holiday.
   Veterans and relatives from Illinois, Wisconsin, Indiana and
Michigan sang patriotic songs and carried signs with such messages
as ``Freedom of speech does not include desecration of the American
flag'' during the demonstration Sunday.
   Officials closed the exhibit at the Art Institute's school early,
the second time in a week the controversy has closed it down.
   A man who tried to return to the exhibit a second time to pick up
the flag and refused to leave and a woman who would not come down
from a police barricade were arrested for disorderly conduct, police
said.
   Neither Fernandez nor Art Institute officials could be reached by
telephone at the institute's school today.
   The flag is part of a work by art student ``Dread'' Scott Tyler
titled ``What is the Proper Way to Display a U.S. Flag?'' Besides
the flag on the floor where viewers might step on it, it features
photos of flag-draped coffins and South Koreans burning the flag,
and a book inviting viewer comment.
   The exhibit was closed to the public Feb. 24 after veterans
groups complained that it was an insult and sued. The show reopened
Thursday after a circuit judge ruled the exhibit is ``as much an
invitation to think about the flag as it is an invitation to step on
it.''
   Chicago Republican mayoral candidate Edward Vrdolyak also
attended Sunday's rally, and pledged to lobby the corporations that
support the Art Institute to reduce their financial support if the
flag is not removed. Dudycz and Republican state Rep. Linda
Williamson want to try to cut off state funds.
   On Saturday, a tourist from Alexandria, Va., art teacher Susan
Willhoft, was arrested on a felony flag desecration charge after she
stepped on the flag. Her lawyers said it was an accident. She was
released Sunday on bond.
</TEXT>
