<FIRST>r a AM-Gumbel'sGrumble     03-06 0505</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Gumbel's Grumble,0522</SECOND>
<HEAD>Welcome To `Todays of Our Lives'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   To recapitulate: Bryant ripped Willard and Gene
in a memo which surfaced mysteriously while Bryant was on vacation.
Willard was hurt; Jane, not mentioned in the memo, stood by
stoically.
   On Monday, host Bryant Gumbel returned to NBC's ``Today'' show
and joked about the controversy that had engulfed the nation's
top-rated breakfast show in his absence.
   Weatherman Willard Scott was not there; he was starting his own
one-week vacation. An attempt to ease tensions by telephoning Scott
on the air foundered embarrassingly when the connection was lost,
and Gumbel and co-host Jane Pauley were forced to ad-lib through the
show's final moments.
   ``A very unusual Monday _ in many ways best forgot,'' said Gumbel.
   It all started last week, when someone leaked to New York Newsday
a memo Gumbel had written to ``Today'' producer Marty Ryan. In it,
Gumbel criticized reviewer Gene Shalit, consumer reporters David
Horowitz and Betty Furness and medical reporter Dr. Art Ulene. The
harshest words were reserved for Scott's hokey, homey shtick,
including his endless recitations of centenarians' birthdays.
   Scott at first made light of the memo, but later said Gumbel's
comments were hurtful and hinted he might leave.
   ``If it's not real, and if there isn't an honest, genuine
reconciliation, I don't think I belong there,'' Scott said.
   Exit Scott and Shalit, on vacation. Enter Gumbel.
   ``Good to be back after what should have been a quiet vacation,''
said Gumbel at the top of Monday's show. ``The fact that it wasn't
is something we'll get into a little bit later, but first things
first.''
   Pauley welcomed him back. ``You were never far from our
thoughts,'' she said wryly.
   Later on, Gumbel thanked callers for expressions of support,
saying ``Jane, Willard, Gene and I are very grateful.''
   ``We do appreciate your concern, and despite what you may have
heard or read in recent days, we are together and hopefully we're
going to be with you for many years to come,'' said Gumbel.
   ``Now that may come as sad news for those who have tried to
capitalize on our differences, but rest assured, that `Today' family
is intact and still smiling, albeit through some pain,'' he
continued.
   ```We'll still be here long after the recent headlines are
forgotten. Enough said.''
   Of course, it is not possible to say enough about the ``Today''
imbroglio. Midway through the show, Gumbel managed a crack after a
news story about secret government documents found in discarded safe.
   ``You've got to be careful where you put documents these days,''
said Gumbel, to peals of laughter.
   Then, at the show's end, came the phone-call fiasco. Gumbel said
he intended to talk with Scott ``about vacation plans and onto some
other things.'' He said he had talked to Scott several times since
Saturday and before the show.
   ``This was going to be our little surprise before going off,''
Gumbel said, and he wished Scott happy birthday.
   Tuesday is Scott's birthday. His 55th, not his 100th.
</TEXT>
