<FIRST>r w AM-Eclipse     03-06 0151</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Eclipse,150</SECOND>
<HEAD>Partial Eclipse Tuesday in West</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The sun will be partly obscured Tuesday morning
in an eclipse visible in the western portions of the United States
and Canada, the U.S. Naval Observatory reports.
   The sun will be as much as 80 percent hidden for residents of
western Alaska and Hawaii, while lesser amounts will be obscured in
other areas.
   The eclipse will not be visible at all east of a line running
from about Grand Rapids, Mich., through Peoria, Ill., Tulsa, Okla.
and Del Rio, Texas.
   The eclipse will begin at 8:17 a.m. PST, will reach its greatest
extent at 10:07 a.m. and end at 11:58 a.m., the Observatory reported.
   Astronomers cautioned that the eclipse must not be watched
directly because of danger of burning the eyes. The event can be
watched indirectly with a pinhole projector or through darkened film
made specifically for solar viewing.
</TEXT>
