<FIRST>r a PM-GroundedTanker     03-06 0345</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Grounded Tanker,0354</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oil Transfer Halted Amid Rough Seas</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rough seas forced crews to suspend work early
today on removing the remainder of the 90,000 barrels of crude oil
left aboard a damaged tanker that spilled 33,000 gallons of oil last
week.
   Coast Guard spokesman Dennis Hubbard said crews stopped work
shortly after midnight, and would decide later today when to resume
pumping what is left of the 3.7 million gallons of oil from the
800-foot Exxon Houston to its sister ship, the Exxon Yorktown, in
waters 14 miles off Oahu Island.
   Less than 10 percent of the oil remained aboard the damaged ship
when the transfer was suspended, Hubbard said.
   Once the oil is abord the Exxon Yorktown, Exxon Shipping Co. can
decide what to do with the Exxon Houston, which was torn from its
offshore mooring buoy in rough seas and high winds Thursday while
unloading crude oil, said Carrie Chassin, an Exxon spokeswoman.
   The stormy weather drove the ship aground on a coral reef about
1,500 yards off a little-used shoreline about 15 miles from Honolulu
and its famed Waikiki Beach.
   Cleanup crews spent their third day removing oil from a two-mile
stretch of coastline Sunday.
   The U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service said there were no reports of
birds or marine life being harmed by the oil.
   Exxon Shipping Co. President Frank J. Iarossi said the company
will spend whatever is needed to clean the beaches and ocean.
   Despite the wind and seas, the Exxon Houston was within safety
standards for unloading its cargo of Alaska North Slope crude oil at
the Hawaiian Independent Refinery, Iarossi said.
   About 25,200 gallons of crude oil spilled when floating hoses at
the mooring buoy separated, and about 8,400 gallons of fuel oil
spilled from a ruptured tank when the ship ran aground, according to
revised estimates Saturday by Coast Guard officials. Earlier
estimates were that 117,000 gallons of oil had spilled.
   The tanker floated free of the reef on the rising tide Friday
night after its ballast water was pumped out.
</TEXT>
