<DOCNO> AP890306-0096 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-06-89 1417EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Agriculture     03-06 0384</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Agriculture,0395</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pravda Attacks Superministry of Agriculture</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Communist Party newspaper Pravda Monday joined
other Soviets criticizing the ministry in charge of agriculture,
reprinting citizen comment that it is ineffective and useless.
   Commonly known as ``Gosagroprom,'' the governmental committee
that oversees the agencies that run the nation's state-owned and
collective farms has recently been broadly criticized in the press.
   Rumors swept Moscow last week that the Kremlin leadership is
planning to abolish the committee, which was formed under Soviet
leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev in 1985 when five agricultural
ministries and some other state agencies were merged.
   The party's policy-making Central Committee will meet this month
and is expected to make reforms in agriculture to remedy chronic
food shortages.
   An article published in Pravda on Monday said the paperwork
produced by Gosagroprom indicates the ministry isn't overlooking
serious problems, but that a closer look reveals ``it's possible to
say it did not solve any big problems.''
   People attending a party conference in Kharkov, a Ukrainian city
400 miles south of Moscow, wrote a letter to the Supreme Soviet
parliament calling for the dismantling of ``this monopolistic,
ineffective, bureaucratic organization'' that hinders effective
forms of farming, the article said.
   Pravda said Gosagroprom has made certain the farmer's dream of
living as well as non-farmers who work in food processing remains
just a dream. The most common words to Gosagroprom from farmers are:
``Give us resourses, and don't bother our work,'' Pravda said.
   The government daily Izvestia also printed an article Monday by a
doctor of economic sciences, I. Buzdalov, that indicated there is
consensus at least on the need to drastically cut back the size of
Gosagroprom, starting with the regional organizations responsible
for agriculture, known to the Soviets by the Russian-language
acronym of RAPOs.
   ``The judgment on whether Gosagroprom, starting with RAPO, is
necessary in its present form is no longer subject to debate, it
seems,'' the economist wrote.
   The Politburo published a report Saturday saying it supported the
creation of various types of farms to help alleviate the Soviet
Union's food shortage.
   The 12-member ruling body made no direct reference to abolishing
Gosagroprom, but said new forms and methods of management were
needed in the country's agricultural management.
   The Central Committee has announced it will hold a plenum March
15-16.
</TEXT>
