<DOCNO> AP890306-0098 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-06-89 1456EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Botha     03-06 0507</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Botha,0521</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pro-Government Newspaper Calls for Botha to Resign</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A pro-government newspaper
known for its staunch support of President P.W. Botha joined other
leading publications that called Monday for the resignation of the
ailing leader.
   Botha, 73, is recovering from a stroke suffered Jan. 18, but he
announced last week that he will return to office in April and plans
to remain at least until his term expires in September.
   Botha, who has been head of government for more than 10 years,
left open the possibility he may seek another five-year term as
president.
   ``There is a time to come and there is a time to go,'' said the
pro-government daily Beeld in an editorial, quoting the words of
D.F. Malan, a prime minister in the 1940s and 1950s and Botha's
political mentor.
   ``May we suggest that (Botha) again reads these words
attentively,'' the editorial said. ``(Malan's) voice from the far
past still has much to say to us all.''
   There had been speculation Botha would return to office only long
enough to step down with dignity and ceremony, making way for
Education Minister F.W. de Klerk, the heir apparent as president.
   De Klerk was elected leader of the governing National Party last
month after Botha resigned from that post. Traditionally, the party
leader has been head of government, and de Klerk has found himself
in an awkward position because he has no formal power over
government decision-making.
   The government-run South African Broadcasting Corp. said Monday
the country had been ``reinvigorated'' by de Klerk's initial
speeches since becoming head of the National Party.
   The lengthy editorial made no mention of Botha, but said de
Klerk's calls for race reform had drawn an ``enthusiastic response''
from opposition groups that have refused previously to negotiate
with the government.
   De Klerk has yet to declare any major policy differences with
Botha, but he is widely depicted as more flexible and pragmatic, and
thus more capable of breaking South Africa's political stalemate. He
has made vague proposals to soften the impact of existing
segregation laws.
   Several leading newspaper in recent days have predicted a power
struggle in the governing National Party if Botha attempts to remain
in charge.
   ``There is now a strong possibility that after the meetings of
... (National Party) organizations this week, a delegation could be
sent to Mr. Botha to ask him to stand down,'' the independent Star
newspaper, the country's largest selling daily, said in a front-page
story.
   Calls from Botha's resignation have come from liberal and
far-right opposition parties, as well as from some National Party
members.
   ``Botha, unable to relinquish high office gracefully, has put
himself into an untenable position,'' said Business Day, the leading
financial daily. ``Nobody in his personal entourage is likely to
tell him ... he is the most disliked leader the (National) Party has
ever had.''
   Botha has spent most of the time since his stroke recuperating at
his coastal vacation home while being replaced by an acting
president, Constitutional Development Minister Chris Heunis.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
