<FILEID>AP-NR-03-06-89 1530EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-BankOfficial     03-06 0285</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bank Official,300</SECOND>
<HEAD>Federal Reserve Board Attorney Says Enforcement Efforts Could Suffer</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM BOVEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An attorney for the Federal Reserve Board said
Monday that bank law-enforcement efforts could suffer because a
federal appeals court vacated a board order that had barred a former
chairman of Michigan National Corp. from the banking business.
   ``It creates a certain problem when someone can resign and
therefore elude jurisdiction,'' said Douglas Jordan, an attorney for
the board.
   In January 1988, the Federal Reserve Board removed Stanford
Stoddard as officer and director of the Detroit-area bank-holding
company and barred him from engaging in banking activities.
   However, in July 1984, Stoddard had resigned as head of the bank,
leaving the company nearly a year before the comptroller of the
currency began steps toward removing him. The comptroller,
recommending action against Stoddard, said the bank officer used
some of the institution's funds for improper purposes.
   Saying ``one cannot remove what isn't there,'' a federal appeals
court here, in a ruling Friday, vacated the board's order and agreed
to review the case.
   The board had argued that Congress intended the removal provision
as a way of barring people who engaged in midconduct from returning
to the banking business.
   ``It is not an uncommon occurrence for someone who has been
suspected or accused of misconduct to resign voluntarily or to
resign as a result of pressure from his institution,'' Jordan said.
   Stoddard's attorney, Keith Fisher, said his client ``seriously
wants to get back into the banking business.''
   ``In the current climate of troubled institutions all over the
country, someone of his enormous experience and talents would be
quite useful to any number of institutions,'' Fisher said.
</TEXT>
