<FIRST>r w AM-US-PalestinianThreat     03-06 0149</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Palestinian Threat,140</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Condemns New Threat on Rushdie</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department condemned on Monday a
threat by a radical Palestinian leader to carry out the orders of
Iran's Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini to kill British author Salman
Rushdie.
   Department spokesman Charles Redman said the statement by Ahmed
Jibril, leader of the Popular Front for the Liberation of
Palestine-General Command, ``highlights the menace'' posed by that
group and its association with Iran's state-sponsored terrorism.
   ``This terrorist group is based in Damascus and therefore the
government in Syria has an obligation to exercise control over the
group's actions,'' Redman said.
   ``We call on Syria to take appropriate action to ensure the
PFLP-GC does not follow through on this threat,'' he added.
   Jibril said Sunday that Rushdie's novel, ``The Satanic Verses,''
was a conspiracy to defame Islam and had been written at the behest
of ``arrogant'' Western forces.
