<HEAD>People in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GARDEN GROVE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The 1,000th taping of his ``Hour of
Power'' television show drew congratulations for the Rev. Robert H.
Schuller from all sorts of celebrities including three ex-presidents.
   Former Presidents Gerald Ford, Ronald Reagan and Richard Nixon
were among the well-wishers who sent videotapes to Sunday's service
at the Crystal Cathedral.
   Other celebrities sending tributes included Olympic swimmer Janet
Evans, entertainer Sammy Davis Jr., Mother Teresa and Coretta Scott
King, the widow of the Rev. Martin Luther King Jr.
   ``You've been our pastor, both on our visits to your church and
as we've traveled this great country,'' said Labor Secretary
Elizabeth Dole on behalf of herself and her husband, Sen. Bob Dole,
R-Kan. ``We're extremely proud of the accomplishment you're
celebrating today.''
   The anniversary show is scheduled to be broadcast April 2 in the
United States and April 9 overseas.
   Schuller began his ministry 34 years ago when he started a
congregation at a drive-in movie theater.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Eds: For release 6 p.m. EST.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>RADNOR, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ringo Starr feels right at home doing
children's television because he's with the same audience he had
when he was a Beatles.
   ``Kids and mothers were my crowd'' during the glory years as
drummer with the British singing group, Starr said in an interview
in TV Guide's March 11 issue.
   Starr said he does not think his current job is an anti-climax to
his years as a Beatle. Starr, 48, plays a train conductor in the new
PBS British import, ``Shining Time Station.''
   ``John had the intellectuals, Paul had the teenies (teen-age
girls), and George had the mystics. I always had the mothers and
babies,'' Starr said.
   He said mothers used to hold up their youngsters and yell to him,
``His first words were `Yeah, yeah, yeah,''' lyrics from the Beatles
hit ``She Loves You.'' Now, mothers lift up their kids saying
``There's Thomas,'' referring to his new character.
   ``So, I've got it all over again,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ROSWELL, N.M. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former ABC White House correspondent Sam
Donaldson, who calls himself a native son of New Mexico, plans to
build a ranch west of here.
   ``We're not speculating or trying to subdivide the area. We want
a working ranch,'' he said. ``I grew up in a ranching area and I
like it.''
   Donaldson, who was born in Texas and grew up in New Mexico,
bought 7,300 acres in the central part of the state last week.
   Donaldson, 54, said he and his wife, Janice, will eventually put
cattle and horses on the ranch.
   ``We've still got to fix the fences and the windmills,'' he said.
``And while the wind will be pumping water at the ranch, I'll be
pumping the wind in Washington.''
   He is preparing for a new prime-time news program with Diane
Sawyer.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Conrad Hall, the photography
director of ``Tequila Sunrise,'' took top honors as the people
behind the lens stepped into the spotlight for an annual awards
ceremony.
   Actor Gregory Peck presented Hall with his award in the
theatrical release category during the American Society of
Cinematographers' awards banquet at the Beverly Hilton Hotel Sunday
night, said society spokeswoman Rosalind May.
   Actor Jimmy Stewart presented the niece of Joe Biroc with the
society's Lifetime Achievement Award. Stewart and Biroc worked
together on the 1946 film classic ``It's A Wonderful Life.''
   Biroc, 86, was unable to attend the event.
   Biroc shared an Academy Award for his work on the 1974 film ``The
Towering Inferno'' and an Emmy Award for the 1971 TV movie ``Brian's
Song.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>RED BAY, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The daughter of country singer Tammy Wynette
returned to her mother's hometown to marry a college sweetheart.
   Miss Wynette's daughter by country singer George Jones,
18-year-old Tamla Georgette Jones, married Billy Wayne Terrell, 23.
   The ceremony Sunday at the Church of God was filmed for use in
Miss Wynette's upcoming television special.
   Miss Wynette sang ``The Twelfth of Never'' during the wedding,
for which she wore a purple and black knee-length dress.
   At a news conference she said that when her daughter told her
about her plans to get married, she wrote a song about it called
``When a Woman Becomes a Wife.'' The song appears on her new album,
``Next to You.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Where's George?
   That question could be asked at the meetings of the Board of
Regents of the newly formed University of Maryland system about the
absence of political columnist George F. Will.
   Will, who is also a network television commentator, has not shown
up for any of the seven regents' meetings held since Gov. William
Donald Schaefer appointed him in July.
   Will also is a member of the board's educational policy
committee, but he has failed to attend any of those meetings, too.
The policy committee is setting directives for each of the 11
campuses in the system.
   University of Maryland Chancellor John Toll said he has been in
contact with Will by telephone.
   ``He has been very busy,'' Toll told The (Baltimore) Evening Sun.
``There have been scheduling conflicts. The role of a regent is to
guide us on issues and perform services, and he is doing that.''
   Will's assistant in his Washington office told the newspaper that
Will was unavailable to comment on his attendance record as a
regent. Several calls to Will's office Monday went unanswered.
   Will has indicated he will attend the board's next meeting, April
5.
</TEXT>
