<FIRST>r a AM-Brites     03-06 0478</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brites,0493</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bright &amp; Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   No elk showed up, but it wasn't for lack of trying
as 43 contestants growled, grunted, chirped and squealed through
what was billed as the world elk-calling championship.
   The contestants each had one minute to give their best rendition
of bull and cow elk calls, while a panel of seven judges listened
intently behind a wooden partition at the Washington State
Convention and Trade Center.
   About 1,000 people attended Sunday's finals of the contest,
officially called the Anheuser-Busch World Wapiti (Elk) Calling
Championships.
   Many of the callers, or ``buglers,'' heaved their shoulders and
gyrated as they blew through two-foot long sections of rubber pipe
that directed their screeching calls to all parts of the room in the
convention center.
   One bugler brought a small tree and an armful of brush that he
ripped apart to simulate the sound of an animal tramping through the
woods. All but two of the callers had small rubber diaphragms in
their mouths that they blew on to create the wide range of noises an
elk makes.
   Wayne Carlton, who has 25 years experience calling everything
from alligators to turkeys, said most of the people who call elk do
it so they can hunt them, but others are photographers or those who
want excitement, he said.
   ``Imagine standing by a tree or just being out in the woods and
if you can imitate that, out walks a 700-800 pound bull elk looking
for you to run you away,'' he said. ``The excitement builds up when
you see the antlers walking through the trees at you.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>GREEN COVE SPRINGS, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   If justice is blind, it could
still follow the aroma down the halls of the Clay County Courthouse
to find Circuit Judge Giles P. Lewis cooking a daily gourmet lunch.
   ``He's the only person I've ever known who can spend the least
time and with the least amount of space and ingredients and turn out
such good food,'' said Circuit Judge William A. Wilkes, a regular at
Lewis' luncheon gathering.
   Each day in his courthouse office, Lewis takes off his robe and
whips up one of his many specialties, such as navy beans with smoked
sausage and ``lots of onions,'' with the help of a two-burner hot
plate and a microwave oven.
   His kitchen is neatly arranged along one wall of his office,
every nook and cranny of which doubles as a pantry.
   Lewis, 62, said he has loved to cook for years.
   ``I've been cooking for 40 years. I pulled so much `KP' in the
Army that I decided I might as well learn to cook.''
   Lewis, who has been a judge for 11 years, said he sometimes
thinks about switching careers.
   ``I could always be a cook,'' Lewis said. ``I'm afraid they don't
make much money, but they always eat.''
</TEXT>
