<FILEID>AP-NR-03-06-89 2043EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r p AM-TownMeeting     03-06 0467</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Town Meeting,0479</SECOND>
<HEAD>Death Penalty, Land Preservation Tops Issues for Town Meeting Day</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BURLINGTON, Vt. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Burlington voters on Tuesday will replace
socialist Mayor Bernard Sanders, who is stepping down after eight
years in hopes of seeing his movement broadened with the election of
a like-minded candidate.
   ``I'm no Bernie Sanders,'' Progressive Coalition candidate Peter
Clavelle, has said. ``Our backgrounds are different, our styles are
different, but our political visions are the same.''
   Mayoral elections in Burlington and other Vermont cities are part
of the yearly Town Meeting Day, when residents of all 247
municipalities debate civic issues and have their say about how
their towns and schools will run. In at least 35 towns, residents
will be voting on a non-binding resolution asking the state
Legislature to reinstate the death penalty.
   The mayor's race is expected to draw a large number of
Burlington's 25,000 registered voters to the polls.
   ``I think (turnout) is going to be high, higher than normal,'' Jo
Lamarche, secretary to City Clerk James Rader, said Monday. She said
her office has already received more than the usual amount of
absentee ballots for a mayor's race.
   Clavelle, 39, is the former community development director in
this city of 38,000 people and a former city manager in nearby
Winooski. He lacks Sanders' rhetorical flair and national reputation
for bashing corporate capitalism, but has support from the local
chapter of the National Organization for Women.
   Clavelle's main competition is Alderman Nancy Chioffi, 46, a
Democrat and clothing store owner who has support from both
Democrats and Republicans. The GOP didn't field a candidate.
   An anti-development candidate, Sandra Baird, 48, is running on
the Vermont Greens ticket, claiming Clavelle and Chioffi both have
``sold out'' to business interests.
   The move to put the death penalty question to voters came from
four Republican legislators who say there is strong support for
putting capital punishment back on the books for the first time
since the 1960s.
   Two years ago, about 30 towns took up the question, and
two-thirds voted for reinstatement, Rep. Nancy Sheltra said.
   At least nine towns will decide whether to form environmental
conservation commissions. Nine communities already have such boards,
which are volunteer groups created to protect a town's natural
resources.
   Proponents say the commissions help towns preserve and protect
wetlands, streams and other natural resources at a time when
overburdened town planning commissions are struggling to manage
growth.
   ``It makes people aware of what's going on in their town. They
begin to spark each other. It's amazing what an educational process
it is,'' said Justin Brande, the first executive director of the
Vermont Natural Resources Council.
   In several other communities, voters may authorize selectmen to
create funds with local taxes to protect land resources, such as
farmland, waterfront property and scenic areas.
</TEXT>
