<FILEID>AP-NR-03-06-89 2044EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-India     03-06 0382</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-India,0396</SECOND>
<HEAD>104 Sikhs Freed, Arrive in Amritsar</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEEPAK SHARMA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AMRITSAR, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge freed 188 Sikh political detainees
Monday, but police immediately rearrested 84 of them to face charges
related to militancy that prompted a 1984 army raid on the holiest
Sikh shrine.
   Witnesses said those released from more than four years' jail
without trial arrived under heavy guard Monday at the scene of their
arrests _ northern Amritsar city and its Golden Temple.
   Their freedom is part of a reconciliation drive Prime Minister
Rajiv Gandhi announced last week to try to end ethnic violence that
has wracked the prosperous northwestern state of Punjab for seven
years.
   ``The 104 men are free to go where they want,'' Punjabi police
chief K.P.S. Gill said at Amritsar as 300 police guards released the
detainees.
   Some of those freed shouted radical Sikh slogans demanding an
independent homeland, witnesses said.
   They were among about 300 men and women arrested in June 1984
when former Prime Minister Indira Gandhi ordered the army to raid
the Golden Temple and rout Sikh militants who had taken sanctuary
inside.
   At least 1,200 people died in the operation. Many of those
arrested in the temple complex were pilgrims who were held for
questioning but never charged.
   Mrs. Gandhi was assassinated by two Sikh bodyguards four months
later in retaliation for the raid.
   Sikhs make up 2 percent of India's population but are a slight
majority in the rich farming state of Punjab. Militants claim Sikhs
are discriminated against by the Hindu majority who comprise 82
percent of the population. They have waged a bloody secessionist
insurgency since 1982.
   In May 1987 the federal government dismissed the state government
and brought Punjab under direct federal rule in an effort to curb
the violence.
   But killings of Hindus and moderate Sikhs escalated. At least
2,400 were killed by Sikh militants last year, more than double the
number killed in 1987. More than 340 people have died this year.
   On Friday, Gandhi announced a peace initiative.
   In addition to the release of political detainees, Gandhi said
foreigners now can travel to Punjab without special government
permission. He also said elections will be held, starting May, for
village committees to supervise development work and law and order.
</TEXT>
