<FIRST>r a AM-BRF--SanQuentin     03-06 0138</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--San Quentin,0141</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lockdown Follows Discovery of Five Stabbing Weapons</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN QUENTIN, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 260 inmates at San Quentin
State Prison were under lockdown Monday after prison officials
discovered five homemade weapons during weekend searches, officials
said.
   Residents of a parole violators' unit were confined to their
cells after weapons made out of plastic dining utensils were
discovered Saturday in two hiding areas on the roof of a shower
area, said Vernell Crittendon, the warden's administrative assistant.
   Investigators planned to question all prisoners in the unit about
the weapons, Crittendon said.
   The weapons each measured six to seven inches long and were made
from plastic utensils that had been heated until pliable, sharpened
and submerged in cold water to harden the material, Crittendon said.
   Crittendon predicted the lockdown may last up to 10 days.
</TEXT>
