<FIRST>r a AM-CruseTrial     03-06 0357</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cruse Trial,0369</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jury Selection Begins in Mass-Murder Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By IKE FLORES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BARTOW, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jury selection began slowly Monday in the
murder trial of William B. Cruse, who contends he was ``drunk and
crazy'' during a 1987 shooting rampage that killed six people and
wounded 12 in Palm Bay.
   The trial was moved from the Atlantic Coast town to central
Florida after a court-ordered survey indicated that mostresidents of
the county where the shootings occurred believe Cruse is guilty.
   The first prospective juror called for questioning on pretrial
publicity offered a similar assessment when asked if she believed
she could deliver an impartial verdict.
   ``I truthfully do not think so,'' she responded. She said she had
a ``firm belief'' about the defendant's guilt, based on newspaper
stories and television news reports, which she did not think she
could put aside.
   Circuit Judge John Antoon dismissed her.
   Another of the six potential jurors questioned by noon Monday was
former Sheriff Louie Mims, who said he had formed an opinion about
the case but could put it aside to consider the facts as presented
in court.
   State Attorney Norm Wolfinger and Assistant Public Defender
Marlene Alva said they hoped to seat a jury by the end of Tuesday.
   The long-haired and bearded defendant is charged with six counts
of first-degree murder, 28 counts of attempted murder and two counts
of kidnapping.
   Public defenders for the 61-year-old former librarian are
prepared to argue that he was temporarily insane when he shot
students, shoppers, motorists and two police officers in two
shopping centers on April 23, 1987.
   Cruse kept his eyes closed much of the time. The gaunt-looking
former librarian sat quietly at the defense table. At times, he
seemed to doze.
   Cruse told police shortly after his capture _ following a
seven-hour standoff in a supermarket _ that he believed neighbors,
store employees and strangers were spreading rumors that he was
homosexual.
   ``I just wanted people to leave me alone,'' he told investigators
the morning after the shootout. ``I had to do something to stop
them.''
   However, he said he didn't remember hurting anyone.
</TEXT>
