<FIRST>r i AM-Korea-US     03-06 0153</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Korea-US,0159</SECOND>
<HEAD>Protesters Demand Relocation of U.S. Bombing Field</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Riot police clashed Monday with
protesters demanding the U.S. Air Force stop bombing practice on a
site near a residential area. Three women were injured in the
demonstration, press reports said.
   About 1,000 protesters from eight villages in Hwasung, 10 miles
south of Seoul, clashed with police during the four-hour rally,
according to Yonhap, the South Korean news agency.
   Yonhap said the protesters demanded U.S. military authorities
stop bombing practice near their villages or pay financial
compensation.
   The protesters pushed through a human wall of about 1,200 riot
police as well as barbed wire fences to demonstrate near a control
tower inside the field, the agency said.
   Demonstrators carried signs calling for safety measures to
protect the residential areas located near the bombing site, Yonhap
said.
   There was no immediate comment from either U.S. or South Korean
authorities.
