<FIRST>r w AM-Scotus-MentalPatients     03-06 0412</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Scotus-Mental Patients,410</SECOND>
<HEAD>Supreme Court to Decide Case of Man Held Without Hearing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court agreed Monday to decide
whether state officials can be sued for damages in federal court by
people involuntarily held at state mental hospitals without hearings
required by state law.
   The justices voted to review a ruling that would allow such a
federal lawsuit by a man held in a Florida state hospital for five
months without a hearing that state law said he should have had
within 48 hours.
   Florida authorities contend the man should be limited to suing in
state court.
   Darrell Burch was found wandering along a Florida highway on Dec.
7, 1981. He was taken to a Tallahassee community health services
center where he was held for three days.
   During that time, Burch was hallucinating. He said he believed he
was in heaven.
   After his stay at the center, Burch was transferred to the
Florida State Hospital, where he remained until May 7, 1982.
   Despite a state law that entitled him to a hearing within 48
hours to challenge his detention and treatment, Burch did not
receive a hearing.
   His federal suit alleged that various officials and employees of
the Florida State Hospital acted ``with willful, wanton and reckless
disregard of and indifference to'' his due-process rights.
   The suit invoked a much-used federal civil rights law.
   A federal judge threw out the suit, ruling that Burch was barred
from filing it because he could win adequate relief _ including
monetary damages _ by suing under personal-injury law in state court.
   A three-judge panel of the 11th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals
upheld the dismissal, but the entire appeals court voted 8-5 last
March 18 to reinstate the suit.
   The trial judge and three-judge appellate panel had relied on a
1981 Supreme Court decision in which the justices limited federal
civil rights lawsuits when certain state court remedies exist.
   But the full 11th Circuit court ruled that the 1981 decision
``does not apply to procedural due-process violations when the state
is in the position to provide pre-deprivation process.''
   Because Burch could have been given a hearing before his right to
liberty was deprived, the appeals court said, ``post-deprivation
remedies cannot provide due process.''
   The 1981 ruling also dealt with prison inmates who alleged they
wrongly had been deprived of their property rights, not their right
of liberty.
   The case is Zinmermon vs. Burch, 87-1965.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890306-0117 </DOCNO>
