<FIRST>r w AM-Quello-PayHike     03-06 0484</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Quello-Pay Hike,450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Quello Says ``Exorbitantly Paid'' Media People Campaigned Against
Pay Hike</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY ARNOLD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   FCC Commissioner James H. Quello on Monday said
``exorbitantly paid'' television journalists and entertainers
carried out an unconscionable campaign against the recent attempt in
Congress to raise the pay of high-level federal officials by 51
percent.
   Quello, who as a member of the Federal Communications Commission
would have gotten the pay hike had it cleared Congress, said it was
``the ultimate in unconscionable self-appreciation for TV and cable
personalities, news anchors and talk show hosts, many of whom make
10 to 25 times more than a senator or congressman, to indulge in a
Messianic binge against a salary adjustment to keep pace with
inflation for congressmen, key government officials and judges.''
   ``Are exorbitantly paid personalities and anchors who utilize
government licensed airwaves to accommodate their perpetual quest
for ratings, money and power really performing more valuable service
than those that grant and manage communications licenses, pass laws
and govern the nation? I think not,'' Quello said in a speech for
the New York chapter of the Federal Communications Bar Association.
   A copy of the speech was released in Washington.
   Quello said the pay plan, which would have raised congressional
salaries to $135,000, had been proposed by ``an impartial,
well-qualified, non-political commission of civic leaders'' and had
been supported by President Bush and then-President Reagan. He said
Congress and the news media ``failed to emphasize enough that this
was a catch-up increment'' recommended by the panel ``to keep
government pay abreast of inflation.''
   Quello's salary is $80,700 and he said that ``with a moderate
lifestyle, I have no problem living well on my government salary.
... But the salary level simply does not reflect the complexity or
importance of commission responsibilities.''
   He said that killing the salary proposal did not serve the public
interest ``because it doomed much-needed reforms on eliminating
congressional honoraria, limiting outside income and changing
campaign fund laws.''
   On another issue, Quello also repeated his view that it is
essential that free, over-the-air television survive in any future
scenario in which telephone companies are allowed to carry TV
signals on fiber-optic networks.
   ``Only broadcasting, not cable or phone fiber, has a government
licensed obligation to provide TV service to the public,'' Quello
said, adding that broadcasting is the ``principal source of local
news and government affairs, of vital local services like traffic,
road, weather, school closing reports and emergency bulletins. And
only broadcasting has a program-issues public file requirement for
license renewal and for public inspection.''
   He said it may be necessary for the FCC to require telephone
companies to provide a basic antenna service to transmit local
broadcast signals at no charge.
   The FCC is considering proposing that Congress lift
cross-ownership restrictions that prevent telephone companies from
competing with cable TV systems in the phone company service area.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
