<DOCNO> AP890306-0118 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-06-89 2057EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-CatholicPoll     03-06 0305</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Catholic Poll,0312</SECOND>
<HEAD>Poll Shows Massachusetts Catholics Disagree With Vatican</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Roman Catholics responding to a statewide newspaper
poll gave Cardinal Bernard F. Law a favorable rating, but disagreed
with a papal warning that dissenters should not be considered ``good
Catholics.''
   Sixty-one percent of the respondents to a Boston Herald poll of
Massachusetts Catholics held a favorable opinion of the Boston
archbishop, who supports the Vatican's position on social and moral
issues.
   But 71 percent of the poll respondents said they should be able
to dissent from official teachings and be considered good Catholics,
the Herald reported Sunday.
   Twenty percent disagreed, and 9 percent said they did not know
whether dissent meant one could not be a good Catholic.
   During the pope's U.S. visit in 1987, he told the nation's
bishops, ``It is sometimes claimed that dissent from the Magisterium
is totally compatible with being a `good Catholic' and poses no
obstacle to the reception of the sacraments. This is a grave error.''
   Archbishop Rembert G. Weakland of Milwaukee warned the pope then
that an authoritarian style is counterproductive in the United
States. ``The faithful are more inclined to look at the intrinsic
worth of an argument proposed by the teachers in the church than to
accept it on the basis of the authority itself,'' he said.
   The poll of 302 Catholics around the state was conducted Thursday
and Friday for the paper by Opinion Dynamics Corp. of Cambridge. The
Herald said it had a margin of error of 5.6 percent.
   ``Nothing is going to change because of a poll,'' Cardinal
Bernard F. Law said Friday.
   ``His (the pope's) teaching authority doesn't rest on whether or
not people agree with him. Therefore, whatever a poll might show has
no relevance as far as his teaching responsibility and the message
that he teaches.''
</TEXT>
