<FILEID>AP-NR-03-06-89 2012EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-India-Liquor     03-06 0481</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-India-Liquor,0500</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bootleg Liquor Kills 130 in India</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BARODA, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three people were arrested for supplying
home-brewed liquor that killed at least 130 people and left 251 ill
in the only Indian state that bans alcohol, authorities said Monday.
   Doctors said 151 of those 251 hospitalized were critically ill
and probably would die. At least 25 people have been blinded by the
lethal moonshine.
   In addition to the three arrested, several policemen have been
suspended for failing to avert the tragedy in the city of Baroda,
the local government said.
   Baroda is a major industrial center in Gujarat, the only Indian
state where alcohol is banned. The city 560 miles southwest of New
Delhi is home to 2.5 million people.
   United News of India said the son of one supplier and the son of
a prominent local politician are among those killed.
   The liquor normally is brewed from ethyl alcohol, alum and
matured spirits. But this time, industrial methyl alcohol was mixed
to the brew called ``lattha,'' which is sold in plastic sacks for 10
cents. Methyl alcohol paralyzes the central nervous system.
   Press Trust said many victims became dizzy and complained of
nausea and stomach aches before losing consciousness.
   Most survivors were too ill to speak, but one told the Press
Trust of India news agency the only difference he noticed was the
liquor was ``sweeter than normal.''
   A doctor at state-run Sir Siyaji General Hospital said groaning
victims crowded against each other on the floor, on stretchers, and
occasionally three to a bed.
   ``We do not have enough bottles of glucose to even administer
first aid to the victims,'' the doctor said on condition of
anonymity.
   Gujarat's chief minister, Amarsinh Chaudhary, ordered an
investigation and promised action against the police officials who
failed to avert the disaster, the Times of India newspaper reported.
   It said most victims were poor laborers who bought the liquor
Saturday morning after receiving their monthly wages. The first
deaths were reported about midnight Saturday, it said.
   As news of the deaths emerged, police fanned out across Baroda
with loudspeakers blaring warnings about the liquor.
   About 300 people have died in seven illicit liquor cases in
Gujarat in the last decade, United News said. Two previous cases
occurred in Baroda.
   In Norway, meanwhile, a court arraigned two alleged moonshiners
Monday after police raided the largest illegal still ever found in
the country.
   Police discovered a modern facility capable of producing 1,000
liters of high-grade alcohol a day hidden in stalls on a horse farm
in eastern Norway, NTB news agency reported.
   Small-scale bootlegging is not uncommon in Norway, where the
government has imposed a high alcohol tax to discourage drinking.
   A fifth of the cheapest scotch costs $32 and gin $27.60 at state
stores which have a monopoly on alcohol sales.
   The moonshine sells for about a third of the state price.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890306-0120 </DOCNO>
