<HEAD>Conservative Group Trying to Build Support for Tower</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Tower Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A conservative group is mounting a last-ditch
effort to drum up support for Defense Secretary-designate John Tower
with a public relations campaign in several states, a spokesman said
Monday.
   Brent Bozell III, chairman of the Conservative Victory Committee,
said the organization raised $100,000 from supporters to take out
newspaper advertisements and conduct television interviews by
satellite.
   Bozell said the group's lobbying campaign came after President
Bush last week urged conservatives to generate political heat for
Tower, whose nomination has so far failed to garner much enthusiasm
around the nation.
   ``The momentum has clearly swung,'' Bozell said. Bush, meanwhile,
said Monday he was ``sick and tired of the rumors and innuendos''
blocking Tower's confirmation.
   Bozell said his group plans to take out advertisements in
newspapers in Washington and in Dallas.
   It will also arrange for Tower's daughter, Penny Tower Cook, to
appear on televised question-and-answer sessions with reporters in
Texas, Louisiana, Alabama, Connecticut, Rhode Island and Virginia.
   Those are states with Democratic senators who conservatives think
might be persuaded to vote for Tower on the Senate floor, Bozell
said.
   One conservative who has criticized Tower, Paul Weyrich, says he
thinks the Senate has not treated Tower fairly in not allowing him
to confront his accusers.
   Weyrich, president of the Free Congress Foundation, has publicly
criticized Tower's drinking habits and personal conduct.
   ``As much as I want to see him defeated, I don't want to see him
ruined,'' Weyrich told The New York Times in an interview over the
weekend.
   As for support for the nomination, a Los Angeles Times poll taken
last Wednesday and Thursday said 44 percent of those questioned said
the Senate should reject Tower, 35 percent thought he should be
confirmed and 21 percent were unsure. The survey of 1,046 adults had
a margin of error of 4 percentage points.
   But Bozell said he believed ``there is a growing disgust with
Sen. (Sam) Nunn's shenanigans.'' Nunn, D-Ga., chairman of the Senate
Armed Services Committee, has spearheaded the campaign against Tower
in the Senate, where Democrats hold a 55-45 majority. A vote could
come this week.
