<HEAD>Former Klan Leader Apologizes For Picture With Nazi</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BATON ROUGE, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   State Rep. David Duke apologized to the
Louisiana House on Monday for newspaper photos of him shaking hands
with a Nazi, saying it was an attempt to discredit him.
   ``Because of my controversial background, the media saw it as an
opportunity to discredit me,'' Duke told the House, saying he found
the ideology of Nazis ``abhorrent.''
   Duke shook hands with Art Jones, vice chairman of the American
Nazi Party, after he spoke Saturday at the Chicago convention of the
right-wing Populist Party of America.
   About 200 people attended the convention, some of whom identified
themselves as Klansmen and neo-Nazis.
   Duke, elected as a Republican last month, told his colleagues
that he did not know Jones and had no idea he was affiliated with a
Nazi movement.
   Duke's Nazi ties were an issue during the legislative race he won
by a narrow margin Feb. 18. His opponents noted that his 1988
presidential campaign, in which he ran as the Populist Party's
candidate, was managed by a former Nazi leader.
   Only after shaking hands with Jones did the lawmaker discover
that the man was ``a Nazi kook,'' Duke told the House.
   ``My politics in this House will be on a high plane. I call for
equal rights, for non-discrimination. I'm deeply sorry for the
embarrassment this may have caused you,'' he said.
   The House had no reaction to his comments.
