<FIRST>r w AM-Court-Martial     03-06 0608</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Court-Martial,600</SECOND>
<HEAD>Army Warrant Officer Pleads Guilty to Spy Charges</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID PACE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Army warrant officer pleaded guilty to 10
espionage charges at the opening of his court-martial Monday under
an agreement that prohibits the government from seeking the death
penalty.
   Warrant Officer James W. Hall III, 30, of New York City, admitted
that he participated from 1983 to 1988 in a conspiracy to deliver
classified military information to representatives of East Germany
and the Soviet Union.
   Hall's civilian attorney, Vaughn E. Taylor, said Hall is ``truly
sorry for whatever damage he may have done to national security''
will ``throw himself on the mercy of the military judge.''
   Col. Howard C. Eggers, the military judge presiding at the
court-martial at Fort McNair in southwest Washington, did not
immediately accept Hall's guilty plea.
   Under Army regulations, Eggers will hear the prosecution's case
against Hall and defense witnesses before deciding guilt and
punishment. Court officials said the final verdict and sentence
probably will not come before Friday.
   Hall, an intelligence analyst with a top-secret security
clearance, was arrested Dec. 21 near Savannah, Ga., and accused of
delivering exposed film and documents dealing with communications
intelligence and war plans to Warsaw Pact nations.
   At the time of his arrest, Hall was assigned to the 24th Infantry
Division and worked as an intelligence analyst in the Army's G-2
intelligence section. He joined the Army in 1976 and spent most of
his career in Europe working as an analyst of intercepted radio and
telephone traffic and coded messages.
   Under the plea agreement, Hall waived his right to a grand
jury-type hearing to determine if a court-martial was warranted. He
also agreed to be tried by a single military judge, rather than a
panel of officers.
   Hall also agreed to submit to ``unlimited debriefing'' and
polygraph examination by government officials and to testify, if
called, at grand jury proceedings against Huseyin Yildirim, a
Turkish-born, naturalized citizen to whom Hall allegedly passed the
classified information.
   Taylor said through a military spokesman that the defense would
have no comment on Hall's motivation for passing classified
information until after he has been questioned by Eggers during the
closed part of the court-martial.
   The maximum punishment Hall could receive, since the Army agreed
not to seek the death penalty, is life in prison, forefeiture of all
pay and allowances, dishonorable discharge and a fine.
   The plea agreement, however, outlines the sentence that Hall will
receive, unless the presiding judge, who is not permitted to see the
sentencing agreement, imposes a lighter sentence. If the judge
imposes a sentence that is harsher than the one in the agreement,
the agreement will prevail.
   Taylor said Hall will not ``comment at any time now or in the
future'' on the espionage case or his involvement with classified
materials while in the Army. Part of the plea agreement requires
that Hall sign away any profits that might accrue to him in the
future from any publication based on his involvement in the
espionage case.
   A statement of the facts in the espionage case, which Hall told
Eggers was ``mostly written by myself,'' was included in the plea
agreement, but it was not made public.
   Hall's father, James W. Hall Sr., his wife, and one of his
children were in the military courtroom when the court-martial
began. They are expected to testify later in the week in Hall's
behalf.
   ``His family was totally uninvolved and unaware of his
activities,'' Taylor said, ``and Hall will spend the remainder of
his life working to prove that he eventually deserves to be reunited
with his wife and children.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
