<FIRST>r w AM-VeteransBudget     03-06 0411</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Veterans Budget,410</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senator Says VA Getting More Money</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration will seek an extra $300
million from Congress for Veterans Administration medical care this
year, Sen. Frank Murkowski, R-Alaska, said Monday.
   Edward Derwinski, the new head of the VA, had sought additional
money for the VA's medical services branch, which agency officials
have said for months is $600 million to $1 billion short of what it
needs this year.
   Derwinski, who joins the Cabinet as veterans affairs secretary on
March 15, said last week he doubted that the Office of Management
and Budget would approve a request for more money this year.
   Murkowski's announcement came at a hearing of the Senate Veterans
Affairs Committee on the VA's budget for the next fiscal year, which
begins Oct. 1.
   Barbara Clay, spokeswoman for the Office of Management and
Budget, said she was unable to confirm what Murkowski had announced
about the current year. ``The issue has been the timing of such a
request,'' she said.
   Former President Reagan had requested $29.96 billion for the VA
in the coming fiscal year, not much above the $29.77 billion in the
current year. Of those totals, $10.99 billion would be devoted to
medical care in the new year, up from $10.8 billion this year.
   The House Veterans Affairs Committee has asked the Budget
Committee to add $1.3 billion to the agency's budget for next year,
of which $1.1 billion would be for medical care.
   Derwinski has sought an additional $607 million for next year, of
which $512 million would be for medical care. Ms. Clay said it was
premature to discuss final figures for next year, which will depend
on the administration's negotiations with Congress on the overall
budget.
   Agency officials have complained to Congress they have been
forced to raid equipment and supplies accounts to keep paying
salaries.
   As an example of this process, the VA's medical director, Dr.
John Gronvall, told Sen. Dennis DeConcini, D-Ariz., that a new
nursing care installation at Prescott, Ariz., wouldn't open for now
even though complete.
   At the insistence of congressional appropriations committees, the
VA had ``borrowed'' $46 million in funds earmarked for equipping new
facilities to maintain ``a higher level of staff than would
otherwise be the case,'' Gronvall said.
   ``If we get a supplemental appropriation we'll pay that back,''
and the Prescott unit should be able to open later in this fiscal
year, Gronvall said.
</TEXT>
