<FIRST>r i AM-Palme     03-06 0352</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Palme,0364</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Extends Custody for Palme Suspect Despite Criticism</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A court extended the custody Monday for
a man suspected of the 1986 murder of Prime Minister Olof Palme amid
charges that his continued detention was aimed at winning a
confession.
   It was the sixth time that Stockholm's district court granted
prosecutors' requests to hold Christer Pettersson, who was arrested
Dec. 14.
   Pettersson, 41, who has a history of violent crime and mental
problems, is suspected of shooting the four-term prime minister in
downtown Stockholm. Prosecutors have said they have circumstantial
evidence against him but they need further evidence to file charges.
   Astrid Holgersson, an expert in witness psychology at Stockholm
University, charged that Pettersson's detention in solitary
confinement for nearly three months was a ``psychological assault''
that could lead to a ``false confession.''
   Holgersson wrote in the Dagens Nyheter newspaper that such
treatment ``can after a few days lead to serious psychological
disorders ... and a `confession' aimed at getting out of a
psychologically unbearable situation.''
   She said it appeared to be an example of ``malpractice against an
individual by the Swedish judicial system.''
   Pettersson's lawyer Arne Liljeros, who objected to previous
detention orders, raised no protest against the latest court
decision.
   ``The conditions for my client are OK,'' he told Sweden's TT news
agency. ``He is not subjected to any psychological assault.''
   ``We must accept that he is forced to be in jail for a while.
After all, there are circumstances against him,'' Liljeros was
quoted as saying.
   The search for Palme's killer produced the largest manhunt in
Swedish criminal history, centered at first on a suspected
international conspiracy. An $8 million reward offer produced no
breakthroughs.
   Pressure to solve the case prompted senior officials to sidestep
Swedish laws. The former head of the investigation, Hans Holmer, was
dismissed in 1987 amid a dispute with prosecutors over who was in
charge of the case.
   Former Justice Minister Anna-Greta Leijon quit in June when it
was revealed she had supported a private investigation into the
case, which included illegal wiretapping and unauthorized access to
classified documents.
</TEXT>
