<HEAD>Parents March to Protest Private Education Bill</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 5,000 parents of children
attending private schools marched through the city center Monday to
protest an education bill that could severely limit the independence
of private schools.
   Protesters Shouting ``down with the anti-constitutional and
anti-democratic bill,'' marched to the Parliament building, where
they spoke against the proposed legislation.
   If passed, the bill will strengthen the ruling Panhellenic
Socialist Movement's hold over management, financing and day-to-day
running of private schools.
   The legislation, which would also affect foreign private schools
operating in Greece, is slated for discussion in Parliament before
the end of the month, Education Ministry officials said.
   Education Minister George Papandreou, the son of socialist
Premier Andreas Papandreou, has denied the bill aims at abolishing
private schools.
   More than 100,000 pupils attend 486 private institutions in
Greece.
