<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Brazil-Torture     03-06 0191</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Brazil-Torture,0196</SECOND>
<HEAD>Human Rights Activist Kidnapped and Tortured in Brazil</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Italian human rights worker said
Monday he was kidnapped and tortured with lighted cigarettes by
three men who identified themselves as members of a ``death squad.''
   Luis Tenderini, head of the Justice and Peace Commission of the
Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Recife and Olinda, 1,500 miles
northeast of Rio, said he was driving home Saturday night when a car
with three men forced him to stop.
   Tenderini, 46, said the men took him to an isolated area and for
two hours burned him with cigarettes on the chest and forehead and
threatened to kill him.
   Tenderini, who has lived in Brazil for 20 years, said he believed
he was targeted because the commission has been pressing the state
government to investigate the death squad's activities.
   The death squads, made up of off-duty and retired policemen,
first appeared in Brazil during the 1964-85 right-wing military
government. They summarily executed known or suspected criminals and
political opponents of the regime.
   Since 1987, death squads have executed about 500 people in
Recife, according to church estimates.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
