<FIRST>r w AM-US-Laos     03-06 0306</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Laos,330</SECOND>
<HEAD>US Regrets Lao Postponement</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. government said Monday it regrets a
Laotian decision to postpone a joint excavation of the site of the
crash of an American plane that went down during the Indochina war.
   State Department spokesman Charles Redman said he understood the
delay was related to a U.S. government report last week which
criticized Laos' performance in international efforts to curb drug
abuse.
   ``I don't have the exact text of what they said, but I think
that's the sense,'' he said.
   A team of U.S. experts had been scheduled to fly to Laos over the
weekend for the excavation, but Laotian officials delayed the
project, which was part of the U.S. effort to locate the remains of
missing U.S. military personnel.
   ``We regret that the Lao government has temporarily postponed
plans for a joint crash-site excavation, which had been scheduled to
start March 4th,'' Redman said.
   ``The US and Laos have been working together closely to
accelerate cooperation to resolve the issue of Americans still
missing or otherwise unaccounted for in Laos,'' he added.
   Redman noted that four excavations have already been conducted,
going back to February 1985.
   ``We hope that the delay of this fifth excavation will be brief,
and are prepared to send our team of technical experts to Laos
immediately, once the Lao reschedule this important humanitarian
effort,'' he said. ``We also look forward to expanding our dialogue
and cooperation on narcotics matters.''
   The annual U.S. international narcotics control report said there
had been no reduction in opium production in Laos in the previous
year and that heroin refining continues.
   ``And there continues to be information that the extensive
involvement of ... military and civilian government officials in the
narcotics trade suggests this is a matter of de facto government
policy,'' the report said.

</TEXT>
