<FILEID>AP-NR-03-06-89 1658EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Poland     03-06 0578</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland,0596</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government and Opposition Clash on Wage Indexation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH G. SEWARD</BYLINE>
<UNK>Associated Press Writer</UNK>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Government and opposition negotiators had a
stormy session Monday over a Solidarity proposal to reduce 60
percent inflation by tying wages to the cost of living, opposition
economists said.
   The ``round table'' talks on economic and political reform
entered their fifth week with delegates from both sides under
pressure from their leaders to reach agreement by late this month.
   Lech Walesa, who founded Solidarity in 1980 and is trying to get
the union made legal again, said he probably will have his second
meeting with Interior Minister Czeslaw Kiszczak in less than a week
about problems in the talks.
   Members of the Communist Party Central Committee and leaders of
provincial party organizations convened to hear reports on progress.
The meeting was called a ``consultation,'' not a formal party
session, but was expected to produce advice for the government
negotiators.
   Walesa has said he expects new ``political decisions'' intended
to move the talks forward.
   About the indexing question, opposition economist Andrzej
Wielowieyski said: ``We had the impression today the government side
blocked itself. ... We are going to face a very difficult situation
tomorrow. I think the situation is very difficult and very
dangerous,''
   Wielowieyski, a member of the working group on economic issues,
said officials feared indexing would limit the authority of managers
who control pay decisions.
   He said Solidarity leaders decided Sunday the government must
agree to a form of indexation if it expects union agreement to a
package of reforms that includes opposition membership in Parliament.
   ``Our demand for indexing is the indispensable condition,''
Wielowieyski said.
   Solidarity believes wages must be indexed to inflation, at least
temporarily, to give workers some sense of security while economic
reforms are introduced.
   Deputy Premier Ireneusz Sekula said on state television the
government believes some indexing is needed, but ``it has to be
introduced in a prudent manner so it does not disturb ... the
motivating function of pay.''
   Walesa came to Warsaw by train Monday from Gdansk, where he works
as a shipyard electrician, and he met with opposition delegates to
the talks, said Piotr Konopka, a spokesman for the union leader. He
would not give details.
   Working groups on trade union problems and youth issues also
reported no progress Monday.
   Although the union has resolved the issue of how to legalize
Solidarity and other unions, it is stalled on the mechanics of
organizing.
   The youth subgroup had no problems with a proposal to make the
Independent Students Association legal again, but government
negotiators said they want a broader agreement under which the
opposition would endorse a statement on values in rearing children.
   ``Today's discussion of the youth table resembled a mental
hospital rather than negotiations,'' said Andrzej Celinski, leader
of the opposition team.
   Slawomir Wiatr, a government delegate, said it was possible no
agreement would be reached in the youth talks, but added that the
decision to legalize the student association might be made at a
higher level.
   Walesa has expressed optimism in recent days about the
unprecedented talks between communist authorities and the opposition
movement led by Solidarity.
   The talks are aimed at producing a compromise under which the
government would legalize Solidarity and other banned groups in
exchange for their help with a reform program.
   Solidarity, the first independent union movement in the Soviet
bloc, was banned after martial law was imposed in December 1981.
</TEXT>
