<FIRST>r i AM-Israel-Soldier     03-06 0251</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel-Soldier,0259</SECOND>
<HEAD>Security Forces Arrest Arab Who Claims He Kidnapped Soldier</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Security forces have arrested a Palestinian who
allegedly made numerous anonymous telephone calls falsely claiming
he kidnapped a missing Israeli soldier, a military spokesman said
Monday.
   He said the suspect, an unidentified resident of Gaza Strip's
Mughazi refugee camp, made calls to ``several elements'' in which he
demanded the release of all Palestinian prisoners in exchange for
the soldier's freedom.
   Avi Sassportas, 21, has been missing since Feb. 16 when he
disappeared on his way from the army to his home in the coastal city
of Ashdod.
   ``An investigation showed the caller has no connection to the
missing soldier,'' said the military spokesman. ``He made the calls
with the intention of trying to release a friend of his who is in
jail in Israel.''
   He declined to identify the suspect, against whom no official
charges have been filed.
   An anonymous caller last week telephoned prominent Palestinian
lawyer Fayez Abu Rahmeh in Gaza City, the Agence France Presse news
bureau in Jerusalem and Israel Radio. He said Sassportas had been
kidnapped by a group called the Palestinian Arab Army, and promised
to deliver a cassette proving they are holding the soldier.
   No cassette was delivered. The group the caller identified has
not been heard of previously.
   The military spokesman, who by custom is not named, said it was
not yet clear whether the suspect made all the telephone calls.
   ``The matter is still under investigation,'' he said.
</TEXT>
