<FIRST>u a AM-ChannelOne Bjt   03-06 0617</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Channel One, Bjt,0638</SECOND>
<HEAD>Channel One Pitches Jeans, Anti-Drug Message with News at High Schools</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Toi is cq in 6th graf</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto KV1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KNOXVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Paid pitches for jeans, a candy bar and
dandruff shampoo were mixed in with a fast-paced menu of current
events Monday as Channel One, the televised news show for
teen-agers, had its first school day.
   The paid advertising on the show, which is produced by
Knoxville-based Whittle Communications LP, has enraged some
education groups who want Big Business barred from making sales
pitches to students inside the classroom.
   The fourth 30-second commercial was a public service announcement
for the Partnership for a Drug-Free America.
   Students, teachers and parents who witnessed Channel One's debut
at Central High expressed few reservations about the ads.
   `It's fine with me,'' said Shelley Bible, a 14-year-old freshman.
`You get more pressure from other students than you do from the
commercials.''
   Toi McCane, a 17-year-old senior, said the commercials ``are just
the same thing you get on the news at night.''
   The 12-minute program included two minutes of commercials.
   Whittle Communications is a media concern that has developed
magazines and posters that can be used by advertisers to reach
narrowly defined audiences, such as people in doctors' waiting rooms.
   Channel One is Whittle Communications' first venture into
television, and groups such as the National Parent-Teacher
Association and the National Association of Secondary School
Principals are opposing sending commercials into school along with
the news show.
   `They are trying to make it a part of every school day, and this
medium has a much stronger impact than any other,'' said Tari
Marshal, a spokeswoman for the National PTA.
   Christopher Whittle, the company's chairman, said schools can't
afford the equipment and level of programming he is providing as
part of the Channel One project.
   The company has provided each of the six test schools with about
$50,000 worth of television monitors, video recording equipment and
a satellite dish on which they can receive the daily show.
   In addition to Central, the show debuted Monday at Billerica
Memorial High School in Billerica, Mass., Mumford High School in
Detroit, Gahr High School in Cerritos, Calif., and Eisenhower Middle
School in Kansas City, Kan.
   The sixth test school, Withrow High School in Cincinnati, was
closed Monday by bad weather.
   If the test proves successful, Whittle hopes to expand it
nationally to as many as 8,000 schools in the fall of 1990.
   In exchange for the equipment, the schools agree to run the news
show once each school day.
   After the show began with flashy graphics, two youthful anchors
read headlines illustrated with purchased film footage about the
Eastern Airlines strike, the battle over John Tower's nomination as
secretary of defense and life as a Soviet teen-ager.
   The show's last segment dealt with the controversy over Channel
One itself.
   In Connie Wilkes's senior homeroom class, all 20 students
appeared to follow the show intently, fidgeting only during the
shampoo commercial.
   Whittle gave the show high marks for content, but said the
broadcast's pacing needed some work and his anchors needed to
``loosen up a bit.''
   He said the complaints had not deterred any advertisers who have
signed up for the test run which will involve 25 shows over the next
seven weeks.
   Eight advertisers have signed up, he said, and he is courting
four more. No show will have more than two minutes of commercials,
Whittle said.
   Earl Hoffmeister, superintendent of the Knox County public school
system, said he thinks the show's educational value was worth two
minutes of paid ads. Besides, he said, ``kids don't pay a lot of
attention to commercials anyway.''
</TEXT>
