<FILEID>AP-NR-03-06-89 2316EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-WrightInvestigation     03-06 0343</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Wright Investigation,340</SECOND>
<HEAD>Congressman Says Republican Group Trying to Sway Vote on Wright</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER DIXON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Texas Democrat said Monday that Republican
``propaganda terrorists'' are trying to intimidate GOP members of
the House ethics committee into voting against House Speaker Jim
Wright and ought to be punished.
   Rep. Ron Coleman of El Paso said the ``righteous right'' is
operating its lobbying effort from within the House and is behind
``a mailing insisting Republicans have to be unified and anything
short of censure or expulsion would be a whitewash.'' He said, ``It
sounds like a vigilante group ... out of the last century with a
`hang him regardless of the evidence' mentality.''
   The ethics committee has been meeting behind closed doors over a
series of ethics charges against Wright, including allegations he
used his office for personal financial gain. An independent counsel
has spent nine months investigating the charges.
   Wright has denied violating any law or rule of the House,
although he has conceded he might have done some things differently
if given the chance to do them over.
   The panel, evenly split with Republican and Democratic members,
met to consider the independent counsel's findings last week, and
the outcome of the investigation may be known sometime this week.
   Speaking on the House floor Thursday, Coleman decried the actions
of a number of Wright's Republican opponents, including Rep. Newt
Gingrich of Georgia.
   Recent news accounts ``make it clear this small band of
propaganda terrorists has been plotting all along, on a series of
conspiracies to discredit Speaker Wright and other Democrats,''
Coleman said. ``Moreover, they are cynically trying to intimidate
Republican members of the ethics committee into finding some
complaint against the speaker to be valid.''
   Coleman said the group's efforts are ``tantamount to jury
tampering and it's criminal.'' He is proposing the House adopt
sanctions, such as censure or expulsion, for members found to have
improperly influenced members of the ethics committee.
   Gingrich did not respond immediately to requests to his office
for an interview.
</TEXT>
