<FILEID>AP-NR-03-06-89 2133EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Lebanon     03-06 0651</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon,0673</SECOND>
<HEAD>Christian Troops Patrol Waters</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RODEINA KENAAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Helicopter gunships and navy gunboats of
the army's Christian command patrolled Lebanon's territorial waters
under Druze rocket fire Monday to prevent foreign merchant ships
from using illegal port facilities operated by feuding militias.
   The move, aimed at choking off the main revenues of Christian and
Moslem private armies, has triggered a political crisis in the
Moslem camp.
   Police said neither of the army's two French-built Gazelle
gunships was hit when militiamen of Druze warlord Walid Jumblatt
fired rocket launchers near the port of Jiye, 15 miles south of
Beirut.
   To underscore Moslem objections to the Christian patrols, the
Moslem army command ordered the closing of a Green Line crossing
point linking the capital's Christian and Moslem sectors only one
week after rival military forces reopened it.
   A communique issued by the command of Maj. Gen. Sami Khatib, who
heads Moslem army units in west Beirut, said the decision to close
the crossing at Beirut port was made on orders from Acting Prime
Minister Salim Hoss' Moslem cabinet.
   The communique said the Christians' sea and air patrols were
``provocative acts.''
   The makeshift harbor at Jiye has been the main sea outlet for the
Druze community, a Moslem sect based mainly in the Chouf mountains,
since they captured it from the Christians in 1985.
   A Defense Ministry communique said foreign ships heading for
Lebanon have been warned not to enter any of the militia-controlled
harbors along the Mediterranean country's 110-mile coastline.
   The ban was ordered Sunday by Gen. Michel Aoun, who heads the
Christian military cabinet vying for power with Hoss' Syrian-backed
government.
   It was part of Aoun's campaign to restore state authority, eroded
by 14 years of civil war in which Christian and Moslem militias took
over many government functions.
   The militias use the ports to bring in arms and supplies as well
as imported goods sold in the areas they control, depriving the
state treasury of an estimated $100 million a year in customs duties.
   ``We're not forcibly shutting militia harbors or blockading them.
... We are merely blocking foreign ships from going there,'' a
Defense Ministry spokesman said on condition of anonymity.
   ``If a ship insists on violating the ban, it will be seized and
forced to sail into Beirut port to question its captain before
beginning legal procedures,'' said the spokesman.
   He listed five legal ports _ Beirut, Jounieh and Tripoli north of
the capital and Sidon and Tyre to the south.
   To supervise the new ban, Aoun revived a maritime authority made
up of representatives from the public works ministry, the navy, air
force, police and the customs department.
   Hoss said Monday that the ban could undermine ``the positive mood
that has lately emerged about a possible end to Lebanon's plight.''
   He was referring to mediation efforts by an Arab League committee
set up in January to help resolve a constitutional crisis that has
left the country without a president for 162 days and threatens to
formalize its de facto partition into Christian and Moslem cantons.
   President Amin Gemayel appointed Aoun to head an interim cabinet
when his 6-year-term expired Sept. 22 without a successor being
elected.
   Moslems refused to accept Aoun's appointment and pledged
allegiance to Hoss, who governed during the Amin presidency.
   In another development Monday, an associate of Roger Tamraz, a
Lebanese international banker, said Tamraz was kidnapped Feb. 19 and
is being held for ransom.
   But some Beirut newspapers say the 48-year-old Tamraz fled after
a run on his bank and after accusations he embezzled $200 million.
Police said they know nothing about his reported disappearance.
   Tamraz's spokesman in West Beirut could not be contacted by
telephone.
   Until recently, Tamraz was chairman of Bank Al-Mashrek, Lebanon's
second largest bank, which is involved in a liquidity crisis with
several subsidiaries, including banks in Switzerland, France, Jordan
and Qatar.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
