<FILEID>AP-NR-03-06-89 1727EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-SovietStrike     03-06 0279</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet Strike,0285</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet Coal Miners End Five-Day Strike</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 100 coal miners ended a five-day strike
Monday after the government agreed to correct their pay system, a
dissident reported.
   Sergei Grigoryants, a Moscow-based journalist, said sources in
the Ural Mountain city of Vorkuta reported that 115 miners had been
striking while underground since Thursday and began a hunger strike
two days ago.
   Vorkuta, with a population of 90,000, is 1,200 miles northeast of
Moscow. It is in the Pechora Basin, one of the Soviet Union's major
coal mining regions that in 1985 produced 28 million metric tons of
bituminous coal.
   Workers in the Northern Mine began the strike to protest
increased work orders, to demand replacement of the facility's
director and chief economist and a reduction of the management
staff, according to Grigoryants. He said the strikers also demanded
changes in the salary disbursement system.
   A group of supporters, who called their organization Solidarity
after the independent union movement in Poland, pressed the miners'
case with authorities while the strikers remained underground,
according to Grigoryants.
   He said Soviet Coal Minister Mikhail I. Shchadov arrived in
Vorkuta Saturday, negotiated with the strikers and promised to
partially meet their demands including paying them 158,000 rubles
($254,800) to compensate for problems in the salary system.
   Grigoryants said the miners announced the end of the strike on
Monday.
   The Soviet government has traditionally claimed that strikes are
inconsistent with the Communist system that places priority on the
interests of workers. But last year there were strikes of an
unprecedented scale and length in Armenia and Azerbaijan in the
dispute over control of the Nagorno-Karabakh region of Azerbaijan.
</TEXT>
