<DOCNO> AP890306-0148 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-06-89 2221EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Time-Warner-Congress     03-06 0432</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Time-Warner-Congress,430</SECOND>
<HEAD>Metzenbaum Seeks Review of Merger</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY ARNOLD</BYLINE>
<HEAD>Associated Press Writer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Howard Metzenbaum urged the Justice
Department to review the antitrust implication of the Time-Warner
merger because he said cable television customers could be big
losers in the merger between the media giants.
   Metzenbaum, D-Ohio, said there were ``strong indications'' that
the $18 billion merger between Time Inc. and Warner Communications
could substantially reduce competition and diversity in the
communications and entertainment field, particularly in the cable
television industry.
   ``Such a development is especially disturbing in light of a
continuing trend toward further concentration and reduced
possibilities for meaningful competition in cable television,''
Metzenbaum said in a letter to Charles Rule, the assistant attorney
general in charge of the Justice Department's antitrust division.
   ``I...urge you to undertake a careful and thorough review of this
proposal,'' said Metzenbaum, chairman of the Senate Judiciary
subcommittee on antitrust, monopolies and business rights.
   Vickie Togans, a staff assistant in Rule's office, said the
letter had not been received there Monday.
   Metzenbaum said the merger, which was announced Saturday, would
link two of the world's leading media and entertainment
conglomerates, creating a company worth $18 billion.
   Time publishes Time, People, Sports Illustrated and Fortune
magazines, and owns Home Box Office, the nation's largest pay cable
service, along with HBO's sister cable service, Cinemax. Time also
owns American Television and Communications Corp., the nation's
second largest cable system.
   Warner Communications owns the Warner Bros. movie and television
studios, Warner Records and Lorimar Telepictures Corp., along with
Warner Cable Communications, the fifth largest cable system in the
nation.
   Metzenbaum said less than 1 percent of the 8,000 communities
nationwide served by cable have more than one cable system. ``Cable
is an unregulated monopoly throughout the entire country,'' he said.
   He said a Time-Warner merger could extend the dominance of the
larger multisystem cable operators over small cable companies.
   ``With the acquisition of Warner Cable systems, there is an even
greater incentive for Time to deny competing technologies its
existing programming _ and the new programming which Time-Warner is
expected to create.''
   ``It is this ability to control both the conduit for programming
(the cable wire) and the content of the programming (through MSO
equity interest in programming ventures) that poses the greatest
threat to consumers,'' Metzenbaum said.
   ``The absence of competition in the delivery of cable programming
means that consumers have no protection against unrestrained rate
hikes. The de facto editorial control which MSOs can exercise over
new programming threatens diversity of information and entertainment
sources available to cable viewers,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890306-0149 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-06-89 1759EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Soviet-Latvia     03-06 0566</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Latvia,0585</SECOND>
<HEAD>Actors Protest in Latvia, Some Detained</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RIGA, U.S.S.R. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police detained some of Latvia's leading
actors Monday after they protested an anticipated crackdown on
independent-minded journalists.
   In response, the actors canceled at least one performance.
   Ulolis Dumpis, one of those detained, said they demonstrated for
an hour outside Communist Party headquarters in Riga, capital of the
small Baltic state the Soviet Union absorbed in 1940 along with
Estonia and Lithuania.
   As the protest was ending, a police officer told the group of
about 50 people it was illegal because they had no permit, Dumpis
said.
   He said the officer gave them three minutes to disperse, but
other police moved in almost immediately and started taking people
away in two groups.
   About 15 were in his group but he could not tell how many were in
the other, the actor said. They were held for about two hours and
released without being charged, he said.
   Actors of the Latvian National Theater, Youth Theater, Theater of
Opera and Ballet and the Artistic Theater met after the detentions
to decide whether to perform.
   Aivars Bogdanovics told about 200 performers in the small hall of
the National Theater of the day's events, and they decided to cancel
the performance there.
   Dumpis spoke to about 700 people in the theater's cream-and-red
large hall and said the actors decided the play in that hall should
go on.
   Those attending the meeting were in 17th century garb for the
performance of ``Once Upon a Time There Was a Rider'' about a
struggle for peasant rights 300 years ago.
   Members of the Latvian People's Front, a grassroots group
campaigning for greater autonomy, said scheduled performances also
were given at the other theaters.
   Actors who protested outside headquarters said they expected the
authorities to act this week against up to 16 journalists working
for state television who have been accused of creating ill-feeling
between ethnic Latvians and ethnic Russians.
   Of Latvia's 2.6 million inhabitants, 54 percent are Latvian and
33 percent Russian.
   Two television journalists, Velta Purinya and Mara Grunte, said
they were told privately they would be disciplined.
   Ms. Purinya, a member of both the Communist Party and People's
Front, said she was told the nightly public affairs program Panorama
``whips up bad feelings between Russians and Latvians'' by showing
film of demonstrations and reading letters from viewers.
   Editors of the People's Front weekly Atmoda said censors would
not let them publish an article Monday about the arrests of young
Latvians who protested conscription into the army. Atmoda appeared
Monday with pictures of scissors pasted where the article would have
been.
   Several hundred people gathered at downtown Riga's Freedom
Monument on Monday for a rally by the Movement for the National
Independence of Latvia. The rally honored Oscars Kalpaks, who
commanded the army of independent Latvia between the two world wars.
   Latvia, Estonia and Lithuania were taken over by the Soviet Union
one year after Stalin's pact with Hitler assigned the region to the
Kremlin sphere of influence.
   In January, Latvian party Janis Vagris expressed alarm about
tension in the republic, saying even the party felt the effects of
``ethnic stratification.''
   Political ferment in the Baltic states has increased in the more
liberal atmosphere fostered by Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
Some residents say openly their want their homelands to be
indpependent again.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
