<FIRST>r w AM-Thornburgh-Trip     03-06 0311</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Thornburgh-Trip,320</SECOND>
<HEAD>AG Headed to Latin America</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Attorney General Dick Thornburgh left Monday
for Latin America to talk with the leaders of three nations about
how to curb the flow of drugs from their countries.
   A political assassination in Bogota last week prompted Thornburgh
to delay, until the end of his trip, a visit with Colombian
President Virgilio Barco, department officials said.
   Thornburgh had originally been scheduled to leave Washington on
Sunday for Columbia, the first stop on his fact-finding trip that
also includes visits to Bolivia and Peru.
   But the U.S. ambassador in Bogota recommended that Thornburgh
delay his visit to Colombia following Friday's assassination of the
leader of a leftist political party and subsequent street rioting,
said officials, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   David Runkel, the attorney general's spokesman, acknowledged that
security concerns prompted the schedule change.
   Thornburgh is now scheduled to visit Colombia on Thursday but the
stop in Bogota will depend on ``how things settle out'' there, said
one official.
   Thornburgh, accompanied his executive assistant, Robert S. Ross
Jr., and Jack Lawn, head of the Drug Enforcement Administration, is
scheduled to meet Tuesday with Bolivian President Paz Estenssoro.
   While in Bolivia, Thornburgh is scheduled to address a meeting of
the United Nations Fund for Drug Abuse and Control.
   On Wednesday, Thornburgh is set to meet in Peru with President
Alan Garcia and interior minister Armando Villanueva.
   The meeting in Colombia, originally set for Monday, will include
discussions with leaders of that nation's defense department and the
national police.
   ``This trip has been scheduled to allow me to talk directly with
leaders of these nations about our cooperative drug law enforcement
efforts,'' Thornburgh said in a statement.
   ``As the United States steps up our efforts to reduce demand for
illegal drugs, we must also push ahead with the reduction of
supply,'' Thornburgh said.
</TEXT>
