<DOCNO> AP890306-0154 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-06-89 2022EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-HeflinProfile     03-06 0459</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Heflin Profile,460</SECOND>
<HEAD>With AM-Tower</HEAD>
<HEAD>Heflin No Stranger To Partisan Battles Over Presidential Appointments</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID PACE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In becoming the first Democrat to support John
Tower, President Bush's nominee for secretary of defense, Alabama
Sen. Howell Heflin followed the rule he always applies to
presidential appointments.
   ``My general approach is that the president is entitled to have
his appointments'' unless it can be proved ``that the person is
flawed or that he would be a detriment to the country,'' Heflin said
last week after meeting with Bush to discuss the Tower nomination.
   In the case of Tower, Heflin said he was not convinced after
reading the FBI reports that the former Texas senator has a drinking
problem that would disqualify him from serving in the nation's top
defense post.
   Had Tower been nominated for a lifetime judgeship, Heflin might
well have voted against confirmation. But he said the fact that the
secretary of defense serves at the pleasure of the president makes
Bush responsible and accountable for Tower's conduct.
   ``It is the president's cabinet,'' Heflin said, ``not Congress'
cabinet.''
   Being at the center of a partisan battle over a presidential
appointee is nothing new for Heflin, a 67-year-old ex-Marine and
former Alabama chief justice who was former President Reagan's most
consistent Democratic support in the Senate.
   As a member of the Senate Judiciary Committee, Heflin frequently
found himself holding the balance of power when controversial Reagan
appointments divided the panel along partisan lines.
   His vote in committee against Reagan's nomination of Robert H.
Bork to the Supreme Court in 1987 helped persuade other Southern
Democrats to oppose Bork, who eventually was rejected by the full
Senate.
   Heflin also cast the deciding vote on the only other Reagan
appointees rejected by the Judiciary Committee, the nomination of
William Bradford Reynolds to the third-ranking post in the Justice
Department and the nomination of Jefferson B. Sessions III to a
federal judgeship in south Alabama.
   Heflin was widely criticized in his home state for opposing both
Bork and Sessions, but his popularity does not appear to have waned
in Alabama despite the increasingly tendency in recent years of the
state's voters to support Republican candidates.
   During his first Senate campaign in 1978, Heflin was so popular
that then-Gov. George C. Wallace decided not to challenge him.
Heflin carried all but five of Alabama's 69 counties in the
Democratic primary, and won move than 90 percent of the general
election vote.
   He was re-elected in 1984 with 63 percent of the vote over a
conservative Republican congressman. His only announced challenger
in 1990 is state Sen. Bill Cabiness of Birmingham, a businessman who
chaired the state's delegation to the Republican convention that
nominated Bush for president.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
