<FIRST>u i AM-Lebanon-Iran 1stLd-Writethru a0604 03-06 0623</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon-Iran, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0604,0640</SECOND>
<HEAD>Iran Making Economic Breakthrough In Lebanon</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUB final two grafs, 20-21, `A 10-yard...' CORRECTING size of
carpet.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA ABU-NASR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Iranian trade fair has successfully
introduced merchandise from the Islamic state to the Lebanese
market, drawing 100,000 visitors and selling $60,000 worth of goods
a day.
   ``Many deals have been struck between Iranian companies and
Lebanese businessmen, both Christian and Moslem,'' said Abbas
Zaferian, director of the ``Second Trade Exhibition of the Islamic
Republic of Iran.''
   ``I cannot give you a final figure, but I can assure you that the
number is large,'' he added.
   Zaferian said 70 companies are participating in the fair that
opened Feb. 20 at a hotel in a Syrian-controlled district of west
Beirut. It ends Tuesday.
   He refused to say whether the fair had political motives, such as
supporting the 1 million Shiite Moslems who make up Lebanon's
largest single sect. ``I only answer questions related to the
commercial aspect,'' Zaferian said.
   Iran and its mainly Shiite Moslem population back the Hezbollah,
or Party of God, militia which seeks to set up an Islamic state
modeled on Iran in southern Lebanon.
   Hezbollah intermittently fought fierce battles from April until
January against Amal, its Syrian-backed rival. After 500 people were
killed, Iran and Syria brokered a truce that currently is holding.
   At the entrance to the fair, Iranian flags and huge portraits of
revolutionary patriarch Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini contrast sharply
with other events at the seaside hotel: a cheese and wine party and
a Greek night.
   Cheap prices make the Iranian goods attractive not only to
Shiites, but also to other low-income and middle-income groups.
   People flock to the exhibition, where an air conditioner is
priced at $90, a gas stove at $39 and a pair of tennis shoes costs
$2.
   The fair may mark a breakthrough for Iranian-made products in
Lebanon, despite their mediocre quality.
   Nobody seemed to mind the long wait to park in the hotel's
spacious grounds, or meticulous security checks.
   ``It's worth it. I cannot afford to pay $40 for a pair of jeans.
Here, it's only $7,'' said a woman who identified herself as Soha, a
Sunni Moslem. ``The quality may not be the same as French designer
ones, but we're living through hard days and jeans are jeans.''
   A fair salesman said Iran's first trade exhibition in Lebanon
last year provided an opportunity to assess the market.
   `That was just an exhibition. People could not purchase any of
the products. But it helped make this year's exhibition
successful,'' said the salesman, who refused to give his name.
   Cars assembled in Iran were popular, with prices ranging from
$4,200 for a Renault 5 to $13,000 for a Range Rover.
   A government education stand was one of the fair's biggest,
boasting a bookshop, a children's corner and a video room playing an
Iranian film, ``The Eagles.'' The film showed Iranian jets mounting
an attack against bases in Iraq. Jubilant crowds watching the movie
shouted ``Allaho Akbar!'' (``God is Great!'') as the jets unleashed
their bombs.
   Wealthier people also attended the fair, but for different goods.
   ``I came here to look at the silk carpets and buy some caviar and
pistachio nuts,'' said a woman whose hand glittered with diamond
rings. These luxuries are the only Iranian goods imported to Lebanon
regularly, although the trade is minimal.
   A silk carpet runner measuring a bit more than 5 feet by 3 feet
cost $1,827, and two pounds of caviar sold for $200.
   ``The caviar shelves were wiped (clean) during the first few
days,'' said Zaferian. ``People would buy it here for $200 and sell
it outside for at least double the price.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
