<FIRST>r i AM-Rushdie-Foreign 1stLd-Writethru a0699 03-06 0697</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Rushdie-Foreign, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0699,0718</SECOND>
<HEAD>Britain Wants Stronger Soviet Stand on Rushdie</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERT 6 grafs after 15th pvs, `He said...' UPDATING with Iranian,
Swedish remarks after Swedish diplomat returns. Picks up 16th graf pvs,
In Jerusalem ...</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Britain-Moslems, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRENCE PETTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Britain wants the Soviet Union to take a
stronger position against Iran for Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini's
calls for the death of novelist Salman Rushdie, the British foreign
secretary said Monday.
   Sir Geoffrey Howe said he and Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard
Shevardnadze discussed the matter during private talks Monday in
Vienna, where both are attending East-West talks on reducing
conventional forces in Europe.
   ``I left Mr. Shevardnadze no doubt of our view that the
principles involved in that problem are of universal application,''
Howe told a news conference.
   Howe said he told Shevardnadze ``there can be no justification
for (Iran's) incitement to murder ... and no justification for
seeking to impair the freedom of speech in a country like ours.''
   Howe said he also told Shevardnadze ``that that view was a view
which should commend itself to both halves of a common European
house.''
   Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev has used the term ``common
European house'' to portray Western Europe and the East bloc as
having common interests because of their geographical proximity.
   Howe said, ``There was no question of any mediation discussion on
either side,'' indicating the question of a possible Soviet
go-between role did not come up.
   The 12 European Community nations, angered by Iran's threats,
have recalled their ambassadors from Tehran.
   Rushdie is a British citizen. Many Moslems charge that his novel,
``The Satanic Verses,'' blasphemes their faith. Khomeini, Iran's
revolutionary and religious patriarch, urged Moslems to hunt down
and kill Rushdie.
   Howe did not say how Shevardnadze responded at their talks on
Monday.
   However, his remarks indicated he is not satisfied with the
Kremlin's stance on the threats against Rushdie.
   Moscow has said Western countries are justified in their
``indignation'' over the matter. But Soviet officials, while not
condoning the death decree, also said Khomeini may have felt he had
to denounce Rushdie under Islamic teachings.
   Shevardnadze last week met with Iranian officials in Tehran, and
later the Soviets offered to help cool the strife between Iran and
Western nations.
   In a midday speech on Monday, Shevardnadze mentioned the dispute
and said no nation should try to gain an advantage from the rift.
   He said, in calling for international cooperation to improve
conditions in the Middle East: ``There should be no playing on any
contradictions _ whether it is Israel's conflict with the Arabs or
the difficulties in the West's relations with Iran.''
   Sweden's ambassador to Iran, Hakan Granqvist, said after
returning to Tehran that Rushdie's novel was a serious insult to
Moslem beliefs, state-run Tehran radio, monitored in Cyprus,
reported Monday.
   Granqvist was recalled for consultations after Khomeini's death
threat against Rushdie.
   The radio quoted Granqvist as saying at a meeting with Deputy
Foreign Minister Mohammad Javad Larijani, ``In the West, the
consciousness is gradually arising that the publication is a serious
insult to Moslem beliefs, and many (Western) writers and politicians
now realize this.''
   The Swedish Embassy also represents British interests in Iran.
   Iran is due to announce Tuesday whether it will break off
relations with Britain over the Rushdie affair.
   Iran's official Islamic Republic News Agency, also monitored in
Cyprus, quoted Larijani as telling Granqvist, ``The only solution to
this crisis is respect in the West for Moslems and their belief.''
   In Jerusalem, in an interview published in the newspaper Maariv
on Monday, Israel's chief Ashkenazi rabbi, Avraham Shapira, asked
for a national ban on Rushdie's book, saying it threatens
Moslem-Jewish relations and world peace.
   Ashkenazi Jews are of European heritage and comprise almost half
of Israel's Jewish population. Chief Rabbi Mordechai Eliahu
represents Jews of Middle Eastern heritage. He was unavailable for
comment.
   On Sunday, Palestinian extremist Ahmed Jibril vowed in Damascus,
Syria, to make every effort to kill Rushdie ``in defense of
religion, God, and his prophet (Mohammed).'' He said he would use
his Popular Front for the Liberation of Palestine-General Command to
carry out the threat.
</TEXT>
