<FIRST>u i AM-Paraguay     03-06 0656</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Paraguay,0676</SECOND>
<HEAD>Extradition Approved of Argentines Accused of Stealing Children</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELIZABETH LOVE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ASUNCION, Paraguay (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court issued extradition
orders Monday for two Argentine couples accused of taking four
children from parents who were arrested and presumed executed by
security forces a decade ago.
   During nearly two years of house arrest in Asuncion, the couples
appealed lower court rulings and argued they were victims of
persecution by the Argentine government of President Raul Alfonsin.
   The court ruling said: ``It was not proven that both couples are
persecuted politically, and in accordance with the extradition
treaty signed by Paraguay in 1889 in Montevideo, the appeals are
rejected.''
   ``After two years, this is very good news,'' said Raul Quijano,
Argentina's ambassador.
   In a domestic political development, Paraguay's main opposition
party filed documents Monday seeking recognition that would allow it
to enter national elections set for May 1.
   Domingo Laino, president of the Authentic Radical Liberal Party,
indicated it still might boycott the elections unless the
provisional government of Gen. Andres Rodriguez changes voting laws
and procedures. Rodriguez overthrew President Alfredo Stroessner, a
general who had ruled since 1954, in a coup Feb. 3.
   The kidnapping case strained relations between the neighboring
South America countries. Ambassador Quijano was recalled for for
several months last year after Attorney General Clotildo Jimenez
Benitez urged the Supreme Court to deny extradition.
   Jimenez was dismissed Friday, a month after the coup against
Stroessner.
   Argentine justice and human rights officials accused Maj.
Norberto Bianco and retired police official Samuel Miara and their
wives of taking children of alleged subversives who were imprisoned
at the Campo de Mayo army base outside Buenos Aires in the late
1970s.
   Many children disappeared in similar fashion during the so-called
``dirty war'' against leftist subversion conducted by the military
dictatorship of 1976-83.
   Bianco was a doctor at the army base and Miara was a police
intelligence officer. Both fled to Paraguay in April 1986, claiming
they would not receive a fair trial in Argentina.
   Neither couple was required to appear in court Monday. Bianco
told The Associated Press by telephone he learned about the decision
from a television newscast.
   ``We know the extradition ruling is for me and my wife, and that
the situation of the kids still must be resolved,'' said Bianco, who
like Miara claims he is his children's natural father. ``We don't
know anything for sure yet.''
   Bianco said he assumed his son Pablo, 11, and daughter Carolina,
12, would be allowed to accompany him and his wife, Susana, to
Argentina. Ambassador Quijano said he expected the order to be
carried out within within two weeks.
   ``The kids are resigned, very crestfallen, but they have a great
strength of spirit and they think that in Argentina they will be
able to put things right,'' Bianco said.
   Grandmothers of the Plaza de Mayo, an Argentine human rights
group, claims Miara's 11-year-old twin sons Gonzalo Javier and
Matias Angel are Gustavo and Martin Rosetti Ross, whose parents were
arrested during the ``dirty war.''
   Their mother was never seen again but the father, Gustavo
Rosetti, survived, was released and now is a lawyer in Buenos Aires.
   No one answered the telephone Monday at the office of Miara's
lawyer.
   Asked for comment Monday, a spokeswoman for the Grandmothers said
they expected the decision but had no formal notification of it. She
would not identify the supposed biological parents of the Bianco
children.
   The group was set up in 1977 to trace the children who
disappeared and were presumed killed in the anti-leftist campaign.
Investigators for Alfonsin's civilian government say at least 8,960
people were killed but human rights groups put the toll nearer
30,000.
   According to the Grandmothers, about 300 babies were born in
captivity or taken with their mothers to clandestine detention
centers. The group has helped reunite about 50 children with their
biological families since Alfonsin took office in December 1983.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
