<FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     03-06 0589</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0603</SECOND>
<HEAD>Widespread Snow In East, With Flooding In Appalachians</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A strong weather system spread heavy snow from the Plains over
sections of the Ohio Valley, and heavy rain caused flooding in the
Appalachians.
   Snowfall ended over Missouri after more than a foot fell in some
areas. Lebanon got 16 inches and 15 inches fell ar Marshfield. The
11 inches at St. Louis was the 11th heaviest snowfall on record, and
the fourth heaviest for March, the National Weather Service said.
   In Arkansas, snow and ice accumulations piled up 12 to 14 inches
deep in Benton County and 8 to 12 inches in Washington County.
   In central and southern Illinois, 6 to 8 inches fell at
Taylorville and Litchfield, with 6 inches in Moultrie county.
Northern Indiana got 2 to 4 inches.
   Freezing rain and sleet mixed with the snow from southern
Illinois to southern Indiana and Ohio. A layer of ice three-quarters
of an inch thick accumulated on trees at Clay City, Ill. In southern
Ohio, ice on electrical lines caused scattered power outages.
   Snow also fell on southern Pennsylvania, sections of New Jersey
and southeastern New York.
   A mixture of rain and sleet fell just south of the snow area.
   A line of strong showers and thunderstorms developed over western
sections of the Carolinas. Near Mooresville, N.C., intense
thunderstorms damaged several homes, overturned cars and blew down
fences.
   Heavy rain that fell over much of the Ohio and Tennessee valleys
during the last couple days caused rivers to rise in Kentucky, West
Virginia, Tennessee and Ohio. West Virginia had flash flooding, and
many northern streams were expected to crest above flood stage
during the night. The Kentucky River was rising at a rate of a foot
and a half an hour in many areas and was expected to crest during
the evening over eastern Kentucky.
   In Tennessee, roads were flooded in Grundy and Marion counties.
   Light lake-effect snow fell along the western shores of Lake
Michigan in northern Wisconsin.
   Light rain and fog spread along the northern and central Pacific
Coast.
   Record lows were reported Monday at Austin, Texas, 27;
Bryan-College Station, Texas, 29; Corpus Christi, Texas, 29; Fort
Worth, Texas, 20; Galveston, Texas, 27; Grand Island, Neb., 10 below
zero; Houston, 25; Huron, S.D., 17 below; Lake Charles, La., 25;
Midland, Texas, 15; Port Arthur, Texas, 24; Shreveport, La., 24;
Victoria, Texas; and Wichita Falls, Texas, 8.
   Temperatures around the nation at 2 p.m. EST ranged from 9
degrees at Limestone, Maine, to 85 at Fort Myers, Fla. Monday's low
for the Lower 48 states was 18 degrees below zero at Ord, Neb.
   Tuesday's forecast called for showers over Virginia and the
Carolinas, the Tennessee Valley and the lower half of the Florida
Peninsula; widespread rain along the northern and central Pacific
Coast and the northern and central Intermountain region between the
Sierra Nevada and the Rockies; and snow from southern Pennsylvania
to New Jersey and the southern New England coast.
   Highs in the teens and 20s were predicted from the upper Great
Lakes to northern sections of the Ohio Valley, the lower Great Lakes
and New England; in the 30s and 40s from Washington state to the
northern Rockies, the northern and central Plains, Oklahoma, eastern
Texas, much of the Mississippi Valley, the Tennessee Valley and the
middle Atlantic Coast; in the 70s over the southern Florida
Peninsula; in the 70s and 80s over Southern California; and
generally in the 50s and 60s over the rest of the nation.
</TEXT>
