<FIRST>r i AM-Czechoslovakia     03-06 0330</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Czechoslovakia,0340</SECOND>
<HEAD>Meeting Canceled In Controversy Over Hajek</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The International Helsinki Federation
canceled a meeting Monday with the government in Prague after
authorities refused to accept former Czechoslovak Foreign Minister
Jiri Hajek as part of its six-man delegation.
   The Czechoslovak state news agency CTK later said the delegation
will meet Tuesday with officials of the Committee of the
Czechoslovak Public for Human Rights and Humanitarian Cooperation
and representatives of the Czechoslovak Peace Committee.
   It said a meeting at the Ministry of Justice and the passport and
visa authority of the Interior Ministry could not take place because
the delegation's condition for holding the talks was unacceptable to
the Czechoslovak side.
   CTK did not spell out the condition.
   The Vienna-based Helsinki Federation monitors human rights in
East Europe. Its delegation, led by Karl Johannes von Schwarzenberg,
was scheduled to meet with officials in Prague to discuss human
rights in Czechoslovakia.
   Hajek is chairman of the Czechoslovak Helsinki Committee, a
member of the Federation. He helped lead Czechoslovakia's 1968
reform movement that was crushed that year by a Soviet-led invasion
and was a signer of the Charter 77 document on human rights in
Czechoslovakia.
   Von Schwarzenberg told Czechoslovak Premier Ladislav Adamec in a
letter made available to news media, ``We wish to express our
disappointment and grave concern about the refusal of Czechoslovak
ministers to meet with us.''
   He referred to the authorities' rejection of Hajek as a member of
the Federation delegation and the Federation's cancellation of
Monday's meeting.
   In behalf of the Federation, von Schwarzenberg protested ``police
brutality in Czechoslovakia against citizens engaged in peaceful
demonstrations during August, October and January.''
   He protested the trials and sentencing of rights activists in
Prague, including prominent playwright Vaclav Havel and Jana
Petrova, both members of the Czechoslovak Helsinki Committee.
   The Federation demanded immediate release of all political
prisoners, guarantees of due process, and an end to using visa and
passport regulations as a punishment for political activities.
</TEXT>
