<FILEID>AP-NR-03-06-89 2224EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-AIDS-Drugs     03-06 0603</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AIDS-Drugs,0622</SECOND>
<HEAD>Group To Import Drugs For AIDS Patients</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICK HAMPSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A drug buyers club announced plans Monday to
provide American AIDS patients with prescription drugs from abroad
that have not been approved for use in the United States.
   The People with AIDS Health Group said it would rely on foreign
doctors to obtain the prescription drugs, then pass them along at
cost to AIDS patients.
   To get a three-month supply of a drug, an AIDS patient must
present a physician's prescription or note, group officials said at
a news conference.
   Although they described the plan as unprecedented, they said it
would not violate Food and Drug Administration rules.
   Last year, the FDA said it would allow people with
life-threatening illnesses to import personal supplies of unapproved
drugs.
   But until now the New York group and other buyers clubs have only
imported drugs that do nt require a prescription in the foreign
country. Anyone wishing to legally obtain such drugs had to travel
abroad and get a prescription from a physician there.
   ``We're saving people the trip and the importation expenses,''
said Michael Callen, a founder of the group.
   Dr. Frank Young, commissioner of the FDA, has declined to say if
his agency would try to stop the drug importation effort, but said
any action probably would depend on what drugs the group imports and
how it does so.
   One will be fluconazole, which has been approved by several
European nations as an anti-fungal medication for use against
meningitis and AIDS.
   It is seen by some physicians and AIDS patients as an effective
yet mild alternative to amphotericin B, a drug which must be taken
intravenously once a week and whose harsh side effects include
shakes and fever.
   Acquired immune deficiency syndrome is caused by a virus that
damages the body's immune system, leaving victims susceptible to
infections and cancer. According to the Centers for Disease Control
in Atlanta there have been 49,976 deaths from AIDS since June 1981.
   Callen said his group would decide which other drugs to import
based on criteria such as toxicity, cost, effectiveness and
availability. It is unclear how many patients might use the service,
he said.
   Although Callen said the group would try to keep drug costs as
low as possible, some AIDS remedies are relatively expensive. Mark
Mutchnik, an AIDS patient whom the group supplied with fluconazole,
said a daily dosage cost about $23, and was not covered by insurance
because it was not FDA-approved.
   The New York Times on Monday quoted group officials as saying
they would obtain the drugs through foreign doctors. But Callen said
at the news conference that they had decided ``not to be fully
forthcoming about our precise means'' of importation. One
possibility, he said, would be to put a patient directly in touch
with a foreign physician who would send the drug.
   AIDS patient advocates have criticized the FDA for being overly
cautious about approving AIDS drugs, arguing that they do not have
time to wait for more tests on drugs deemed controversial by the
agency.
   The FDA says it has a responsibility to protect Americans from
drugs that could be useless or harmful, but ``something is wrong
when doctors feel compelled to send patients overseas'' to obtain
drugs, said Dr. Peter Seitzman, a physician with a large AIDS
practice. He said several of his patients have gone to England to
obtain fluconazole.
   The People with AIDS Health Group has been supplying about 2,000
AIDS patients with non-prescription drugs from abroad which have not
been approved for use in this country.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890306-0166 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-06-89 1929EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-China-Democracy     03-06 0532</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Democracy,0550</SECOND>
<HEAD>Scientists Join Call For Amnesty, Democracy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY WILHELM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 40 prominent scientists have joined the
movement among Chinese intellectuals for greater democracy and the
release of political prisoners, a spokesman for the group said
Monday.
   Xu Liangying, a scientific historian at the Academy of Sciences,
said 42 people signed a letter urging China's top leaders to
guarantee freedom of speech, publication and information.
   ``This is the only reliable guarantee of unity and stability,''
the letter said, referring to government fears that democracy could
bring instability.
   ``World history and China's experience shows that political
democratization, including a legal system, is necessary to guarantee
economic reform and the whole modernization (program),'' the
scientists said.
   Xu said he mailed copies last week to Communist Party chief Zhao
Ziyang, Premier Li Peng and the heads of the National People's
Congress and Chinese People's Political Consultative Committee, an
advisory body of intellectuals.
   It was the third letter of its kind sent to the leadership this
year. China's best-known dissident, astrophysicist Fang Lizhi, first
proposed amnesty in a letter to senior leader Deng Xiaoping in
January.
   Thirty-three intellectuals, including some of China's most famous
writers and philosphers, signed a letter with the same message in
February. Hundreds of people in Hong Kong and Taiwan, as well as
Chinese living in the United States, have signed petitions and
letters of support for an amnesty.
   Specific requests were made in the first two letters for the
release of Wei Jingsheng, who was convicted of counterrevolutionary
activities in 1979 and is said to have become mentally ill.
   No names were mentioned in the scientists' letter, which appealed
for the release of ``all young people who were convicted and
sentenced to labor reform because of ideological problems.''
   It said that would ``open a new era in the political history of
our country.''
   Xu said he helped write the letter and the signers believed China
``shouldn't arrest people because they have different political
views.''
   Last month, the Justice Ministry said calls for amnesty amounted
to ``interfering in the administration of justice.''
   No other direct government response has been forthcoming, but
Monday's Beijing Daily defended the imprisonment of Wei.
   ``Freedom of speech in any country cannot be held to be above the
country's basic interests,'' it declared. ``People have the freedom
of speech but not the freedom of agitating for counterrevolution by
taking advantage of socialist democracy.''
   Among signers of the latest letter were Wang Ganchang, a former
vice minister of nuclear industry, and physicist Qian Lingjiao.
   Many intellectuals have learned caution from four decades of
alternating thaws and freezes on freedom of expression, but
increasing numbers now are speaking out on political and economic
issues.
   They say they are disillusioned by China's continued backwardness
and poverty and believe a free exchange of ideas is necessary to
modernizaton.
   Fang Lizhi, who last week was barred from a dinner given by
President Bush, has encouraged intellectuals to press for democratic
reform.
   China's leaders say their priority is stability. Party chief Zhao
told Bush during his two-day visit that multi-party democracy is not
suitable for China and efforts to promote it will endanger economic
reform.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
