<FILEID>AP-NR-03-06-89 2043EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Eastern-PilotsRules     03-06 0412</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Eastern-Pilots Rules,410</SECOND>
<HEAD>Given Two Safe Choices: Take The Slowest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Plans by pilots for nearly all U.S. airlines to
strictly fly by the rule book starting Tuesday could cause lengthy
flight delays, especially where there is heavy traffic and bad
weather, according to aviation experts and pilots.
   The Air Line Pilots Association announced the action by its
40,000 members as a show of support for 8,500 striking Eastern
Airlines Machinists union members and the Eastern pilots and flight
stewardesses who have refused to cross the picket lines.
   Pilots, in announcing the action, said it would not amount to a
``slowdown,'' because they would simply be following procedures,
taking the longer option when there are two or more safe options
available.
   The primary impact could come if pilots rely on instrument
landing procedures when they could use visual procedures, said FAA
spokesman John Leyden.
   But Leyden said it was impossible to tell how much the pilots'
action would affect overall air travel. He said in some instances,
the impact might be minimal and in areas where weather is bad and
traffic heavy, it could be greater.
   Pilot John Sheehy, who has been flying for Eastern for 19 years,
said he viewed the action as ``a morale booster'' from Eastern
pilots who are honoring the pickets but doubted it would cause
significant tie ups.
   Wayne Dolan, spokesman for picketing Eastern pilots at
Washington's National Airport, said the action could enhance safety
in a time when several airlines have beefed up routes normally flown
by Eastern, using pilots unfamiliar with the routes.
   ``What you want to do is be sure the public is protected. We want
to be sure the crews know where they're going ... so the approaches
are made safely,'' said Dolan.
   One thing pilots might do is require air traffic controllers to
read back flight plans for verification, rather than simply giving
an acknowledgement that they have heard the pilot's intentions.
   ``They'll make sure every `t' is crossed and every `i' dotted,''
said a government official who is a pilot. The official, who asked
not to be identified, said pilots likely would be taking the ``most
conservative and time-consuming way'' whenever possible.
   The official said this might not necessarily enhance safety,
because tie-ups at crowded airports could lead to increased
frustration.
   ``It's a matter of a few seconds here and a few seconds there,
and it could really cascade,'' the official said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
