<FIRST>u i AM-Salvador-Elections     03-06 0311</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Salvador-Elections,0322</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chief Lawmaker Rules Out Election Postponement</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Salvador</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The presidential election
scheduled this month cannot be postponed as suggested by leftist
rebels, the president of the legislature said Monday.
   ``Just like they (the guerrillas) do not accept the March 19 date
for whatever reasons, we do not accept any change in the date,
because constitutionally the date cannot be changed,'' Ricardo
Alvarenga told journalists at the National Assembly.
   His remarks appeared to quash any prospect that an election delay
could be a first step toward ending the 9-year-old civil war.
   On Jan. 24, the rebels' Farabundo Marti National Liberation Front
offered to take part in the presidential election and respect its
outcome if it were postponed until September and if security and
anti-fraud conditions were met.
   The guerrillas had rejected all previous elections this decade as
sham.
   The government of President Jose Napoleon Duarte, a Christian
Democrat, suggested the election be delayed by six weeks rather than
six months. The rebels said that was insufficient.
   The single-chamber legislature has virtual veto power over any
postponement and is controlled by the opposition rightist Republican
Nationalist Alliance. The alliance, known as ARENA, is favored to
win the presidential election and has rejected any postponement of
the vote.
   The constitution says the election must be held at least two
months before a new government takes office. Duarte's term ends on
June 1.
   The Christian Democrats have said elections could be legally
postponed and an interim president named by the legislature if a
political consensus to do so exists.
   The Farabundo Marti on Saturday said direct talks with the
government on their proposal must be held Tuesday and Wednesday in
San Salvador, the capital.
   It repeated its accusation that the government was
procrastinating.
   The civil war has killed an estimated 70,000 people, most of them
civilians.
</TEXT>
