<FIRST>r a AM-WifeSlain 2ndLd-Writethru a0723 03-06 0681</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Wife Slain, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0723,0695</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bayh Vows Discipline for Correction Workers after Slaying</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 4 grafs to reflect that corrections workers suspended,
ADD where slaying occurred; picks up 5th graf, ``He had ...;'' SUBS grafs
8-11, ``Bayh said ...,'' with two grafs to reflect suspensions, DELETE
redundant graf on review of pass system; picks up 12th graf, ``Bayh said
...''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STANLEY D. MILLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A program that allowed convicts time away
from prison was suspended Monday by Gov. Evan Bayh after an inmate
out on an eight-hour pass allegedly bludgeoned his former wife to
death while neighbors watched.
   Bayh said two corrections officers were suspended in connection
with the furlough of Alan Matheney, 38, from the Correctional
Industrial Complex near the Indiana State Reformatory at Pendleton.
   ``Clearly, mistakes were made, there's no doubt about that, and
I'm good and mad about it,'' Bayh said.
   Matheney was being held Monday on a preliminary charge of murder
in Saturday's death of his ex-wife, Lisa Marie Bianco, 29, in
Mishawaka near the Michigan state line. Officers said she was beaten
to death with the butt of a shotgun.
   He had been serving an eight-year sentence for beating Bianco two
years ago. The two were divorced in 1985, police said Monday.
   Prison officials said Matheney was released from the light-medium
security CIC to the custody of his mother, Martha Matheney, Saturday
morning and his freedom was supposed to be limited to the
Indianapolis area.
   ``I understand proper procedures were not followed, and we're
going to find out why that happened, discipline those who were
involved, re-evaluate the whole program and see if it makes sense,''
Bayh said.
   At a Statehouse news conference later Monday, he announced the
suspension of the two corrections officers pending an investigation
into their approval of a pass for Matheny. Correction Department
spokesman Vaughn Overstreet said he would not identify the workers
because they had not yet been notified.
   The governor said former U.S. Attorney Virginia Dill McCarty
would head a Correction Department internal investigation. A report
is due Friday.
   Bayh said earlier he thought that proper procedure was for a
victim to be notified that his or her attacker was being released.
   But Christopher Meloy, supervisor of work release services for
the Department of Correction, said policy calls for victims such as
Bianco to be notified of a release only if they had previously
requested such notification. Meloy did not know if Bianco had made
such a request.
   ``Some victims are not that concerned about it, some victims move
and are very difficult to get in touch with, and sometimes we don't
even have an easily identifiable victim,'' he said.
   Meloy also defended the programs.
   ``We for the most part have been enjoying a successful track
record,'' Meloy said.
   Succeeding in either program means the offender has not been
returned to the institution after his full release, Meloy said.
   Bayh spokesman Fred Nation said no inmates involved in the
special assignment program will receive a pass for the next four
weeks while the policy is reviewed.
   Bayh said the review would determine whether the program
``deserves to be continued or whether we should eliminate it
entirely.''
   Matheney got the pass under a program that sends inmates at state
expense to work for Interfaith Housing, a not-for-profit
organization that refurbishes hoouses and sells them to low- and
middle-income families, Meloy said.
   Bayh said he was aware of Indiana's Regulated Community
Assignment program and work-release program, but he was unaware of
the special release program that allowed Matheney an eight-hour pass.
   ``In fact, I have some serious doubts about this program because
it does not help significantly with the overcrowding situtation in
the prison. It is not related to work-release activities which
prepare inmates for meeting full employment in the private sector.
   ``This is used, as I understand it, as a tool to promote good
behavior in the prison walls. And it seems to me that there may be
some other less risky methods to make that possible,'' Bayh said.
</TEXT>
