<FIRST>r a AM-DiabeticArrest     03-06 0435</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Diabetic Arrest,0447</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Defend Actions In Diabetic's Arrest For Drunken Driving</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JULIA RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LAKEWOOD, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police on Monday denied allegations that
they beat a diabetic man who went into insulin shock while driving
his car and was arrested for drunken driving.
   ``The police probably should have checked a little closer,''
Police Chief Charles Johnston said. ``But they had a lot of other
concerns at the time, mainly that this guy didn't fall down and hurt
himself.''
   Phillip Sanchez, 63, sustained bruises to his face, hip and arms.
He said he doesn't remember much of what happened in the incident
Friday because of his condition, but remembers being ``roughed up
pretty good'' and telling police he needed insulin.
   He said police should have diagnosed his problem sooner and that
they mistreated him by handcuffing him and putting him in a holding
cell.
   At a news conference, Johnston defended his officers' actions and
said a preliminary investigation showed no evidence of brutality or
excessive force.
   He said the bruises to Sanchez's arms and wrists were caused when
officers tried to handcuff him. He added that Sanchez bruises easily
because of medication he takes for a heart condition.
   Johnston said Sanchez may have contributed to discoloration
around his eyes by rubbing them a lot, but added that he also fell
and hit his eye on a file cabinet in the police station.
   The incident began when Sanchez allegedly made an improper turn
at an intersection and his pickup was hit by a car. He drove away,
and police were notified of a hit-and-run accident.
   Officers later found Sanchez and his car in a stranger's driveway.
   Police said they did not notice a necklace Sanchez wore under his
shirt identifying him as a diabetic or a similar identification card
in his wallet. They noticed a medical bracelet he wore which said he
suffered from a heart ailment but mentioned nothing about diabetes.
   Sanchez refused to take a sobriety test, but later tests showed
he had no alcohol in his blood. Officers said they asked Sanchez on
the way to the station if he needed medical attention and he said no.
   Police reports say Sanchez was uncooperative at the police
station, exhibited mood swings and was handcuffed to a bench in a
holding cell.
   An officer found him unconscious in that cell some 80 minutes
later and he was rushed to a hospital, where glucose injections
revived him.
   Johnston said Sanchez probably would not be charged in the
traffic accident because he was unaware of what he was doing at the
time.
</TEXT>
