<FIRST>r i AM-Haiti     03-06 0488</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Haiti,0505</SECOND>
<HEAD>Reports Hundreds of Haitians Seized Boats to Sail to U.S.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL NORTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   PORT-AU-PRINCE, Haiti (AP) _ Hundreds of impoverished Haitians
seized boats over the weekend in efforts to go to the United States
after a rumored change in U.S. immigration politicies, a radio
station reported Monday.
   The independent station Radio Metropole said at least five cases
of ``piracy'' were reported after people tried to seize sailboats
and small cargo ships in the harbors of Port-au-Prince, Petit Goave,
Les Cayes and Jeremie.
   It said one body washed ashore after a commandeered boat
foundered on a reef. Craft carrying 183 Haitians were stopped at sea
by U.S. Coast Guard vessels, and the people were being returned to
Haiti, the report said.
   The rumor suggested that immigration authorities in Miami had
relaxed U.S. residency requirements, and that would improve the
chances of Haitians seeking refuge in the United States.
   A U.S. immigration official in Miami, speaking on condition he
not be identified, said he was not aware of any change in residency
requirements for Haitians.
   Radio Metropole gave this account of the various incidents:
   Early Saturday a group of armed men including at least six
soldiers boarded a cargo ship in Petit Goave, tied up the crew and
ordered the captain to take them to Miami. The ship struck a reef
and was abandoned.
   A soldier and three other men allegedly involved in the takeover
were arrested later Saturday by Petit Goave police, and the body of
an unidentified man was found on the shore.
   On Saturday night, a yacht docked in Petit Goave harbor was
stolen, presumably by members of the shipwrecked group, and the
vessel has not been recovered.
   Police, moving to block the possible seizure of boats, arrested
30 Haitians on a dock in Port-au-Prince's Cite Soleil slum district.
   The report about the U.S. Coast Guard stopping Haitians en route
to Florida said only that 183 people were picked up and were being
returned to Haiti.
   Coast Guard officials in Florida, in reports on three incidents,
said 154 Haitians were apprehended Sunday and Monday.
   Coast Guard spokesman Jerry Snyder said the Honduran coastal
freighter Madrid was intercepted Sunday 40 miles from Haiti, and 36
Haitians were transferred to a Coast Guard cutter. He said the
Haitian government suspected three of its soldiers hijacked the
250-foot freighter out of Mirgoane, Haiti, Saturday night.
   Snyder reported the Madrid's captain said eight others aboard the
freighter were either crew or visitors and were not involved in the
takeover.
   While dealing with the Haitians from the Madrid, the Coast Guard
cutter stopped a sailboat carrying 80 Haitians, and they also were
taken aboard.
   Coast Guard officer Luis Diaz said 38 more Haitians were picked
up Monday in a 30-foot sailboat 17 miles east of Fort Lauderdale.
   More than 7,000 Haitians trying to flee their Caribbean homeland
were apprehended in 1988 and returned to the island.
</TEXT>
