<HEAD>Leaders of Divided Island Hold First Round of Intensive Talks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President George Vassiliou and Turkish
Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash on Monday held their first session of
intensive talks on reunifying the island.
   The talks, held under United Nations auspices, lasted three hours
at the home of the U.N. special representative to Cyprus, Oscar
Camilion, a U.N. statement said.
   Vassiliou and Denktash are to hold 10 sessions of closed-door
talks over the next three weeks in preparation for a review April
5-6 in New York with U.N. Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar.
   U.N. officials have said the current intensive talks are intended
to examine a wide range of options on a non-binding basis.
   The two leaders started regular weekly meetings last September
but have failed to make progress on a formula for establishing a
two-state federation.
   The Greek side reportedly is pushing for a strong federal
government, while the Turkish side supports a looser federation.
   The two sides reportedly also disagree over the withdrawal of
Turkish troops, and the right of Greek Cypriots to return to
property they fled after the 1974 Turkish invasion.
   In 1974, a coup by Greece's military junta failed on the island.
Turkey invaded the northern part of Cyprus, saying it was protecting
the minority Turkish Cypriot community, and sent thousands of Turks
to settle in the north.
   
   Denktash in 1975 proclaimed the northern part of the island an
independent Turkish state. The state, where an estimated 30,000
troops remain, is recognized only by Turkey.
