<FIRST>r i AM-Poland-Food     03-06 0262</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland-Food,0271</SECOND>
<HEAD>Polish Border Authorities Block More Than 3,000 Food Smugglers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Customs officials recently stopped more
than 3,000 Poles who were seeking to smuggle food into Western
Europe, where they could sell it for a profit, the official PAP news
agency reported Monday.
   It attributed its report to Zygmunt Janczyk, spokesman for the
main customs office.
   PAP did not say during what period of time the offenders were
turned back. It quoted Janczyk as reporting the crackdown and
saying, ``We will fight this negative phenomenon until it vanishes
completely.''
   Communist authorities on Jan. 1 eased procedures to obtain
passports and thousands of Poles have headed West to trade, mainly
to West Berlin or Austria where visas are not required.
   Janczyk said Poles were allowed to take enough food for their
journey, but a 300 percent customs duty is charged on any excessive
amount.
   He said some Polish passengers on a train en route to West Berlin
threw food away when they saw customs officers approach.
   Janczyk told PAP that in one case a Pole tried to smuggle a goat
and a baby pig into West Berlin.
   Meat has been rationed in Poland since December 1980. Although
consumers must wait in line to buy at state stores, meat also can be
bought privatedly from farmers at higher prices.
   Trading in the West is tempting to Poles because they can buy
goods in Poland for zlotys, sell them for hard currency in the West
and then convert that money back into zlotys at the black-market
rate for a profit.
</TEXT>
