<FILEID>AP-NR-03-06-89 2052EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-ImperialQuakes     03-06 0481</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Imperial Quakes,0493</SECOND>
<HEAD>Quakes Prompt Concern Among Scientists</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NILAND, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 30 mild earthquakes rocked the
Imperial Valley on Monday, apparently causing no damage or injuries
but raising concern among scientists because the jolts were centered
near the San Andreas Fault.
   A temblor at 2:16 p.m. that measured 4.7 on the Richter scale was
followed by 32 aftershocks over magnitude 2 by 5 p.m., including a
magnitude-4.0 jolt, said California Institute of Technology
spokesman Robert Finn.
   The two largest quakes were centered six miles west-southwest of
Niland in the Imperial Valley, one of the state's major agricultural
areas and located north of the Mexican border, Finn said. Quakes in
the valley typically occur in swarms of dozens or hundreds.
   ``Hardly anyone has called, and we have no reports of damage,''
Imperial County Sheriff's Department dispatcher Pam Skipper said
after the main shock.
   ``It was one of those quakes that were fun _ just enough to
jiggle you around but not strong enough to scare you. It didn't
shake things off the wall,'' said Harry Jensen, city manager of
Brawley about 20 miles south of here.
   The quake was the largest of a swarm of jolts that started
several months ago in the Brawley seismic zone. It was centered 12
miles from the southern end of the San Andreas and roughly three to
six miles from an extension of that fault, said Tom Heaton,
scientist in charge of the U.S. Geological Survey's Pasadena office.
   ``It's not far from the San Andreas Fault so of course it's a
concern to us any time there are earthquakes down there,'' Heaton
said. ``There's definitely communications back and forth among the
scientists and the state of California'' Office of Emergency
Services.
   Scientists are concerned about quakes in the Imperial Valley
because of the slight possibility they might trigger larger quakes
on the San Andreas.
   However, Heaton emphasized the quake was not on another fault
called the Extra Fault, but well south of it. That fault intersects
the San Andreas.
   A recent study by Columbia University's Lamont-Doherty Geological
Observatory raised the possibility that Southern California's next
great, or magnitude-8, earthquake on the San Andreas might be
triggered hours after an Extra Fault quake of magnitude 5.5 or more.
   The Imperial Valley is California's most active seismic region.
   ``It's not uncommon to have earthquakes in the Brawley seismic
zone,'' Heaton said. ``There have been many earthquakes in the
Brawley seismic zone and the big earthquake has not occurred.''
   Until Monday's quake, the largest quake in the swarm was a mild
one of magnitude 3.6, Heaton said.
   The Richter scale is a gauge of the energy released by an
earthquake, as measured by the ground motion recorded on a
seismograph. An earthquake of 3.5 on the Richter scale can cause
slight damage in the local area, 4 moderate damage, 5 considerable
damage, 6 severe damage.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890306-0180 </DOCNO>
