<SECOND>AM-Germany-US Soldier, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0731,0328</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Army Charges Soldier Thought To Have Defected To East Germany</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 4th graf, ``Peri was... with 1 graf to delete reference
to 12 days. Pick up 5th pvs, ``Active duty...</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A U.S. soldier whose 11-day
disappearance prompted speculation he had defected to communist East
Germany was charged Monday with leaving his unit without permission
and violating security rules.
   Michael A. Peri, 21, of Laguna Niguel, Calif., returned
voluntarily to his unit Saturday. He disappeared Feb. 21 from the
11th Armored Cavalry Regiment in Fulda, about 62 miles northeast of
Frankfurt.
   The disappearance baffled military officials, who said Peri had
been a model soldier.
   Peri was charged with being absent without leave and for entering
the half-mile-wide security zone near the communist East German
border without permission, said Lt. Col. Jake Dye, a spokesman for
the U.S. Army's 5th Corps in Frankfurt.
   Active duty U.S. forces must have permission to enter the areas
next to the border with East Germany.
   Dye said Peri also was charged with theft of a vehicle and other
items, including a portable computer he took from the regimental
intelligence office where he worked.
   Peri has undergone questioning since he returned to his unit late
Saturday. His disappearance prompted speculation he had defected to
East Germany because his military vehicle was found parked and
undamaged near the border.
   Dye said Peri, of Laguna Niguel, Calif., has refused to tell
authorities where he was or what he was doing during his absence.
   ``Mr. Peri, on the advice of counsel, has elected not to comment
to investigating authorities,'' Dye said.
   Dye said Peri had been moved to a military detention facility in
Mannheim to await a court-martial.
   Peri had worked as an electronics warfare signal specialist and
was responsible for monitoring radar and other military signals.
   He has been stationed in West Germany since March 1988.
</TEXT>
