<FIRST>u a AM-CollegeDesegregation 1stLd-Writethru a0589 03-06 0807</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-College Desegregation, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0589,0825</SECOND>
<HEAD>After 15 Years, Trial To Start in College Desegregation Case</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs to UPDATE with settlement talks held Monday.
Picks up 4th graf pvs,`Alumni from...'. SUBS 15th graf pvs,`Gov. Buddy...,'
to conform.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JANET McCONNAUGHEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The first federal desegregation lawsuit ever
filed against an entire state university system heads back into
court Tuesday, 15 years after the Justice Department first sued
Louisiana.
   A special master appointed by a panel of federal judges is
convening hearings on desegregation plans proposed by the state, the
Justice Department, Southern University and the Grambling State
University Alumni Association.
   The panel of federal judges ruled in December that a 1981 consent
decree aimed at improving Southern and Grambling in order to bring
more whites to them had failed miserably.
   Settlement talks were held Monday, but the hearings will go
ahead, said the state's attorney.
   ``Some progress was made. There has not been total consensus in
the form of a settlement,'' said John Kennedy, attorney for Gov.
Buddy Roemer. ``And as a practical matter, even if everyone agreed
on everything, we couldn't get it all drawn up and written out in
time to stop the hearings.''
   Alumni from Southern, the nation's largest predominantly black
university system, and Grambling, also mostly black, are fighting to
keep their schools distinct from other state universities while
making them equal.
   ``Separate but equal has another connotation, so I wouldn't
describe it in those words,'' said Dolores Spikes, president of
Southern.
   ``I think what Southern is asking for is the same thing that the
Justice Department is asking for _ a desegregated system, but one
that still allows for access and a chance for reasonable success for
minority students, poor students, and disadvantaged students,'' she
said. ``That's part of the mission of Southern University; we're
asking that remain intact.''
   The problem that must be corrected, supporters say, is that
Southern and Grambling never got the money and programs needed to
catch up academically to other schools.
   Paul Verkuil, president of the College of William and Mary in
Virginia, was appointed special master in the case to draw up a
desegregation plan because attorneys for 13 universities, four
governing boards, the state and the Justice Department were unable
to agree on one.
   The first day of hearings comes one week before the suit's 15th
anniversary; Verkuil has said they must end by March 15, the day
after that anniversary.
   Louisiana State University and the Shreveport and New Orleans
campuses of the LSU system remain almost all white, while Southern's
campuses in those cities remain nearly all black. The same is true
of Grambling and Louisiana Tech, about eight miles down Interstate
20.
   Southern contends that Louisiana, not the agreement, failed
miserably.
   The state says it spent more than $200 million to upgrade the
black schools. Southern contends the total spent on black schools
was closer to $75 million.
   Grambling and Tech are among nine schools run by the Board of
Trustees for State Colleges and Universities, and the state's
proposal includes Grambling. However, the Grambling University
Alumni Association has proposed its own plan.
   Although the LSU, Southern and trustees systems all are
controlled by the Louisiana Board of Regents, they often fight over
the limited money in a state budget hit hard by the oil industry
bust.
   Roemer wants to scrap the current four-board system and set up
one board to run all of the schools and end the turf wars.
   Southern, which lost $5.6 million when $11 million in state money
was cut from all colleges, would probably lose even more if this
happens, supporters say.
   Just as important, they say, thousands of blacks left unprepared
by Louisiana's woeful public schools might lose their chance at a
college education.
   Plans submitted by Southern and by the Grambling alumni depend
heavily on moving programs from predominantly white schools to the
black schools to make them more attractive to whites.
   The Justice Department plan also leans heavily on transferring
programs to Southern and Grambling, and calls for Southern to open
new graduate schools in New Orleans and Shreveport.
   The state's proposal calls for varying admission standards for
seven of Louisiana's 13 four-year universities, for cooperation
among schools in the same part of the state and for a separate
system of community colleges to take over the most basic courses.
   Verkuil already has statements from all the witnesses, plus
depositions they gave to opposing lawyers.
   Rather than listen to arguments he's already read, he plans to
jump directly from an introductory statement by state attorney John
Kennedy into cross-examination of the state's 32 witnesses.
   Attorneys for the Justice, Southern and the Grambling alumni
association each may question each state witness. After that, each
must defend its own alternative to the state plan.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
