<FIRST>r a AM-Klan-Philadelphia 1stLd-Writethru a0742 03-06 0373</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Klan-Philadelphia, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0742,0381</SECOND>
<HEAD>Klan Holds Recruitment Rally in City of ``Mississippi Burning''</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf, ``The Grand ...,'' to UPDATE with later march
in Meridian, edits for transition; picks up 4th graf pvs, ``The fictional
...''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT NAYLOR JR.</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sixteen members of the Christian
Knights of the Ku Klux Klan chanted ``White power for America'' as
they marched Sunday afternoon through the town portrayed in the
movie ``Mississippi Burning.''
   About 100 people lined the streets of the north-central
Mississipi town of 7,500 to watch the Klan demonstration. Only a
handful of hecklers, some of them white, shouted at the white
supremacists.
   About 20 Klansmen marched later in the day in Meridian about 40
miles to the east. About 10 counterdemonstrators and 100 spectators
turned out.
   Philadelphia was chosen for what was billed as a Klan recruitment
rally because of its portrayal in ``Mississippi Burning,'' said the
Grand Dragon for Mississippi, Jordan Gollub of Picayune.
   The fictional movie, which received seven Oscar nominations, is
loosely based on the 1964 slayings of three civil rights workers
whose bodies were found in an earthen dam near Philadelphia.
   James Earl Chaney, 21, who was black, and Andrew Goodman, 20, and
Michael Schwerner, 24, who were white, were shot to death. The
federal government eventually convicted eight people of violating
the civil rights of the three men, but no one was ever charged with
murder.
   The Klan group that rallied Sunday included men and women, with
10 wearing robes.
   Gollub's group has marched in several Mississippi towns in the
past few months, with Philadelphia's crowd drawing by far the
largest number of spectators. The Klan planned another rally later
Sunday in Meridian.
   Several black leaders had asked opponents of the Klan to stay at
home during Sunday's march, saying the less attention the white
supremacists received, the better.
   The Klan members declared during their rally on the Neshoba
County Courthouse grounds that they plan to march in every
Mississippi county in efforts to attract new members.
   However, only a handful of people at Philadelphia took membership
applications offered by the Klan members.
   The Klan marchers were accompanied by two police cars and six
patrolmen on foot.
</TEXT>
