<FIRST>r a AM-KochAssassins     03-06 0206</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Koch Assassins,0211</SECOND>
<HEAD>Newspaper: Assassins Who Planned To Hit Koch Deported</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two Colombians allegedly sent here to assassinate
Mayor Edward I. Koch and the top federal drug official in the city
were secretly deported to their South American homeland, according
to a report published Sunday.
   Federal officials decided to deport the pair because trying to
convict them of conspiracy to commit murder would have endangered
drug informants in other cases, the New York Post said, quoting
unidentified sources.
   Officials also feared they did not have enough evidence to win
convictions.
   According to the Post, Carlos Vargas Martinez and Ivan Esteban
Ayala-Zitagualta were escorted aboard an Avianca Airlines flight
Friday from Kennedy International Airport to Cali, Colombia.
   ``They're out of the country. They're no longer here _ it's a
closed case,'' said Charles Troy, a spokesman for the Immigration
and Naturalization Service.
   The two men were arrested in October in a van loaded with
electronic equipment. Investigators said they were killers who had
targeted Koch and Robert Stutman, head of the U.S. Drug Enforcement
Administration's New York office.
   One source told the Post that the Colombians were part of a team
of contract killers with close ties to the Medellin drug cartel.
