<FIRST>r i AM-Israel-Lebanon     03-06 0199</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel-Lebanon,0204</SECOND>
<HEAD>Israel Denies Army Planning To Expand Security Zone</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israel on Sunday vigorously denied Lebanese
reports that it plans to expand its self-proclaimed ``security
zone'' in southern Lebanon.
   Responding to statements of concern issued in Lebanon, an Israeli
Defense Ministry official said Israel has ``no intention
whatsoever'' of expanding the border strip the army controls.
   Israel carved out the 6- to 10-mile deep zone in 1985 when it
withdrew the bulk of its troops from Lebanon.
   A Lebanon radio station affiliated with the Israeli-allied South
Lebanon Army, Voice of the South, has reported that Israel wants to
include five Druse villages in the zone.
   The report said the move was requested by unidentified leaders of
the Mimes, Khalwat, Ein Senta, Kfir and Ein Ata villages, located a
few miles north of the zone.
   But Defense Ministry spokesman Eitan Haber denied the reports
Sunday. He said there have been numerous requests from certain
villages whose residents would like to be included in the zone to
benefit from increased security and economic advantages. Many
residents of the security zone are employed in Israeli workplaces.
   ``Israel however has not intention whatsoever of widening the
zone,'' Haber said.
