<FIRST>r i AM-Italy-Fashion     03-06 0616</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Italy-Fashion,0631</SECOND>
<HEAD>A Youthful Armani And Moschino Kick Off Milan Fashion Week</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIELA PETROFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Fashion Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MILAN, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Italian ready-to-wear collections for
fall and winter got off to a lively start Sunday with fashion
darling Giorgio Armani's sporty Emporio line and spoof specialist
Franco Moschino's gag-filled winter wardrobe.
   Pants, in all shapes and sizes prevailed in both collections,
with only a spattering of skirts.
   In the early 1980's, Armani, the leader in Italian ready-to-wear,
decided to court the younger set by creating a fresh sporty line at
more accessible prices. He started with designer jeans, but the
label dubbed Emporio soon was manufacturing Armani's trade mark
blazer, suits, coats and even evening wear.
   Today Emporio shops designed to appeal to the young with their
bright lights, trendy posters and hip music are scattered throughout
Italy and the rest of Europe. An Emporio Armani shop is due to open
in New York later this month.
   For this year's chillier season, Armani, who showed his
collection Sunday morning in the modern theater of his downtown
Milan headquarters, plays heavily on casual, with a series of wool
knit sweat pants worn under tweed blazers or matching jackets. Other
trousers are super wide and cropped at the ankle, with or without
cuff.
   Armani's new winter jacket is cut off above the waist. At times
it has a long loose back, at others it is trimmed in demure
pie-crust ruffles. His blazer is single breasted with huge breast
and side pockets, a look he introduced in his more exclusive Armani
label several seasons ago.
   There are plenty of beautiful coats to pick from for next winter,
from the classic polo, to cape coats and fun furs. Armani who has
joined the chorus of voices calling for a ban on the use of real
skins in fashion, introduced fake sables, minks and bear. To prove
his point he even dotted his leather wear from shoes to purses with
precious leopard spots.
   Evening at Emporio is very 1930-ish with long clinging black
jersey velvet dresses, enhanced by small velvet hats complete with
feather, and feather cuffed gloves. He also favors the tuxedo look
from silk lapel to studs and black tie.
   Armani has never been a bright light on the Milan runway where
color is concerned and his new Emporio collection is no exception.
Browns grays and blacks, plus the traditional fall shades are his
favorite palette, with a spatter of bright red and green for future
Christmas cheer.
   Franco Moschino, who also showed Sunday, was putting everything
but the kitchen sink on hats, as a joke, before Christian LaCroix
turned potpourri hats into a multi-million dollar business.
   For the winter season he gets his biggest laugh out of the label
racket, by flaunting labels and price tags throughout the
collection. Thus a simple striped silk stole has a super visible
huge white label with the designers name and the word `couture'
written on it.
   A jacket bears the inscription embroidered in gold, ``this is
very expensive,'' and a blouse states its price, also in gold.
   Other fashion gags at Moschino include tape measure belts, dinner
jackets decorated with real forks, knives and spoons, and an Irish
knit sweater with a ball of yarn and knitting needles still attached
around the collar.
   But don't be fooled by Moschino's sense of humor. Behind the
chuckles is a very serious designer with lots of superbly designed
clothes.
   For next season Moschino prefers pants, with wide bell bottoms to
skirts, and favors long jackets with large cloth buttons.
   Like Armani he prefers to let the animals keep their skins opting
for opulent fuzzy coats and stoles in harmless synthetic fabric.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
