<FIRST>r i AM-SouthAfrica-Botha     03-06 0451</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-South Africa-Botha,0464</SECOND>
<HEAD>Power Struggle Predicted Between Botha and Heir Apparent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A power struggle may break out
between President P.W. Botha and his heir apparent because of
Botha's plans to return to work after he recovers from a stroke,
newspapers reported Sunday.
   There had been speculation that the 73-year-old president, who
suffered a stroke Jan. 18, would return to office only long enough
to step down with dignity and ceremony, making way for Education
Minister F.W. de Klerk.
   However, Botha indicated in an interview last week that he will
come back to work in April and stay in office at least until his
term expires in September.
   De Klerk was elected by National Party members of Parliament on
Feb. 2 to become the party's new leader after Botha resigned from
that post. Traditionally, the party leader has been head of
government, and de Klerk has found himself in an awkward position
because he has no formal power over government decision-making.
   De Klerk was quoted in Sunday newspapers as saying he would raise
the issue this week in an effort to clarify who the party wants as
its top policy-maker.
   ``Showdown over P.W. looms,'' said a front-page headline in The
Sunday Star of Johannesburg.
   ``P.W. and F.W. Set To Clash,'' said a headline in the nationally
circulated Sunday Times, the country's largest-selling newspaper.
   Both newspapers said many National Party officials hoped Botha
would step aside after 10 years in power, but the reports said an
overt move to oust Botha was seen as an unlikely last resort.
   Botha has spent most of the time since his stroke recuperating at
his coastal vacation home while being replaced by an acting
president, Constitutional Development Minister Chris Heunis.
   Calls for Botha's resignation have come from liberal and
far-right opposition parties, as well as from some National Party
members.
   De Klerk has yet to declare any major policy differences with
Botha, but he is widely depicted as more flexible and pragmatic and
thus more capable of breaking South Africa's political stalemate. He
and Heunis have both made vague proposals to soften the impact of
existing segregation laws.
   A national opinion poll, reported Sunday in newspapers of the
Argus group, found that 47 percent of the 1,098 respondents wanted
Botha to step down, while 33 percent wanted him to stay in office
and 20 percent were undecided.
   The telephone poll, conducted by Marketing and Media Research,
involved randomly selected residents in six major cities nationwide.
The polling firm said the margin of error for the survey was 2
percent and noted that it was not representative of the country as a
whole because it was limited to people with telephones.
</TEXT>
