<FIRST>r a AM-HeraldExaminer     03-06 0234</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Herald Examiner,0240</SECOND>
<HEAD>Herald Examiner Newspaper Workers Authorize Strike</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CITY OF COMMERCE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Reporters, janitors and other
employees of the Los Angeles Herald Examiner authorized union
leaders Sunday to call a strike against the newspaper's management
if a contract settlement was not reached soon.
   Bargaining talks were expected to continue up to the midnight
contract expiration deadline, and perhaps into Monday if progress
was made.
   Members of the Graphic Communications Union, which represents 500
of the paper's 800 employees, voted 252 to 48 to allow their
bargaining committee to either call a strike or extend negotiations,
said John Chandler, a union spokesman and the Herald's City Hall
reporter.
   Little progress was reported, however.
   ``As of what I'd heard this morning, they had not even gotten
down to talking much about what the rank-and-file would consider to
be the major economic issues, such as salaries and health plan,'' he
said.
   Management representatives could not immediately be reached for
comment.
   The paper, owned by the Hearst Corporation, has struggled for
market share against the giant Los Angeles Times _ which has more
than three times the circulation _ and has never recovered from a
bitter, decade-long period of labor strife in the 1960s and '70s.
   Union workers are demanding a three-year contract with a 25
percent wage increase the first year, as well as more staff and a
new computer system, Chandler said.
</TEXT>
