<FILEID>AP-NR-03-06-89 1119EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a i PM-PostwarIraq Adv13   03-06 0872</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Postwar Iraq, Adv 13,0904</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv13</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Mon PMs March 13 or Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Iraqi Leader Seeks Dominant Role in Arab World</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NEIL MacFARQUHAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Saddam Hussein, who has proclaimed
Iraq the victor in the war with Iran, now seeks a dominant role for
himself in the Arab world.
   But Saddam, the name he goes by in Iraq, faces growing resentment
at home because promised economic good times are slow in coming
after eight years of wartime hardship and sacrifice by his 16
million people.
   Salaries are low and prices are high.
   ``I want to get married, but I need 10,000 dinars ($30,000) for
an apartment, furniture, gold,'' said Ahmed, a 27-year-old soldier,
referring to the three items required of any perspective Middle
Eastern groom.
   He earns just 100 dinars ($300) a month in the army.
   ``I want to open an auto supply store, but I have to get out of
the army first,'' he said.
   Nevertheless, Iraqis still regard Saddam as a hero and, according
to diplomats in Baghdad, visiting Arab leaders praise his strategies
that led Iran to sue for peace last summer.
   A Western military analyst said Saddam's well-equipped,
1-million-man army has made Iraq ``a major player'' in the region.
   Iraq's new economic alliance with North Yemen, Egypt and Jordan _
all of whom lent men and materiel to Baghdad's war effort _ may
prove the first indication of how Saddam will fare as a pan-Arab
leader.
   Other Arab countries will also be watching the extent of
political and social reforms inside Iraq.
   Iraqis accepted many economic and political limitations as a
necessary price for the war, but now that it's over, the
restrictions chafe.
   ``Wherever you go you feel that the secret police are on your
back,'' said Ali, 51, who works for a retail company. ``Even the
traffic police can beat you. There's no personal freedom here.''
   Said another Iraqi: ``There is some personal freedom, but not as
much as people want.''
   Restrictions like banning foreign travel, limiting imports of
videos and barring foreign publications are widely resented, he said.
   Iraqis are forbidden to allow foreigners into their homes and
even talking to them is viewed with suspicion. So Iraqis interviewed
by visiting reporters usually give their first names or none at all.
   Certain subjects, like the Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini of Iran,
are taboo.
   Iraqi government officials say many of the restrictions were
necessary because of the war and will be lifted gradually.
   ``The trend has been approved that there be more openness in the
political system, including this matter of elections and other steps
to improve the political and social system,'' said Deputy Foreign
Minister Nizar Hamdoon. ``People should expect lots of changes over
the next few months.''
   Elections postponed since August are now set for April, with the
delay attributed to the governing Revolutionary Command Council
working out laws for new political parties Saddam is permitting to
operate.
   But Iraqi officials said the plans date back to the 1968
revolution that brought the Arab Baath Socialist Party to power.
They can now be implemented because Iraq came out of the war a more
cohesive nation.
   ``Difficult conditions existed even before the war,'' said Salah
Mukhtar, director general of the Information Ministry.
   ``But any citizen who lived through the war is qualified to
practice freedom in political life. No one who went through the war
is a threat to our government. Why should we exclude them?''
   The strongest opposition groups _ the Communists, the
fundamentalist Shiite Moslem Islamic Call and separatist Kurdish
factions _ are excluded. All were driven underground in bloody
purges.
   Information Minister Latif Nayyif Jasim said all were
``treacherous and treasonous'' for aiding Iran during the war.
   Iraq's image was tarnished by its alleged use of chemical weapons
against the Kurdish rebels last fall in a major offensive to crush
the guerrillas' campaign for an autonomous homeland.
   Saddam has declared an amnesty for many prisoners and dissidents,
but Kurdish officials described it as little more than cosmetic.
   The U.S. State Department recently singled out Iraq for its
``abysmal human rights record,'' mainly because of the assault on
the Kurds in the northern mountains.
   Diplomats said easing restrictions on personal freedom will help
Saddam deflect the heat from economic problems expected to last at
least five years.
   Iraq has an estimated $60 billion to $70 billion in war debts and
moves to expand the private business sector and secure Arab
investment have yet to make headway.
   Prices skyrocketed as private firms took over agriculture and
importing consumer goods, leaving Iraqis feeling empty handed
despite promises of postwar prosperity.
   Long lines form outside government meat stores when the monthly
ration is distributed. Volkswagen Passat cars imported from Brazil
are the only autos widely available.
   One boutique owner said she spent hours scouring the market for
decent buttons.
   ``Anything electric is very expensive. I can't afford them,''
said Abdel Hamid, 34, a veteran who was wounded seven times and lost
a kidney.
   Blistering attacks have appeared in the press. Economist Human
al-Shuma'a wrote in Al-Qadissiya that the private sector was
``soaking the sweat of the people and grabbing their daily bread.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Mon AMs March 13</NOTE>
</DOC>
