<HEAD>$adv13</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Monday, March 13</HEAD>
<HEAD>Today In History</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Today is Monday, March 13, the 72nd day of 1989. There are 293
days left in the year.
   Today's highlight in history:
   On March 13, 1852, a familiar symbol of the United States,
``Uncle Sam,'' made his debut as a cartoon character in the New York
``Lantern.''
   On this date:
   In 1639, Harvard University was named for clergyman John Harvard.
   In 1781, the planet Uranus was discovered by Sir William Herschel.
   In 1868, the impeachment trial of President Andrew Johnson began
in the U.S. Senate.
   In 1884, standard time was adopted throughout the United States.
   In 1901, the 23rd president of the United States, Benjamin
Harrison, died in Indianapolis.
   In 1906, one of the pioneers of the American suffragist movement,
Susan B. Anthony, died in Rochester, N.Y.
   In 1925, a law went into effect in Tennessee prohibiting the
teaching of evolution.
   In 1928, more than 400 people died when the San Francisquito
Valley in California was inundated with water after the St. Francis
Dam burst.
   In 1933, banks in the United States began to re-open after a
``holiday'' declared by President Franklin D. Roosevelt.
   In 1938, famed attorney Clarence S. Darrow died in Chicago.
   In 1964, in a case that shocked many, 38 residents of a New York
City neighborhood heard but failed to respond to the cries of Kitty
Genovese, 28, a bar manager who was twice attacked and fatally
stabbed as she tried to make her way home.
   In 1969, ``Apollo Nine'' splashed down, ending a mission that
included the successful testing of the lunar module.
   In 1985, funeral services were held in Moscow for the late Soviet
leader, Konstantin U. Chernenko.
   In 1986, the new government of the Philippines opened up the
presidential palace to the public, who got to see the opulence which
had surrounded deposed President Ferdinand Marcos and his wife,
Imelda.
   Ten years ago: Israeli Prime Minister Menachem Begin stunned his
country by rapidly agreeing to a new peace proposal after three days
of intense negotiations with President Jimmy Carter, and said he
would resign if the Knesset rejected the resulting treaty with Egypt.
   Five years ago: In the ``Super Tuesday'' Democratic primaries,
Gary Hart carried Florida, Massachusetts and Rhode Island, while
Walter F. Mondale was the winner in Georgia and Alabama.
   One year ago: Despite several major losses to Vice President
George Bush, Republican presidential hopeful Bob Dole said in a CBS
interview he would continue ``full bore'' to Wisconsin after the
Illinois primary.
   Today's Birthdays: Opera singer Rosalind Elias is 58.
Singer-songwriter Neil Sedaka is 50. Actress Deborah Raffin is 36.
   Thought for today: ``Man must cease attributing his problems to
his environment, and learn again to exercise his will _ his personal
responsibility in the realm of faith and morals.'' _ Albert
Schweitzer, German-born missionary and Nobel laureate (1875-1965).
</TEXT>
