<FIRST>s a BC-APN--SavingHistory Adv19-2Takes   03-06 0817</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-APN--Saving History, Adv 19-2 Takes,0838</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv19</HEAD>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, March 19</HEAD>
<HEAD>Repeat for all needing</HEAD>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<HEAD>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 3 b&amp;w photos.
ColorFoto subscribers get 2 35mm slides.)</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   
   EDITOR'S NOTE _ Changes in federal tax laws have put a chill on
the rehabilitation of historic buildings. Investment in such
projects dropped from $2.4 billion in fiscal 1985 to $866 million in
fiscal 1988, according to the National Park Service, which must
certify properties as historic for tax purposes. Here's a look at
one giant renovating firm that has fallen on hard times as a result.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>By TED DUNCOMBE</NOTE>
<NOTE>Associated Press Writer</NOTE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A developer with a reputation for saving
historic buildings threw a party last April to celebrate completion
of its most ambitious project, a $40 million refurbishing of a
19th-century railroad station in Pittsburgh.
   ``We believe it will be a grand slam home run,'' Carl E. Dranoff,
then-president and chief executive officer of Historic Landmarks for
Living, said as the station reopened with 242 luxury apartments, a
restaurant and office space.
   Less than a year later, he's in trouble, hitting just one more
long fly since the Pittsburgh opening, a 105-unit apartment building
in a former cosmetics factory in Milwaukee, Wis.
   The Philadelphia-based company is struggling to save itself,
largely because of an inability to recover from the tax-law changes
that have slashed the nation's investment in historic rehabilitation
by two-thirds in the past three years.
   Preservationists say the company's predicament symbolizes their
concern about the future of efforts to recycle old factories,
warehouses, hospitals and other threads of the nation's urban fabric.
   ``There already is a chill,'' says Ian Spatz of the
Washington-based National Trust for Historic Preservation. ``That's
not speculative. The numbers are very clear. The interest in
renovating historical buildings has crashed since the Tax Reform Act
of 1986.''
   Word of Historic Landmarks' troubles surfaced when First Fidelity
Bancorp of Newark, N.J., said in mid-December that it expected heavy
fourth-quarter losses in part because of troubled real-estate loans.
   Historic Landmarks, which had completed or planned 66 renovations
in 15 cities, soon announced the resignation of Dranoff and the
suspension of projects in Minneapolis and St. Paul, Minn., Atlantic
City, N.J., Providence, R.I., Ellicott City, Md., and Philadelphia.
   Company officials, trying to renegotiate a $46-million line of
credit and $40 million in construction loans with the bank, agreed
to an interview but then backed out.
   On Jan. 31, the company filed for bankruptcy court protection on
three partnerships set up to renovate buildings in Philadelphia,
Lancaster and Marietta, Pa., and warned in a statement the
protection may be sought for other partnerships.
   Analysts say Historic Landmarks' problems were exacerbated by
softening demand for apartment rentals in Philadelphia, where the
company has its greatest concentration of buildings.
   In addition, the company was stymied in an effort to go public in
1987 and its projects have been under scrutiny by the Internal
Revenue Service. Dranoff has said a city condominium-conversion tax
added to the anticipated costs of selling apartment buildings after
tax credits expired.
   Historic Landmarks was one of a number of companies that sprouted
after Congress in 1976 authorized major tax incentives for
preserving historically certified, income-producing properties.
   Before that, ``our tax laws favored destruction of existing
building stock, because they reimbursed the developer the cost of
the demolition and then gave him preferential depreciation rates on
his new building,'' says William J. Murtaugh, the first keeper of
the National Register of Historic Places.
   In his 1988 book, ``Keeping Time: The History and Theory of
Preservation in America,'' Murtaugh said the public and private
sector were forced to act together on preservation after World War
II because of the impact of interstate highways and urban renewal
programs.
   ``These well-funded government programs were causing major social
displacement and widespread obliteration of visual landmarks in most
parts of the country, especially in cities,'' he wrote.
   Developers took even greater interest in preservation after the
Economic Recovery Tax Act of 1981 allowed investors a 25 percent tax
credit on certified historic rehabilitations.
   But the 1986 tax law cut the historic-rehab credit to 20 percent,
limited it to $7,000 for most taxpayers and eliminated it for people
with more than $250,000 in income. Similar cuts were exacted on
low-income housing credits and non-historic restorations.
   Thus, instead of being able to raise millions of dollars from a
few wealthy investors, developers had to raise money in smaller
parcels from people with relatively moderate income.
   While some companies successfully set up partnerships that put
investors' money in a portfolio of renovations, many just switched
to other types of development.
   Investment in historic rehabilitation nationwide fell 64 percent
to $866 million in fiscal 1988 from $2.4 billion in fiscal 1985,
according to the National Park Service, which must certify
properties as historic for tax purposes.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890306-0216 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-06-89 1545EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s a BC-APN--SavingHistory Adv19-1stAdd   03-06 0809</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-APN--Saving History, Adv 19-1st Add,0832</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv19</HEAD>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, March 19</HEAD>
<HEAD>Repeat for all needing</HEAD>
<HEAD>PHILADELPHIA: tax purposes.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   ``I didn't go out and restore 300 historic buildings because I'm
a frustrated curator,'' said D. Thomas Mistick, president of Tom
Mistick &amp; Sons, a Pittsburgh firm that has worked on three projects
for Historic Landmarks.
   ``I did it because there were incentives in the tax code to work
in historic districts. And it was fun, too.''
   Other companies say they are still making a good profit by
limiting their involvement to raising the money and hiring out the
work.
   ``We generally don't act as developer unless we have to,'' says
Ellen Warren of Dover Historic Properties Inc. in Philadelphia.
``The people here are bankers and lawyers first.''
   Historic Landmarks not only has raised the money, but acted as
developer, managed the buildings after restoration and set up a
realty subsidiary to sell the buildings as condominiums.
   ``They took the approach of doing large, single projects as
opposed to a portfolio of projects,'' says Kenneth E. Banwart of
Boston Bay Capital Inc., a Boston company whose portfolio includes
eight properties this year. ``I don't want to knock them. Both
approaches can be successful, but there's a big difference.''
   Stephen E. Solms, chairman and co-founder of Historic Landmarks,
told The Philadelphia Inquirer in a 1983 interview he got into
preservation because he abhorred modern high-rise apartments and
look-alike developments.
   ``They're nothing but concrete boxes,'' he said. ``Every
apartment looks just like the one next door to it.''
   He also said he found satisfaction in converting old buildings
into housing that could attract well-paid professionals as renters
without displacing low-income residents.
   ``I buy run-down, abandoned industrial properties,'' he said.
``We're not supplanting the poor. We go into neighborhoods or areas
of the city that are languishing.''
   For years, Historic Landmarks seemed to have the Midas touch,
turning buildings covered with pigeon droppings into gleaming,
desirable apartments, complete with concierges and limo service.
   Not that everything always went smoothly with the company.
   In November 1986, 45,000 demonstrators _ by police estimate _
marched in Pittsburgh against conversion of the Pennsylvania
Railroad Station, because Mistick, acting as contractor, was using
non-union labor.
   Some 1,500 union demonstrators kept Gov. Robert P. Casey and
other dignitaries away from the $40 million project's coming-out
party last May.
   ``This demonstration is an embarrassment to everyone,'' Dranoff
said, contending one-third to one-half the project was done by union
workers.
   ``It was an open shop with bids from union and non-union,'' he
said.
   The labor troubles were nothing compared to the firestorm that
greeted Historic Landmarks' plan in mid-1987 to sell up to $25
million of common stock and $50 million in debt certificates in a
subsidiary, Landmarks for Living Inc.
   Jonathan Butcher, chairman and chief executive officer of the
Butcher &amp; Co. investment firm, filed suit in U.S. District Court,
alleging Solms and his partners were trying to defraud him of his
share in several Historic Landmarks projects.
   Butcher's attorneys argued that Solms and his partners ``are
transplanting the heart and brain of the organization which has
taken years to build and are leaving Butcher with a lifeless corpse,
without any compensation whatsoever.''
   Solms' attorneys contended Butcher and a company he formed,
Deilwydd Historic Properties, had bargained away their interest in
the future of Historic Landmarks or its subsidiaries.
   Although Butcher never tried to stop the stock offering, just to
share in the proceeds, it was never completed. An unidentified
spokesman for Historic Landmarks told The Wall Street Journal in
December the plan was halted by the 1987 stock market crash, not
Butcher's lawsuit.
   For preservationists, the work Historic Landmarks and similar
companies have done is ample testimony for the need to restore some
aspects of the tax credits taken away in 1986.
   ``I think the whole purpose of the tax incentive program was to
connect the historic buildings to investors,'' said Spatz of the
National Trust. ``In 1986, that connection was broken.''
   A bill introduced on Feb. 2 by Reps. Barbara B. Kennelly,
D-Conn., and Richard T. Schulze, R-Pa., and by Sens. John C.
Danforth, R-Mo., and George J. Mitchell, D-Maine, would raise the
historic-rehab credit to the first $20,000 of a taxpayer's net
liability, plus 20 percent of anything over $20,000.
   It also removes the credits from rules restricting the type of
income against which they can be applied and contains safeguards to
prevent abuse of the credits by people trying to avoid any tax.
   ``The tax code has always been a tool of social policy,'' said
Mistick, the Pittsburgh developer. ``So we can say, look, we need
the urban investment and we can direct that investment through the
tax code, or we can address the problem head on and provide hard
money for such investment.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, March 19</NOTE>
</DOC>
