<DOCNO> AP890306-0224 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-06-89 1420EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s i BC-Soviet-Campaign'89 Adv12   03-06 1171</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Soviet-Campaign '89, Adv 12,1206</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv12</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, March 12, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Soviet Election Campaign is Firing up Passions</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds, note elections are March 26</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto Planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN-THOR DAHLBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MURMANSK, U.S.S.R. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democracy, Gorbachev style, went to
work aboard a Soviet fishing vessel off South America. Its 50
officers and sailors met during a storm to nominate a candidate for
a new national assembly back home.
   Slicing through 40-foot foam-flecked waves, the 18,000-ton Kola
Bay covered 400 nautical miles before its crew could agree on who
they thought should represent them in the halls of power in Moscow,
said first mate Konstantin S. Atroshnikov.
   Democracy, Gorbachev style, pre-empted the movie ``King Kong'' in
the palace of culture of this port city 1,000 miles north of Moscow,
famed as the destination of the World War II Allied convoys carrying
guns and Spam to the embattled Soviets.
   In snow-coated Kirov Palace, where on other days the great ape
had roared on the screen, more than 700 delegates from city
workplaces and neighborhoods gathered to whittle down the list of
candidates to be proposed to voters. It took them nine hours to pare
the list of six names to three.
   With passion and skepticism, a modest measure of ballyhoo and a
big dose of confusion, this city of 440,000 and the Soviet Union at
large are experiencing their first nationwide election campaign
where voters will be allowed a choice, instead of having a single
candidate put up by the Communist Party.
   ``I'm running because the law now gives me that right, and I want
to state my positions,'' said one Murmansk candidate, Andrei A.
Zolotkov, an engineer who has worked on nuclear-powered icebreakers.
``That's my only goal.''
   Said the chief of Murmansk's Communist Party apparatus, Vladimir
P. Khachenko: ``In the past, we used to gather in committee and say:
`How many women candidates do we need here, or how many workers
there?' This time not a single candidate has been endorsed by the
city (party) committee.''
   President Mikhail S. Gorbachev, who championed the
multi-candidate elections, calls the exercise a ``school of
democracy.'' He says Soviet political life must be opened to greater
citizen participation if his program for ``perestroika'' (social and
economic change) is to succeed.
   That's the theory.
   In practice, there are clear signs of pressure from the party in
some sections of the country, like the conservative Ukraine, to have
a party-backed candidate become the voter's sole option in the
elections March 26 for the newly created Council of People's
Deputies.
   The electoral changes, approved in December by the Soviet
parliament, also create what some Soviets call ``filters'' at
several levels to block candidates who can't garner majority support
on nominating panels.
   One famous victim of the ``filters'' was Andrei D. Sakharov, the
dissident and Nobel Peace Prize laureate, whose candidacy was not
backed by the Academy of Sciences. The choice of the Kola Bay's
crew, the captain of another fishing boat, never made it through a
subsequent nominating meeting held by representatives of Sevriba,
the enterprise that runs the Kola Bay and more than 70 other
Murmansk-based fishing vessels.
   As a result of the meeting in late February at the culture
palace, voters in Murmansk's Territorial Election District No. 224
will choose on March 26 from among a doctor, the chief of a fishing
trawler fleet, and the 37-year-old Zolotkov.
   What's emerging in their fledgling campaigns is a pronounced
accent on local issues, such as the lack of housing that's keeping
50,000 Murmansk residents waiting for better apartments; the
rationing of sugar, sausage and other staples; the lack of
polyclinics in new neighborhoods, and the fouling of the environment
by industry in this once pristine region north of the Arctic Circle.
   Zolotkov's nine-minute speech at the Kirov Palace never mentioned
Gorbachev but detailed the problems of his fellow city dwellers and
had a distinct ``let's send a message to Moscow'' tone.
   ``When you're talking about people's lives, you must make
demands,'' he declared.
   According to Khachenko, there's little if any difference in the
candidates' platforms: ``What people want is a deputy with courage
who will fight for what he believes in.''
   What's also becoming apparent in Murmansk is a clannishness, or
splitting along professional lines.
   ``The city's doctors are campaigning for the doctor and are in
the street passing out leaflets,'' Khachenko said. The captain,
meanwhile, has surrounded himself with other captains.
   A local editor, Viktor V. Prostikhin, is trying to shake off
attempts by Murmansk's electoral commission to force his Arctic Star
newspaper, run by the Murmansk Shipping Company, to give equal space
to other candidates besides Zolotkov, a shipping company employee.
   ``That's pressure on the press,'' Prostikhin maintained.
   If Gorbachev's new electoral system is a school, Zolotkov is a
budding star pupil.
   The lanky Murmansk native with gray-streaked black hair wears a
burgandy tie and light blue shirt, because allies advised him to.
   However, the engineer drew the line at loosening his collar and
tie while campaigning, as his advisers suggested.
   ``Somebody told me that's what American senators do, but it
wouldn't look proper here,'' Zolotkov said in an interview, between
puffs on an imported Pall Mall cigarette.
   Before the Kirov Palace meeting, Zolotkov bought time on an
electric sign that shines down on Murmansk's main square.
   ``VOTE FOR ANDREI ALEKSEYEICH ZOLOTKOV,'' it said.
   He wanted to rent a sound truck but relented when told that the
move might offend other candidates.
   His character became a campaign issue when one participant in the
Kirov Palace meeting asked him if he would have the courage to
publicly oppose a decision by Gorbachev.
   ``Yes,'' he responded.
   ``I already have disagreements with the election law,'' Zolotkov
said. ``Why should a member of the (party) Central Committee have
more votes than I do?''
   The Gorbachev-backed law gives the Communist Party the right to
directly fill 100 of the assembly's 2,250 seats.
   Whether a candidate like Zolotkov can win March 26 is a subject
of keen debate in Murmansk.
   ``Perestroika so far here is more slogans that deeds,'' said Yura
Verbitsk, 24, who works at a plant that burns garbage to generate
electricity. ``There are a lot of people still around from the era
of (Leonid I.) Brezhnev,'' the late Soviet president.
   But the fact Zolotkov even made it to the ballot is a sign of
changing times. To become the candidate proposed by the Murmansk
Shipping Co., he beat out a man who would have been an easy winner
in past elections, an icebreaker captain awarded the coveted title
of Hero of Socialist Labor.
   Zolotkov, a candidate for membership in the Communist Party, says
he is no expert on economics or legal matters but wants to go to
Moscow to make Gorbachev's vision of Soviet democracy work.
   ``If one party is directing things, that's exactly why we need a
stronger legislature,'' he said. ``By my activities, I want to
demonstrate that there can be controls on power.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, March 12</NOTE>
