<FIRST>a e BC-WKD--FilmReview Adv00   03-06 0558</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-WKD--Film Review, Adv 00,0570</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv00</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Anytime</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>At the Movies: ``True Believer''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The American judicial system, that great theater of the absurd,
seems to inspire more movies than any subject except love.
   The newest addition to the pantheon is ``True Believer,'' the
saga of one burned-out lawyer and the murder case which offers him
redemption.
   In the capable hands of director Joseph Ruben and actor James
Woods, the imaginative story of lawyer Eddie Dodd becomes a genuine
edge-of-your-seat thriller with an ending that, for once, is not
telegraphed in advance.
   Believable? Well, one can't ask for everything. Suspension of
disblief is the name of the game in Wesley Strick's cleverly crafted
script.
   We meet Dodd at the nadir of his brilliant legal career. Once a
champion of the underdog, a fighter for unpopular causes, this aging
radical with the graying pony tail, has been reduced to defending
drug dealers. He says he's fighting for the constitution, but
neither he nor we believe that.
   With the arrival of his fresh-faced, hero worshipping new law
clerk (Robert Downey Jr.), Dodd is reminded of his past glories but
gives the apprentice defense lawyer his most cynical assessment of
the accused: ``They're all guilty.''
   That pronouncement quickly is followed by the arrival at Dodd's
office of a tearful mother seeking help for her imprisoned son. She
claims the son, a Korean-American, was wrongly convicted of a
Chinatown murder.
   Dodd takes the case, and with that begins piecing together a
puzzle so complicated we aren't quite sure where it leads. When the
revelations pile up toward the end, they are stunning.
   The pace of ``True Believer'' is so fast that we have little time
to question its real-world underpinnings. It will be hours before we
begin to wonder why Eddie Dodd, hated by law enforcement, would
tempt fate by openly smoking pot in his law office. Or why the most
simple fact involving the location of the coroner's office eludes
everyone on this case for years.
   But the plot is complex enough to distract us from such concerns.
And the peformances _ particularly Woods' _ make it all seem
plausible.
   Downey is appealing as the wide-eyed young law clerk who helps
crack the case. Charles Hallahan is memorable as the key prosecution
witness and Kurtwood Smith gives a cool malevolence to the district
attorney. Yuji Okumoto as the accused murderer and Miguel Fernandes
as one of several villains, give strong supporting performances.
   Production designer Lawrence Miller adds insight into Eddie
Dodd's character with his cluttered office and the lower Manhattan
world he inhabits.
   Woods puts his stamp so strongly on Eddie Dodd that it's hard to
imagine anyone else playing this off-beat character. With such
successful casting, could there be a sequel in the works?
   ``True Believer'' is rated R for violence.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Motion Picture Association of America rating definitions:
   G _ General audiences. All ages admitted.
   PG _ Parental guidance suggested. Some material may not be
suitable for children.
   PG-13 _ Special parental guidance strongly suggested for children
under 13. Some material may be inappropriate for young children.
   R _ Restricted. Under 17 requires accompanying parent or adult
guardian.
   X _ No one under 17 admitted. Some states may have higher age
restrictions.
</TEXT>
