<FIRST>a e BC-WKD--HomeVideo Adv00   03-06 0305</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-WKD--Home Video, Adv 00,0321</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv00</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Anytime</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Video View: Home Video Reviews</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SCOTT WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   
   ``Spike of Bensonhurst'' (Virgin Vision. VHS-Beta, $89.95. Rated
R)
   
   I fell asleep midway through this thoroughly confused and
confusing movie, woke up, dutifully rewound and watched again and I
still don't understand what happens in ``Spike of Bensonhurst.'' Or
why or how. And it didn't make me care.
   Spike (Sasha Mitchell) is your basic no-talent club fighter who
gets involved with Angel (the amusing Maria Pitillo), daughter of
the local don (Ernest Borgnine) and gets her pregnant as a kind of
career move.
   Of course the don wants no part of Spike, who is exiled from
Bensonhurst (in Brooklyn) and he impregnates a pal's sister _ the
achingly lovely Talisa Soto, whose luminous beauty is utterly wasted
here.
   I swear I don't know why any of this movie happens the way it
does. None of the characters are real. The actors are pretending
they are real, but it's really easy to see they are not _ all except
Talisa Soto, who wisely says little.
   ``Spike of Bensonhurst'' is a disquieting thing to see: It's not
like real life. It's not like a movie fantasy. It's not funny. It's
not scary. It's not anything.
   _ By Scott Williams, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Motion Picture Association of America rating definitions:
   G _ General audiences. All ages admitted.
   PG _ Parental guidance suggested. Some material may not be
suitable for children.
   PG-13 _ Special parental guidance strongly suggested for children
under 13. Some material may be inappropriate for young children.
   R _ Restricted. Under 17 requires accompanying parent or adult
guardian.
   X _ No one under 17 admitted. Some states may have higher age
restrictions.
  
