<FILEID>AP-NR-03-06-89 1301EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e BC-WKD--RecordReviews Adv00   03-06 0905</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-WKD--Record Reviews, Adv 00,0934</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv00</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Anytime</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>In the Groove: Record Reviews</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   
   ``New York'' (Sire) _ Lou Reed
   
   ``You can't beat 2 guitars, bass, drum.'' Lou Reed states this in
the liner notes and proves it in each of the 14 songs on this album.
His four-piece band turns out essential rock 'n' roll, lean and
muscular. And this close-to-the-bone playing is the only proper
accompaniment for the down-to-the-marrow lyrics of Reed's bleak look
at his city.
   The wild side of city life that Reed once glorified has turned
brutal in the age of crack and AIDS. Drugged-out parents beat their
kids, love and sex are just a brief escape from the crack wars, the
ghosts of AIDS victims haunt the ``Halloween Parade'' and about all
you can depend on is ``the worst always happening.''
   The album title might as well include a date _ sometime in late
1988. References to specific crime cases and to Morton Downey Jr.,
Jimmy Swaggart and Rudy Giuliani threaten to turn the album into the
audio equivalent of one day's issue of a tabloid newspaper _ lacking
in the timelessness or universality that can touch people years
later or miles away.
   But just as a human interest feature story in a newspaper can be
more gripping than the latest shock headline, ``New York'' is most
successful when Reed focuses on individuals. In ``Romeo Had
Juliette,'' Romeo Rodriguez comes in from the crack-ridden streets
for a few moment's escape in bed with his Juliette. In ``Dirty
Blvd.'' young Pedro finds a book on magic in a garbage can and sits
in his welfare hotel room wishing he could make himself disappear.
   The album's lyrical strengths and shortcomings are highlighted by
a mix in which Reed's unvarnished vocal is featured prominently. But
if ``New York'' proves to have staying power, credit the two
guitars, bass, drum.
   _ By Dan Murphy, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   ``Money for Nothing'' (Warner Bros.) _ Dire Straits
   
   This greatest-hits collection, coming as it does in the midst of
Mark Knopfler's public nonchalance about the future of Dire Straits,
if any, has an air of finality to it.
   But this is no ``Crossroads''-style retrospective; rather, it's
the obligatory, single-disc collection with the obligatory live
track ``not previously available'' _ in this case, the gentle
``Portobello Belle.''
   Much of the material is, then, Dire Straits' ``hits.'' But the
band has had few real hit singles; they are an album group, and most
fans will already have many of these songs. One notable omission is
``Skateaway'' from ``Making Movies,'' which became a semi-video-hit
in the early days of MTV.
   ``Money for Nothing'' _ this album, not the single, which is
indeed included _ also has one major fault: an unfortunate remixing
of the fine dance track, ``Twisting by the Pool.'' This time, the
sound is thinner, and some of Knopfler's vocals _ about the closest
his singing ever came to a rock 'n' roll rave-up _ have actually
been deleted.
   Still, many of these songs remain certifiably brilliant. Mark
Knopfler was fond of introducing his group in concert as the ``Dire
Straits rock 'n' roll band,'' and it has been that milieu, not his
session work or his film scores, that stands as his highest
testament.
   _ By Robert Byrd, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   Concerto No. 2, Op. 18 in C minor; Etudes-Tableaux, Op. 39, by
Sergei Rachmaninoff; Evgeny Kissin and the London Symphony
Orchestra, conducted by Valery Gergiev (RCA Victor)
   
   For an 18-year-old Russian pianist who played his first recital
seven years ago, why not debut on disc with Rachmaninoff's virtuosic
and most recorded of his four piano concerti. Evgeny Kissin, who
looks about 14 in his picture, gives a sure reading of this lush,
difficult work. He has plenty of technique and plays without
affectation.
   What's missing is a more vivid sense of mood and character
changes in contrasting sections _ the different flavors shown by
Gary Graffman, say, with Leonard Bernstein and the New York
Philharmonic on an older CBS recording. Then there's always
Sviatoslav Richter's performance on DG, and of course the composer's
own 1929 version with the Philadelphia Orchestra.
   The sound of the RCA recording is clear, though sometimes the
piano is a bit mushy, perhaps the result of a little too much pedal.
Valery Gergiev, music director of the Kirov Opera, and the LSO
provide solid support, particularly with some gorgeous wind solos in
the second movement.
   Rachmaninoff wrote the work after being treated for a paralyzing
depression brought on by the failure of his first symphony in 1897.
He dedicated the concerto to Dr. Nicolai Dahl, who helped his
depression with hypnosis, repeating _ as Racn to write your concerto. ...
you will work with great
facility. ... the concerto will be of an excellent quality.''' He
did. He did. It is. Kissin's performance is excellent but not
hypnotic.
   It's nice to see the infrequently recorded Etudes-Tableaux
coupled with the concerto. They have a Chopinesque flavor to them,
varying in moods. Kissin is more successful in the more intimate,
quieter moments. By the way, why include only six of the nine etudes
in Op. 39? At only 59:53, the disc has plenty of room to include the
other three.
   _ By Daniel Wakin, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Release Anytime</NOTE>
