<FIRST>a e BC-WKD--Gilliam Adv17-19   03-06 0931</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-WKD--Gilliam, Adv 17-19,0954</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv17</HEAD>
<HEAD>$Adv18</HEAD>
<HEAD>$Adv19</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Weekend Editions, March 17-19 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Star Watch: The Adventures of Terry Gilliam</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN HORN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BURBANK, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Director Terry Gilliam doesn't make
box-office ticket machines sing. His movies aren't stuffed with car
chases, naked women or automatic weaponry. He prefers strange
characters, weird settings and unusual endings.
   Most of what Gilliam does rubs corporate Hollywood the wrong way.
And that's why the arrival of his new film, ``The Adventures of
Baron Munchausen,'' is such a minor miracle.
   While many other Hollywood filmmakers produce predictable, mass
appeal fare, Gilliam grinds out ruminations on fantasy, idealism,
history and death.
   ``I'm desperately trying to make popular films because they speak
to a large audience,'' Gilliam said on a recent visit from his home
in London. ``But I also want to turn people a little bit off the
path they are charging down.''
   Gilliam's past films have been praised by critics as much for
what the movies do as for what they don't do. Both 1981's ``Time
Bandits,'' about a schoolboy's exotic travels through the past, and
1985's ``Brazil,'' a bleak scrutiny of a nonsensical future, refused
to surrender their inventive premises.
   ``I had a very early talk with producer Arnon Milchan when we
started `Brazil,' '' Gilliam said. ``I said, `Arnon, we have to
approach this film in a very specific way. We have to think of it as
the most spectacular failure the world has ever seen. Because the
minute we start to think of it as a great film, or a good film or a
popular film _ any of those things _ we then start compromising.'''
   Four years in the making, ``Baron Munchausen'' fits no mold
either. In visually overwhelming style, the movie chronicles the
fantastic travels of a 10-year-old girl (Sarah Polley) and the
legendary German calvary officer Baron Karl Friedrich Hieronymus von
Munchausen (John Neville), who was known for his exaggerated tales.
(His exploits were chronicled by the German writer Rudolf Erich
Raspe.)
   The two, trapped in an 18th-century European city surrounded by
threatening armies, set out in an improvised hot air balloon to save
their compatriots. The couple's odyssey takes them to the moon, the
center of the Earth and the stomach of a giant sea monster.
   While Gilliam says the film should appeal to a broad audience,
its lack of stars and British flavor will present a marketing
challenge to Columbia Pictures. And Gilliam, already having survived
the film's difficult production, knows he's not yet out of the woods.
   ``There are a lot of people here,'' he said with a sweep of his
hand toward Hollywood, ``who have worked very hard at training an
audience. I think America is the most brainwashed country in the
world.'' Brainwashed, Gilliam said, into thinking that everything is
safe, and nothing unusual is worth experiencing.
   ``McDonald's hamburgers are safe. They're not good or bad.
They're safe. You know exactly what you're going to get.
   ``Everything here is so infantile. There is no future, there is
no past, and the present is reduced to a nanosecond. People are just
seeing the same thing over and over again. They're being pandered to
all the time and their vision of the world gets smaller and
smaller.''
   Only a few moviegoers these days now want to be challenged, he
said.
   ``It terrifies me. What happens is that the handful of people who
are doing really interesting things end up only speaking to a very
small audience. And that's what I don't want to do.''
   Whether U.S. audiences love or hate ``Baron Munchausen'' isn't
exactly the point. What Gilliam is after is shaking the seats in
which they so casually slump.
   ``When my kids were younger, I would read fairy tales to them _
`Red Riding Hood.' And it's bowdlerized. Suddenly, the wolf doesn't
really eat Granny. Granny actually has been somehow hiding _ she'd
run and hide in the cupboard.
   ``And the woodsman has been turned into daddy, who chases the
wolf away. The whole point is just gone. And those fairy tales are
meant to be frightening. They're meant to scare the kids. Children
should know the world is not just a jolly place.
   ``And we just sit here and tell the kids it's all `Sesame Street'
time _ everything is wonderful. I don't mind that, but I think the
balance is gone. ... People don't want to see depressing endings.
But most of the great works of art tended to be tragedies.''
   Unlike ``Brazil,'' a movie so terrifying that Universal Pictures
originally refused to release it, ``Baron Munchausen'' celebrates
the triumph of whimsy.
   ``I wanted to make an upbeat movie,'' Gilliam said. ``I wanted
fantasy to win. I was making a film primarily for my daughters (ages
eight and 12) _ and to tell this fairy tale, not another fairy
tale.''
   Gilliam, 38, a graduate of Los Angeles' Occidental College and a
frequent collaborator with the British comedy troupe Monty Python,
said that as pleased as he is with ``Baron Munchausen,'' he'd never
want to repeat the experience.
   ``You begin to wonder whether it is worth four years of your
life. I wouldn't do it again. I hated the thing and I actually
wanted to quit.
   ``It was the worst nightmare I've ever been involved in. By week
two, I wanted out. It was like punishment for something I'd done. I
actually felt like Job.''
   Out of such anguish, though, do wonderful endings sometimes
follow.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions, March 17-19</NOTE>
</DOC>
