<SECOND>BC-WKD--Mandrell, Adv 17-19,0846</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv17</HEAD>
<HEAD>$Adv18</HEAD>
<HEAD>$Adv19</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Weekend Editions, March 17-19, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Nashville Sound: Movie `Big' Inspires New Mandrell Act</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOE EDWARDS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As country music performer Louise
Mandrell left her dressing room to entertain recently, backup singer
Pedro Tomas greeted her with the show business phrase ``break a
leg.''
   ``I probably will,'' she quipped.
   The reason she fears for her lower extremities is that she has
just added some fancy footwork to her Las Vegas-style act. Inspired
by the recent movie ``Big,'' she has purchased a ``walking piano''
like the one actor Tom Hanks played in the hit film.
   The instrument is a flat, long series of adjoining keys that sit
on the ground. They are played by stepping on them.
   Mandrell, 34, whose sisters, Barbara and Irlene, also are country
music performers, is now using the unusual piano in her act.
   ``It's a novelty,'' she said in an interview before playing the
instrument on The Nashville Network on cable TV. ``It's a toy that
will be interesting to people. It's fun; we've been giggling half
the day away when we practice.''
   The electronic piano, which costs $15,000, weighs 600 pounds and
is 14 feet long. It has 40 keys (24 white and 16 black) which
require 30 pounds of pressure to make a sound. It came in two
sections, and her road crew put it together and made some technical
adjustments to amplify the sound to make it better for settings such
as showrooms.
   She will place a mirror behind her so the audience will be able
to watch the intricate foot work.
   ``It's a toy,'' she said. ``An expensive toy.''
   Three other members of her act will join her on the keys. They
hop on and off and quickly move to different spots along the keys.
The performance looks something like a Chinese fire drill where all
four have hot feet.
   She didn't have to hire a choreographer to take advantage of her
costly new prop.
   ``It's not really dancing,'' she said. ``It's playing an
instrument with your feet.''
   In the movie, Hanks is a boy who suddenly physically becomes a
man but responds at the level of a child. He and his boss, a toy
company executive, hop on the piano at the toy store and play a
``Chopsticks'' duet.
   ``I loved it,'' Mandrell said about the film. ``Movies usually
bomb when I love them, but not this one. I love kids. Tom Hanks was
believable as a child. I'm a big fan of his.''
   R.C. Bannon, her husband who is a country songwriter, suggested
they buy one and put it in her act. They called a New York City toy
store, ordered one and it arrived crated up in Nashville accompanied
by a piece of paper with a telephone number to call with questions.
   She began rehearsing on the piano in February. She knows of no
other performer who has incorporated the instrument into his or her
act.
   ``It's not like the piano where you just sit and do your piece,''
she said. ``Believe me, it's a lot of work.
   ``I play the (regular) piano, so it's not like a whole new
experience. And I dance, so the experience helped.''
   Mandrell, known to many TV viewers for her shampoo commercials,
said she won't be too worried about hitting a wrong key. ``The fans
like me because I'm not perfect,'' she said.
   The first two songs she learned on her new instrument are ``Down
Yonder'' and ``The William Tell Overture.''
   ```Down Yonder' is a standard country song,'' she said. ``The
country music fans know `The William Tell Overture' but it reaches
the non-country fans too. It's challenging.''
   She doesn't plan to carry the new piano to the dusty fairs where
nearly all country music stars perform in the summer.
   ``It's too big, too fragile. I don't think it could endure the
road. But people could set it up at home and it would last forever.''
   She and her sisters starred in the NBC-TV show ``Barbara Mandrell
and the Mandrell Sisters'' for two seasons beginning in 1980.
Louise, whose specialty is playing the fiddle, now performs in Las
Vegas about 12 weeks a year plus makes records and does other
appearances.
   Irlene, whose talent runs more toward comedy, is currently on the
syndicated TV show ``Hee Haw.'' Barbara appears periodically on TV
specials and has recently resumed her recording career.
   Louise recently has been the opening act for ageless George Burns.
   ``He watched every one of my shows and made all these cute
comments. He's really a lot of fun,'' she said.
   She said he's amusing even offstage and enjoys fostering his
image as a ladies' man. He sent her candy one day with this note
attached:
   ``We were great together last night.''
</TEXT>
