<FIRST>a a BC-EXP--MeasurementMarvels Adv09   03-06 0553</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-EXP--Measurement Marvels, Adv 09,0565</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv09</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Thursday, March 9, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>NASA Lab on Leading Edge of Measurement Technology</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL BASKERVILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HAMPTON, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bridges, buildings, trains and planes that
monitor their own structural well-being sound like science fiction,
but they're results of new technology that lets scientists test
things without destroying them.
   ``Our work is like re-inventing the wheel and making it work
better,'' said physicist Joseph S. Heyman, who runs the
Non-Destructive Evaluation Laboratory he started in 1971 at NASA's
Langley Research Center.
   The lab uses an array of measurement techniques _ thermal
diffusion, ultrasonics, acoustics, magnetism, X-rays, lasers and
holography _ to probe for internal defects in objects like space
shuttle solid rocket motors, satellites, airplane wings, train
wheels and railroad tracks _ and even ordinary bolts.
   Then there are ``smart'' materials that take care of themselves.
   ``We're investigating how to incoporate sensors directly into
materials,'' Heyman said. ``It's easy with fiber-like materials like
composites _ a fiber optic line is buried in the structure. An
aircraft wing can be made the same way, and the same applies to
larger structure like the space station.''
   The technology is especially critical for the space station
expected to be built in thes, lasers and
holography _ to probe for internal defects in objects like space
shuttle solid rocket motors, satellites, airplane wings, train
wheels and railroad tracks _ and even ordinary bolts.
   Then there are ``smart'' materials that take care of themselves.
   ``We're investigating how to incoporate sensors directly into
materials,'' Heyman said. ``It's easy with fiber-like materials like
composites _ a fiber optic line is buried in the structure. An
aircraft wing can be made the same way, and the same applies to
larger structure like the space station.''
   The technology is especially critical for the space station
expected to be built in the 1990s because it will be a permanently
orbiting platform bombarded by cosmic dust and stressed by
temperature differences. Less glamorous would be its use in bridges,
buildings, oil platforms and pipelines, ``anything where you need to
measure strain, stress and temperature,'' said Heyman.
   Smart materials will sense that something may be malfunctioning
before a major problem develops, he said. ``This nervous system
we're building will be able to sense when we need help. I'm talking
about the whole structure as a sensor. It can measure with
phenomenal sensitivity.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Texas A&amp;M Scientists In Search Of The Perfect Grass</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLLEGE STATION, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As a plant, grass is taken more or
less for granted. It grows. It gets mowed, watered and fertilized.
It grows more.
   ``There's not just that much attention to it,'' said Milton
Engelke, a turf researcher for Texas A&amp;M University. ``But
everybody's got grass to cut.''
   Engelke, who estimates he's one of just a dozen turf breeders in
the United States, would like to see the care given to grass become
even easier. He and a staff of 11 have 20 acres of grass in College
Station, Dallas and El Paso.
   One objective of their research is to give the homeowner ``a much
higher quality plant with less input, less care, less maintenance,''
he said. ``And in the program we're introducing grasses that won't
have to be mowed as frequently or grasses that produce little or no
clippings.''
   Homeowners, though, aren't the only people who stand to benefit
from Engelke's research. Most people believe turf is just there to
look pretty, but its main purpose is to stabilize and conserve the
landscape.
   Engelke hopes to introduce two new grasses this year to the
grass-growing industry _ a $25 billion business nationwide. One is a
buffalo grass capable of growing from South Texas to the northern
United States; the other is a zoysia grass adaptable along the
southern tier of states from California to Georgia.
   The buffalo grass will be introduced to growers this year and
available to the public in about three years. It would grow to only
about four inches, need little or no fertilizer and pesticides, and
crowd out less desirable grasses.
   Engelke wants it to be called ``Prairie Buffalo Grass'' because
it reminds him of the rippling, wind-blown grass crossed by prairie
schooners.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv March 9</NOTE>
