<FILEID>AP-NR-03-06-89 0748EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Time-Warner     03-06 1031</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Time-Warner,1067</SECOND>
<HEAD>Time, Warner Chiefs Expect Harmony And Few Changes In $18 Billion
Merger</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOYCE M. ROSENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It took two years of negotiations before Time
Inc. and Warner Communications Inc. could agree to create the
world's biggest media and entertainment concern through an $18
billion merger. But the executives who will head the new company say
their protracted talks have paved the way to a harmonious future.
   ``I don't know of an item we didn't explore,'' Warner Chairman
Steven J. Ross said Sunday. ``That is one of the things that makes
me feel very secure in the future.''
   Time and Warner announced Saturday they would join forces in a
merger of equals that would value the combined company, Time Warner
Inc., at $18 billion and would rank it as the biggest media
conglomerate in the world, followed by Bertlesmann AG of West
Germany. Time Warner would have projected annual revenues of $10
billion, while Bertlesmann recorded 1987 revenue of $6 billion.
   The agreement between Time and Warner followed two years of
on-again, off-again talks between the two New York-based companies.
The most-recent hiatus occurred as Warner pursued a $1.2 billion
buyout of Lorimar Telepictures Corp., but the negotiations picked up
steam after Warner completed that acquisition in January.
   Saturday's announcement also followed years of takeover
speculation about Time that sparked periodic surges in the company's
stock price. The company shored up its defenses from time to time,
most recently by extending its stock buyback plan and amending its
shareholder rights plan in January.
   Time Inc. Chairman J. Richard Munro _ who will serve as
co-chairman and co-chief executive officer of the new company along
with Ross _ said Sunday of the merger, ``This is an offensive move,
not a defensive move.''
   However, it is impossible to ignore the fact that the combination
of Time and Warner literally gives the two companies solidarity in
the face of a trend toward consolidation in the media industry.
Publishers including Rupert Murdoch and Robert Maxwell have gone on
shopping sprees in recent years, building media conglomerates that
would have found either Time or Warner to be an attractive takeover
candidate.
   The deal calls for Warner shareholders to receive 0.465 share of
Time for each share of Warner they own. Since there are potentially
177.2 million Warner common shares, and Time closed Friday at
$109.12{ a share, that puts a value on Warner of about $9 billion if
the deal had closed Friday.
   In addition, there are 56.6 million shares of Time outstanding,
giving it a market value of a little more than $6 billion based on
Friday's close. Warner stock closed at $45.87{ on Friday.
   Debt and preferred shares account for the balance of the $18
billion market value of the proposed new company.
   The deal is subject to approval by shareholders of both companies
and by the federal government.
   Because the deal is a merger of equals rather than an
acquisition, it cannot be directly compared to such megadeals as the
record $24.53 billion leveraged buyout of RJR Nabisco Inc. by
Kohlberg Kravis Roberts &amp; Co. last month.
   Munro said in an interview there was no one factor that enabled
the two sides to finally reach agreement.
   ``I'm not sure anything happened,'' he said. ``I think there is a
certain time when things really begin to come together.''
   The price of the merger was not a problem, according to Ross.
``Ninety percent of the discussions had to do with people, logistics
and future plans,'' he said.
   Both executives said the congeniality of their contacts over the
past two years cemented a relationship that will make it easy for
them to work together as co-CEOs.
   It won't be the first Ross has served as a co-CEO. He and William
Frankel shared the top job at Warner from 1967 until Frankel's death
in 1971.
   Munro and Ross will serve together until Munro, 58, retires and
becomes chairman of the executive committee of the combined company.
   Munro will be succeeded as co-CEO by N.J. Nicholas Jr., currently
the president of Time Inc. and who will hold that same post at Time
Warner.
   Upon the eventual retirement of Ross, who is 61, Nicholas is
expected to be sole head of Time Warner.
   Few immediate changes are expected in the structure of the new
company. Ross and Munro said there were no plans to sell any parts
of either Warner or Time, and they did not expect any layoffs as a
result of the combination.
   Ross was reluctant to discuss what Time Warner's plans were, but
did say he expected the biggest impact of the merger to be on the
company's overseas operations.
   Time is the nation's leading magazine company, with such titles
as Time, People and Sports Illustrated, along with Time-Life Books
and the Book-of-the-Month Club.
   Warner has major movie and television production interests,
including Warner Brothers and Warner Brothers Television and Warner
Cable Communications.
   Munro predicted the Warner cable television operations would be
merged with Time's, creating the second-largest cable operation in
the country, behind Tele-Communications Inc. of Denver. Time's cable
holdings include Home Box Office and Cinemax.
   Munro also expected Warner's book division to become part of
Time's larger publishing empire.
   The merger announcement came nearly two months after Warner
completed its long-delayed acquisition of Lorimar. Warner and
Lorimar agreed on a merger last May, but the deal wasn't finalized
until January because of stumbling blocks raised by Chris-Craft
Industries Inc., Warner's largest stockholder.
   Ross and Chris-Craft Chairman Herbert Siegel have been at
loggerheads for years, quarreling not only about Lorimar, but about
Ross' salary and the makeup of the Warner board.
   How much of a thorn Siegel will be in the side of Time Warner
remains to be seen. Ross said it was not yet known if Siegel, who
sits on the Warner board, will also be a director of Time Warner.
   Siegel's stake in the new company will decline to between 6
percent and 7 percent from his current 11 percent Warner share,
Warner officials said.
   Chris-Craft bought its stake of Warner in 1984 to help Warner
fight a takeover attempt by Murdoch's News Corp.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
