<FIRST>u f PM-Japan-Markets     03-06 0245</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0256</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar, Stocks Fall</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar edged lower against the Japanese yen and
share prices also fell on the Tokyo Stock Exchange today.
   The dollar started the week at 127.55 yen, down 0.57 yen from
Friday's 128.12-yen close. It closed at 127.63 yen after ranging
between 127.50 yen and 127.68 yen. It had edged up 2.12 yen over
four trading days last week.
   ``The market wanted to test the dollar's lower depths, but
commercial buying orders were too strong,'' said Kaneo Ogino, a
dealer with Goldman Sachs in Tokyo.
   ``The dollar is still mildly bearish and will move in a tight
range for the time being,'' he added.
   Dealers said market activity wavered without strong direction and
people were taking a ``wait-and-see'' attitude because of concern
over possible Japanese interest rates hikes.
   ``This week, people are waiting for a conference Wednesday by
Bank of Japan Governor Satoshi Sumita and the release of U.S.
unemployment figures due out Friday,'' said one dealer with a major
Japanese securities firm.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225
selected issues, a 73.63-point loser last week, shed another 123.24
points, or 0.38 percent, today to close at 31,876.86.
   Investors moved to the sidelines ahead of the settlement of March
futures contracts scheduled for Tuesday, dealers said.
   ``They are also watching the monetary stance of the Bank of Japan
and whether West Germany will raise its discount rate or not,''
Ogino added.
</TEXT>
