<FIRST>r f PM-Eastern-Q&amp;A     03-06 0773</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Eastern-Q&amp;A,0797</SECOND>
<HEAD>Some Questions And Answers About The Eastern Strike</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Eastern</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are some key questions in the 17-month labor dispute between
Eastern Airlines and its Machinists union.
   Q: Who is on strike?
   A: The 8,500 Eastern workers who belong to the International
Association of Machinists. They are about equally divided between
aircraft mechanics and ramp service workers, who fuel planes, handle
baggage and drive motorized equipment on airport runways.
   Q: How much do Machinists make?
   A: Mechanics at Eastern earn a top wage of $18.83 an hour. That
compares with $16 at non-union Continental Airlines, $18.78 at
American Airlines, $20.05 at United and Northwest Airlines, and
$20.10 at Delta Air Lines and USAir.
   Ramp service workers earn a top hourly wage of $15.60. Comparable
workers earn $15.51 an hour at American, $15.93 at USAir, $16.53 at
Northwest, $16.57 at United and $17.47 at Delta. Continental
contracts for the work.
   Q: What does each side want?
   A: Eastern is seeking $150 million in wage and benefit
concessions to help stem mounting losses at the airline. The
Machinists want $50 million in raises but last week offered to delay
increases for 15 months.
   Q: How has the dispute evolved?
   A: The Machinists have fought wage cuts since contract renewal
talks began in October 1987. Pilots and flight attendants a year
earlier reached concessionary agreements with the airline that
slashed pay 20 percent.
   The National Mediation Board intervened in the dispute in January
1988, but no progress was made during a year that included massive
layoffs and cost-cutting. The dispute reached loggerheads last month
after Eastern rejected binding arbitrtion and the mediation board
declared a 30-day cooling-off period before a strike.
   More than 97 percent of the Machinists on Feb. 15 authorized a
strike. President Bush refused to intervene to delay the strike.
Eastern's last contract offer would have cut pay but kept it 13
percent higher than workers who took the 20 percent reductions. It
was rejected Friday, and the strike began at 12:01 a.m. Saturday.
   Q: Could the Eastern strike affect other modes of transportation?
   A: Yes. The National Railway Labor Act permits secondary boycotts
in air and rail travel. If rail union workers honor pickets, traffic
on the nation's 12 commuter railroads and Amtrak could be severely
disrupted. Also, other airlines could be picketed and the 14
million-member AFL-CIO has asked its members to honor the Machinists
strike.
   However, the union decided Sunday to appeal a judge's order
barring such secondary boycotts in the New York metropolitan area
and said it would not picket any railroads Monday.
   Q: What is Eastern's financial condition?
   A: Eastern says it has lost more than $1 billion this decade and
is losing more than $1 million a day. It also has $2.5 billion in
debt. The airline was bought by Texas Air in February 1986 and since
then has undertaken a series of cutbacks in an attempt to restore
profitability. The carrier's workforce since the takeover has shrunk
to about 30,000 from 42,000. Eastern also has sold planes, cut
profitable routes, closed its Kansas City, Mo., hub and taken
smaller savings measures such as eliminating hot food on some
flights.
   Eastern has about $400 million in cash to help it meet its
financial obligations during the strike. In addition, the pending
sale of Eastern's Northeast shuttle to developer Donald Trump will
bring in about $365 million.
   Q: Why is Eastern ailing?
   A: Management blames union militancy and unrealistic demands and
says it trimmed back operations elsewhere and needs labor to make
sacrifices. Labor maintains Eastern is suffering because it didn't
react aggressively and competitively to airline deregulation in
1978. In 1983, workers made wage concessions in return for future
profits that never materialized and stock. Tey don't want further
concessions without proof Eastern is being managed with long-term
commitment to its financial fitness. The unions also claim Texas Air
Chairman Frank Lorenzo wants to strip the airline of assets or
dissolve it.
   Q: What are the strike's possible effects?
   A: The strike threatens to force the 60-year-old airline into
bankruptcy. To forestall its demise, Eastern could lay off striking
workers and sell other assets, such as planes, airport gates or
international routes, to raise cash. Texas Air could sell the
airline, and Trans World Airways owner Carl Icahn has been among
potential buyers who recently have expressed interest. A separate
settlement with pilots, who are honoring the strike, could allow the
airline to keep more planes airborne. And Bush could change his mind
and appoint an emergency panel that would force the Machinists to
return to work for 60 days.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
