<FIRST>r f PM-EasternAirlines-Glance     03-06 0201</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Eastern Airlines-Glance,0213</SECOND>
<HEAD>A Glance At Eastern Airlines</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Eastern</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a look at Eastern Airlines, whose Machinists were on
strike a third day today after negotiators failed to settle a
17-month-old contract dispute.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Owner: The 60-year-old airline has been owned by Texas Air Corp.,
headed by Chairman Frank Lorenzo, since 1986.
   Headquarters: Miami.
   Employees: 31,200, including 8,500 members of the Machinists
union, which includes mechanics, bag handlers and other ground
workers; 3,500 pilots; and 5,900 flight attendants.
   Size of fleet: 250 jets.
   Cities served: 118, with its major markets in South Florida, the
Caribbean, the East Coast and Latin America.
   Number of flights: 1,040 daily.
   Passengers: 100,000 average daily.
   Main strike issues: Eastern, which claims it lost $1 billion in
the last decade and is losing more than $1 million a day, sought
$150 million in wage concessions. The Machinists wanted $50 million
in raises. Each side said last-minute offers brought the sides
somewhat closer.
   Where negotiations stand: Talks under National Mediation Board
supervision in Washington were suspended at 12:01 a.m. Saturday.
President Bush refused to appoint an emergency panel that would have
delayed the strike 60 days. No new talks were scheduled.
</TEXT>
