<FIRST>r f BC-AtariGames-Nintendo     03-06 0251</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Atari Games-Nintendo,0259</SECOND>
<HEAD>Atari Games Granted Injunction Against Nintendo</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Atari Games was granted a preliminary
injunction barring Nintendo of America Inc. and its Japanese parent
company from suing retailers who carry Atari Games products for
alleged infringement of Nintendo's patent.
   The injunction granted in U.S. District Court Sunday prohibits
the video game giant from filing suit against retailers who sell
products by Atari Games' wholly owned subsidiary, Tengen, until the
dispute between the companies is formally resolved.
   The injunction also places similar restrictions on Atari Games
concerning its claims of patent infringement against Nintendo. The
Milpitas, Calif.-based Atari Games is a privately-held company and
not related to Atari Corp.
   Atari Games said it and Tengen asked for the injunction after
learning that several Tengen retailers, including some large
national toy chains, received letters from Nintendo's lawyers
insisting that they take all Tengen products off their shelves.
   The letters told the retailers that failure to do so would result
in Nintendo's taking legal action against the retailers for
third-party patent infringement, Atari Games said.
   The motion for the injunction was filed in connection with an
antitrust lawsuit Atari Games and Tengen filed against Nintendo. The
suit alleges monopoly, wrongful business interference and patent
infringement.
   In January, Nintendo sued Atari Games, accusing the company of
making and selling unauthorized video-game cartridges.
   Nintendo of America, based in Redmond, Wash., is a wholly owned
subsidiary of Nintendo Co. Ltd. of Kyoto, Japan, a major
manufacturer and marketer of video games.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
