<SECOND>PM-Wall Street 10am,0331</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market headed higher today in activity
dominated by communications and entertainment issues.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials rose 5.35 to 2,279.64 in
the first half hour of trading.
   Gainers outnumbered losers by more than 2 to 1 in nationwide
trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 640 up, 299
down and 465 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 23.65 million shares as of 10
a.m. on Wall Street.
   The big news of the session was the weekend merger agreement
between Time Inc. and Warner Communications.
   Analysts said the deal immediately touched off speculation that
other companies in the entertainment and publishing industries might
be candidates for mergers or takeovers.
   Warner stock was delayed in opening, while Time's shares dropped
1]. Analysts said Time's decline in part reflected disappointment
among traders who had been reckoning that the company might have
itself become a takeover candidate at a higher price.
   Elsewhere in the group, Columbia Pictures Entertainment gained }
to 18[ and American TV-Communications, traded in the
over-the-counter market, jumped 3\ to 42\.
   Brokers also said the overall market benefited from a monthly
report by a purchasing managers' group that suggested a slowing of
economic growth.
   That was interpreted as a favorable portent for the inflation
outlook and a possible slackening of upward pressure on interest
rates.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks rose
.46 to 164.36. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was up .70 at 326.92.
   On Friday the Dow Jones industrial average rose 8.58 to 2,274.29,
stretching its gain for the week to 28.75 points.
   Advancing issues outnumbered declines by about 3 to 2 on the
NYSE, with 850 up, 578 down and 501 unchanged.
   Big Board volume totaled 151.79 million shares, against 161.98
million in the previous session.
</TEXT>
