<FIRST>r f BC-BurleySeason     03-06 0228</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Burley Season,0237</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sales of 1988 Burley Tobacco Crop Strong</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LEXINGTON, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Buyers snapped up the 1988 burley crop
across the eight-state belt, with gross sales up almost 50 million
pounds over the previous year.
   Kentucky burley farmers led the way in both production and price
again this year, selling a total of 380.3 million pounds for an
average price of $1.6145 per pound.
   The lowest statewide average was registered in West Virginia,
where the Huntington market sold 2.8 million pounds for an average
of $1.5368 a pound.
   Gross sales for the 1988 crop throughout the area known as the
Burley Belt totaled 530.7 million pounds, compared with 484 million
pounds the year before.
   In addition, the average price per pound increased 4.7 cents a
pound, from $1.5634 in 1987-88 to $1.6104.
   ``It looks to me like the tobacco program, the tobacco situation,
is as good as it has been for a long time,'' said Danny McKinney,
executive secretary of the Burley Tobacco Growers Cooperative
Association.
   The 1988 crop was rescued from last summer's drought by rains
beginning in mid-July, and was far superior to the previous year's
crop. In 1987, a dry autumn curing season left much of the burley
brittle and undesirable.
   The burley selling season concluded last week. Burley is a
thin-leaved, light-colored tobacco, usually containing less nicotine
than the dark-colored varieties.
</TEXT>
