<FILEID>AP-NR-03-06-89 1114EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Scotus-AgeBias     03-06 0424</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Age Bias,0439</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Bans Tennessee Age Rule</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today refused to let
Tennessee officials impose a retirement age of 55 for officers who
enforce state wildlife laws.
   The court, without comment, let stand a ruling that the state
failed to show that physical fitness and a healthy heart are
necessary to do the job.
   The 6th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals last October struck down
the mandatory retirement age for officers of the Tennessee Wildlife
Resources Agency. The officers' duties include investigating
violations of hunting and fishing laws and arresting suspects.
   The appeals court said the age limit violates the federal Age
Discrimination in Employment Act aimed at protecting the rights of
older workers.
   Tennessee officials said wildlife officers also are responsible
for rescuing boaters and water skiers, work long hours in bad
weather and face life-threatening situations.
   The strenuous nature of the job is too demanding for those 55 and
older, the state officials said, because older officers are more
likely to be unfit and suffer from heart disease.
   But the 6th Circuit court said the state undermined its case by
not requiring physical fitness tests or heart examinations for any
officers, and by permitting some officers to stay on past age 55 due
to economic hardship or political pressure.
   Such waivers of the mandatory retirement age ``were granted
without any determinations as to job performance, physical ability
or physical fitness,'' the appeals court said. Therefore, it said,
Tennessee ``has not treated physical and coronary fitness as
reasonably necessary to the position of wildlife officer.''
   The Supreme Court in 1985 said the federal age-bias law requires
employers to show that employee qualifications _ such as physical
fitness _ are reasonably necessary to carry out the employer's work.
   The court also said in that ruling that an employer must show
that workers over a certain age lack such qualifications, or that it
is impractical to test the workers individually to determine whether
they are so qualified.
   Justice Department lawyers, representing the federal Equal
Employment Opportunity Commission in the case, said the Tennessee
dispute has limited application.
   There are only about a dozen similar cases in which states or
cities allegedly have violated the federal age discrimination law,
the government lawyers said.
   They also noted that Congress amended the law in 1986 to make it
easier for states and cities to impose mandatory retirement ages for
firefighters and law enforcement officers.
   The case is Tennessee Wildlife Resources Agency vs. EEOC, 88-1100.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890306-0255 </DOCNO>
