<FIRST>r f PM-Scotus-Asbestos     03-06 0280</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Asbestos,0293</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Won't Revive Johns-Manville Reimbursement Suits</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today refused to revive
lawsuits by Johns-Manville Corp. that sought government
reimbursement for more than $35 million paid or owed to shipyard
workers suffering from asbestos-related diseases and injuries.
   The court, without comment, let stand a ruling that threw the
suits by Johns-Manville out of a federal claims court.
   Thousands of workers exposed to products containing asbestos made
by Johns-Manville have sued the company.
   Many of the workers were employed at government-owned shipyards,
others at privately owned shipyards that built or repaired ships for
the government. Many of the claims date back to World War II.
   Johns-Manville sought reimbursement from the government,
contending that federal officials negligently approved use of
asbestos in shipbuilding. The company also accused the government of
failing to protect and warn workers about the hazards of exposure to
asbestos.
   The corporation filed suits in the U.S. Court of Claims, a court
here that handles various claims against the federal government.
   The claims court threw out the suits and a federal appeals court
upheld the dismissal.
   The appeals court said Johns-Manville is barred from seeking
reimbursement in the U.S. Court of Claims because the corporation
also sued the government in a federal district court in another
asbestos-related matter.
   The related case sought reimbursement for $45,000 Johns-Manville
paid a worker injured by asbestos exposure after 1963.
   The appeals court said the fact that the cases stem from asbestos
exposure some 20 years apart does not permit Johns-Manville to seek
recovery in the claims court while also seeking reimbursement in
federal district court for a similar claim.
   The case is Johns-Manville vs. U.S., 88-1052.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
