<DOCNO> AP890306-0259 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-06-89 1135EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Scotus-Electricity     03-06 0361</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Electricity,0377</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Rejects Rate Restructuring Appeal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today rejected an appeal by a
group of rural electric cooperatives challenging the authority of
Colorado officials to restructure rates charged to customers.
   The court, citing the lack of ``a properly presented federal
question,'' let stand a ruling supported by major oil companies that
buy power from the cooperative group.
   The Colorado Supreme Court ruled last July that the state's
public utility commission acted properly when it ordered the
Colorado-Ute Electric Association to redesign its rates.
   The association, comprised of 14 rural electric cooperatives, had
been charging what is known as a flat rate _ one not taking into
account the differences between fixed capital costs and variable
energy costs that fluctuate depending on fuel needs and costs.
   The utility commission ordered the cooperative association to
adopt a pricing setup that reflects separate charges for capital and
energy costs and varies according to seasonal demands of customers.
   The association's power needs generally are greater in winter.
   Supporting the change ordered by the state officials were Shell
Oil Co., Exxon, Atlantic Richfield and Union Carbide Corp.
   The state Supreme Court said the public utility commission had
adequate grounds to order the cooperative association to restructure
its rates because the old system resulted in ``an uneconomic
under-utilitization of capacity.''
   ``Rates charged should accurately reflect the utility's actual
cost of providing service, including both capital costs and
operating expenses,'' the state court said.
   In the appeal acted on today, lawyers for the cooperative
association also argued that its constitutional rights were violated
because the public utility commission based its findings in part on
a key computer analysis that the association was barred from
challenging adequately.
   The cooperatives said the they did not have an opportunity to
examine the computer program and supporting documents.
   The coops also said the state regulators interfered with the
power of the Rural Electrification Administration, a federal agency,
to regulate the cooperative utilities.
   Colorado-Ute Electric Association has 14 members. One member,
Empire Electric Association, opposed the appeal by the other 13.
   The case is Colorado-Ute vs. Colorado PUC, 88-977.
</TEXT>
