<FIRST>r f PM-Scotus-FederalWorkers     03-06 0391</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Federal Workers,0407</SECOND>
<HEAD>Federal Workers Don't Have Right to Sue in Federal Court in California
Union Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court said today federal workers do
not have a right to sue in federal court when they accuse the union
representing them of unfair treatment.
   The justices, voting 9-0, ruled that the only recourse for the
employees in such cases is to file an unfair labor practice charge
with the Federal Labor Relations Authority.
   Justice Byron R. White, writing for the court, said the federal
Civil Service Reform Act of 1978 does not ``provide a private cause
of action to enforce federal employees unions' duty of fair
representation.''
   The court ruled against Efthinios Karahalios, a Greek language
instructor at the Defense Language Institute in Monterey, Calif.
   Karahalios had worked for the institute for nearly 20 years when
in 1976 he was promoted to the higher-paying position of course
developer.
   Greek language instructor Simon Kuntelos objected to the
promotion and filed a grievance with the National Federation of
Federal Employees, which represents the institute's workers.
   Karahalios is not a member of the union, but it represents him in
collective bargaining. Kuntelos is a union member.
   The union decided to arbitrate Kuntelos' grievance without
telling Karahalios about it. After a hearing not attended by
Karahalios, an arbitrator cleared the way for Kuntelos, in effect,
to get Karahalios' job.
   Karahalios objected to his demotion, but the union refused to
arbitrate in his behalf.
   He filed an unfair labor practice complaint with the Federal
Labor Relations Authority. But the union and FLRA settled the case
when the union agreed to state it would not undertake similar acts
in the future.
   Karahalios then filed a federal court suit against the union.
   A federal judge said the union breached its duty to give
Karahalios fair representation and ordered the union to pay his
lawyer fees. The 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals overturned the
ruling and threw out the suit.
   In upholding the appeals court decision, White said today that
federal workers do not have the same relationship to unions as
privately employed workers.
   The court enforcement procedures for private
collective-bargaining contracts do not apply to federal employees
covered by the civil service act, White said.
   The case is Karahalios vs. National Federation of Federal
Employees, 87-636.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890306-0262 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-06-89 1229EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Scotus-Arbitration     03-06 0312</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Arbitration,0325</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Says Contract Dispute Between Stanford, Computer Firm Should
be Settled in State Court</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today said a contract dispute
between Stanford University and a computer firm should be settled in
state court, not in arbitration.
   The court's 6-2 decision is a victory for Stanford and a setback
for Volt Information Sciences Inc., which had asked the justices to
compel arbitration.
   Writing for the court, Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist said
California _ not federal _ law governs the case.
   The dispute developed when Volt submitted a claim for additional
compensation for extra work it said it performed installing a system
of electrical conduits connecting computer facilities on the
university campus in Palo Alto, Calif.
   The contract signed by Stanford and Volt contained a provision
that any dispute would be submitted to binding arbitration. The
contract also specified, in typical contractual language, that the
pact would be ``governed by the law of the place where the project
is located.''
   When Volt demanded that its claim for additional compensation be
arbitrated, Stanford sued in state court. Its suit alleged breach of
contract against Volt and two other companies with whom Stanford did
not have arbitration agreements.
   California courts ruled that the contract dispute should be
resolved in state court, and not in arbitration, because of a state
law allowing arbitration to be postponed pending lawsuits involving
third parties not bound by the arbitration.
   In seeking Supreme Court review, lawyers for Volt said the
company was being deprived of its arbitration rights under the
Federal Arbitration Act.
   But Rehnquist wrote today that such rights are not absolute, and
may be overridden by agreements to let state law govern.
   Justices William J. Brennan and Thurgood Marshall dissented, and
Justice Sandra Day O'Connor did not participate in the case.
   The case is Volt Informational Sciences vs. Stanford, 87-1318.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
