<FIRST>r f PM-Eastern-PanAmShuttle 1stLd-Writethru f0029 03-06 0410</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Eastern-Pan Am Shuttle, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0029,0417</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pan Am Shuttle Flies Double Duty</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: ADDS grafs 2-5 to update with Eastern operations; picks up 3rd
graf pvs `Pan Am ...; stands for sty slugged PM-Pan Am Shutle</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Pan Am shuttle doubled its normal rush hour
schedule from Washington, New York and Boston today in the wake of a
strike at its competitor, Eastern Airlines.
   Eastern, however, had crews available and was operating its
shuttle today, said spokesman Tim Cook. Four out of eight scheduled
Eastern shuttle flights left by 10 a.m. _ two to Boston and two to
Washington _ and the others were canceled because of snow, not the
strike, he said.
   Eastern also got off one non-shuttle flight _ to Miami _ from
LaGuardia Airport this morning, Cook said. Eastern was not operating
from the other New York-area airports, John F. Kennedy International
and Newark International.
   The shuttle crews were made up of a combination of union
employees who crossed picket lines and airline managers pressed into
duty, Cook said. He said he did not know how many passengers were on
the Eastern shuttle flights; the man who usually tracked such
figures was ``out throwing bags.''
   The Pan Am shuttle, which normally flies once an hour from each
city, was scheduled to fly every half hour today, except for the
slow hours between 10:30 a.m. and 2:30 p.m., said spokeswoman Pamela
Hanlon.
   Pan Am also planned to substitute 250-seat Airbus planes for
150-seat Boeing 727s on some flights between New York and Boston,
Hanlon said. Noise restrictions prohibited use of Airbuses on
flights to Washington.
   Pan Am carried twice its usual weekend load of 3,000 passengers
on the shuttle Saturday and Sunday, also with a doubled schedule. It
expected 10,000 passengers today, double the weekday norm, Hanlon
said.
   One shuttle passenger, Manhattan lawyer Gloria Hoyal, said she
went to LaGuardia Airport an hour and a half early today in
anticipation of delays that did not occur.
   ``And to add insult to injury, I was in Connecticut for the
weekend and I came back early to avoid the train strike,'' she said.
That problem also did not materialize: A federal judge blocked a
sympathy strike at the railroads.
   Today's first Pan Am shuttle flights arriving in New York, the
6:30 a.m. and 7 a.m. airplanes from Boston and Washington, were
delayed in New York for reasons unrelated to the strike: It was
snowing.
</TEXT>
