<FIRST>r f PM-Pillsbury     03-06 0206</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Pillsbury,0214</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pillsbury To Lay Off 550 in Minneapolis</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An ``overlap of functions'' since Pillsbury
Co. was acquired by Grand Metropolitan PLC has contributed to a
decision to lay off 550 of the company's 2,350 employees in its
Minneapolis headquarters, officials announced today.
   The layoffs, amounting to about 23.4 percent of Pillsbury's
Minneapolis staff, are to take place over the next several weeks,
Pillsbury said. The company will be left with about 1,800 employees
in Minneapolis and 100,000 worldwide.
   ``The decision to eliminate these positions was necessary to make
Pillsbury a stronger, more profitable company, prepared to compete
successfully in the world marketplace,'' Ian A. Martin, chairman and
chief executive officer of Pillsbury and head of Grand
Metropolitan's worldwide foods group, said in a statement.
   ``We have concluded that the Pillsbury Foods business has been
operating at a competitive disadvantage which must be corrected.
Additionally, the merger of Grand Met and Pillsbury created some
overlap of functions which will be eliminated,'' he said.
   After a three-month fight, Pillsbury in December agreed to accept
a sweetened $5.68 billion takeover offer from the Britain-based
Grand Metropolitan.
   Grand Met reported sales of more than $11 billion in fiscal 1988.
Pillsbury had sales of $6.2 billion.
</TEXT>
