<HEAD>Share Prices Rise</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: UPDATES with closing prices</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices on the London Stock Exchange rose
Monday but trading activity was thin as players began casting a
cautious eye toward next week's presentation of Britain's fiscal
1990 budget.
   ``Everybody's really not doing too much because of the budget
next week,'' one dealer said.
   Several factors combined to boost prices, including a
strengthening of the pound and a shortage of stock among market
makers. In addition, revised figures on British retail sales,
showing a greater slowing than had previously been reported,
encouraged hopes that inflation in Britain might be subsiding.
   At the close, the Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index
was up 13.6 points, or 0.7 percent, at 2,072.8. The index rose as
much as 17.8 points at midmorning but later moved down to show a
minimum gain of 6.4 points at midday.
   The Financial Times 30-share index was up 8.9 points at 1,706.4
at the close. The Financial Times 500-share index rose 8.04 points
to close at 1,180.53.
   Volume tapered off to 472.9 million shares from 632.7 million
shares on Friday.
