<FIRST>u f AM-Eastern-Bakes Bjt   03-06 0605</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Eastern-Bakes, Bjt,0623</SECOND>
<BYLINE>Eastern President's Turnaround Plans Blurred By Strike</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastern Airlines President Phil Bakes' birthday
horoscope on Monday promised: ``You'll be on more solid
emotional-financial ground in April.''
   But Bakes, 43, didn't get the present he hoped for _ a return of
Eastern's pilots to work. Without the pilots, who are supporting a
strike by the airline's Machinists union, the airline's chances of
survival by April are considered low.
   Bakes, in pleading Sunday for the pilots to cross the Machinists
picket lines, declined to speculate how long Eastern could survive
but said ``the economics are clear.'' He also referred to
speculation about consequences such as bankruptcy that could stem
from a prolonged strike at Eastern, which is $2.5 billion in debt
and says it is losing $1 million a day.
   Since becoming Eastern president 2{ years ago, Bakes has talked
of plans to pull the carrier out of its 10-year financial tailspin,
make it grow and make it profitable.
   But union leaders call Bakes one of ``the Continental crew,'' the
executive team that helped Texas Air Corp. Chairman Frank Lorenzo
turn Continental Airlines into a cheap-labor, predominantly
non-union company. Texas Air bought Eastern three years ago.
   Lorenzo and his ``union-buster'' image have galvanized Eastern
workers who believe his priorities are attacking organized labor and
milking cash out of Eastern.
   ``What we're seeing here is a remake of the Continental movie,''
pilots union spokesman Ron Cole said Sunday, after Bakes made a
televised plea for pilots to cross Machinists union picket lines.
``You've got the same players and Frank Lorenzo as the script writer
and director. But this time, the first act has been different.''
   In 1983, pilots crossed Machinists picket lines at Continental,
but both unions later had their contracts voided when the parent
Texas Air took Continental into bankruptcy reorganization.
   Bakes said he was ``somewhat surprised'' and had miscalculated
the extent to which Eastern pilots would support the Machinists.
Eastern's strike contingency plans had counted upon the pilots to
follow tradition and not support the Machinists, or for many of the
pilots to defy their union leadership and cross the picket line.
   The tall, lean long-distance runner with bright, piercing blue
eyes was born in Little Rock, Ark., and graduated with honors from
Loyola University of Chicago and Harvard Law School.
   Bakes served as an assistant prosecutor in the Watergate
investigation, was a counsel for Senate subcommittes and then the
Civil Aeronautics Board and then, after the airline industry was
deregulated, joined Texas Air as a vice president.
   In 1982, Bakes became executive vice president at Continental and
the carrier's president and chief operating officer in 1984. There,
he helped Continental return from bankruptcy reorganization as a
low-cost, aggressive airline.
   Bakes joined Eastern as its chief executive in October 1986 and
in January 1987 unveiled a plan to turn the airline around with a
six-point program that included marketing expansions and $490
million in labor cost cuts. He has promised Eastern, which has
shrunk steadily under Texas Air, will grow again if its labor costs
can be cut.
   Bakes said he inherited a tense labor situation that predated
Lorenzo, himself and chief Eastern negotiator Tom Matthews.
   ``Eastern Airlines is a company that's lost $1.5 billion since
deregulation. Frank Lorenzo as chairman of Texas Air...owner of
Eastern Airlines has only been involved for three years.
   ``What we've tried to do is say: `Give it a chance.' We will put
contractual guarantees that perhaps will get over the initial
distrust.
   ``With a successful company, when we're growing, buying
airplanes, refurbishing, trust will come,'' Bakes said.
</TEXT>
