<SECOND>PM-Eastern-Bakes, 2nd Ld - Writethru,0819</SECOND>
<HEAD>Airline President's Plan Not Working Because Pilots Aren't</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 11-13th grafs, bgng `This morning...', with 4 grafs to
UPDATE with federal lawsuit filed. Picks up 14th graf, `The tall...'. Also
moved on general news wires.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Eastern, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Since coming to Eastern Airlines as president 2{
years ago, Phil Bakes has insisted he has firm plans to pull the
carrier out of its 10-year financial tailspin.
   The crippling strike that continued in its third day today
indicates his employees don't really believe him.
   Instead, union leaders call Bakes one of ``the Continental
crew,'' the executive team that helped Texas Air Corp. Chairman
Frank Lorenzo turn Continental Airlines into a cheap-labor,
predominantly nonunion company.
   It's Lorenzo and his ``union-buster'' image that has galvanized
Eastern's workers, who believe his priorites are attacking organized
labor and milking cash out of Eastern.
   ``By all the actions they've already taken, it's clear where he's
taking the airline,'' pilots' union spokesman Ron Cole said Sunday,
after Bakes made a nationally televised plea for pilots to cross
Machinists union picket lines and return to work. ``He (Bakes) is
trying to deflect the issue away from Frank Lorenzo.
   ``What we're seeing here is a remake of the Continental movie.
You've got the same players and Frank Lorenzo as the script writer
and director,'' Cole said. ``But this time, the first act has been
different.''
   Cole referred to 1983 when pilots crossed Machinists picket lines
at Continental, only to join the Machinists in having their
contracts voided when the parent Texas Air took the carrier into
bankruptcy reorganization.
   Bakes admitted Sunday he was ``somewhat surprised'' and had
miscalculated the extent to which pilots would support the
Machinists. Eastern's contingency plans had counted on pilots
crossing the picket lines.
   ``If the pilots had come to work Friday night, I'd be at the
Miami Grand Prix this afternoon and you'd all be home with your
families,'' Bakes told reporters.
   This morning, Bakes accused the pilots of misleading the airline,
and later in the day, the airline dropped the other shoe by filing
suit against the pilots, saying the work stoppage was illegal.
   ``The pilots have been saying over the last year that if the
Machinists did strike, they would come to work. That's why we were
so surprised,'' Bakes said today on ``CBS This Morning.''
   ``This is the pilots strike that really shouldn't have been,''
added Bakes.
   Eastern filed the request for a restraining order to halt the
strike with a federal judge in Miami, who did not immediately
schedule a hearing.
   The tall, lean long-distance runner with bright, piercing blue
eyes turned 43 today. A newspaper horoscope for those with birthdays
today promises: ``You'll be on more solid emotional-financial ground
in April.''
   However, Bakes is unlikely to reach that ground with Eastern if
the strike doesn't end soon.
   He declined to speculate on how long Eastern could stay alive,
but said ``the economics are clear.'' He referred to speculation
about the consequences of a prolonged strike, which include
bankruptcy. Bakes said Sunday the company is keeping up its payments
on nearly $2.5 billion in debts.
   Philip J. Bakes, a Little Rock, Ark., native, graduated with
honors from Loyola University of Chicago and Harvard Law School,
served as an assistant prosecutor in the Watergate investigation,
was a counsel for Senate subcommittees and then the Civil
Aeronautics Board.
   After the airline industry was deregulated, he joined Texas Air
as a vice president. In 1982, he became executive vice president at
Continental and the carrier's president and chief operating officer
in 1984. There, he helped Continental return from bankruptcy
reorganization with a low-cost, aggressive airline.
   Bakes joined Eastern as its chief executive in October 1986.
Three months later, he unveiled a plan to turn the airline around
with a program that included marketing expansions and cutting labor
costs overall by $490 million, or about 30 percent. He has promised
Eastern, which has shrunk steadily under Texas Air, will be rebuilt
to grow if its labor costs can be cut.
   Bakes agreed that trust is an issue.
   ``We would hope that over time there will be much more trust
among all the Eastern people,'' he said, adding that he inherited a
tense labor situation that predated ``Frank Lorenzo, Phil Bakes and
(chief negotiator) Tom Matthews.
   ``Eastern Airlines is a company that's lost $1.5 billion since
deregulation. Frank Lorenzo as chairman of Texas Air ... owner of
Eastern Airlines has only been involved for three years.
   ``What we've tried to do is say: `Give it a chance.' We will put
contractual guarantees that perhaps will get over the initial
distrust.
   ``With a successful company, when we're growing, buying
airplanes, refurbishing, trust will come,'' Bakes said.
