<FILEID>AP-NR-03-06-89 2047EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-PurchasingManagers     03-06 0563</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Purchasing Managers,0591</SECOND>
<HEAD>Purchasing Managers Say Economy Grew in February But At Slower Rate</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's economy grew in February at the
slowest rate in two years, according to a survey of purchasing
executives.
   The National Association of Purchasing Management, which tracks
the economy through its monthly survey of its members, said in a
report for release Monday that its Purchasing Managers Index fell
slightly last month, to 53.0 from 53.2. The February level was the
lowest for the index since February 1987, when it was 52.6 percent.
   Despite the drop, the index still pointed to economic growth. A
reading above 50 generally indicates the economy is expanding, while
below 50 it is contracting. The index has exceeded 50 for 31
consecutive months.
   ``The economy appears to have entered a period of slower and more
moderate growth than the robust pace of last year,'' said Robert J.
Bretz, association chairman and director of materials management at
Pitney Bowes Inc.
   ``This, coupled with a decreased employment and a declining
inflation trend, could be signalling a more subdued and healthier
economy for this stage of the economic recovery.''
   The survey found that new orders continued to increase in
February from the previous month, which was at its lowest level
since October 1986.
   Thirty-two percent of the purchasing managers surveyed said new
orders were better last month, while 53 percent said they were the
same and 15 percent said they were worse. In January, 27 percent
said they were better, while 61 percent said they were the same and
12 percent said they were worse.
   The rate of production growth slowed to an index level of 53.7
percent from 56.2 percent in January. The February level was its
lowest since 53.0 percent in December 1986.
   Vendor deliveries continued to grow, but their change came at a
slower pace. Slow vendor deliveries are a bullish economic signal;
they indicate a business is getting new orders faster than it can
fill them.
   Sixteen percent of the respondents said deliveries were slower,
while 74 percent said they were the same and 10 percent said they
were faster. In January, 15 percent reported slower deliveries,
while 79 percent said they were the same and 6 percent said they
were faster.
   Inventories declined for the second consecutive month.
   Eighteen percent of the purchasing managers said inventories were
higher, 67 percent said they were the same and 15 percent said they
were lower. That compared with 17 percent who said they were higher,
59 percent who said they lower in January.
   Thirty-eight percent of the respondents said prices were higher,
while 57 percent said they were the same and 5 percent said they
were lower. In January, 51 percent reported higher prices, while 46
percent said they were the same and 3 percent said they lower.
   Employment declined in February after eight consecutive months of
increasing, according to the survey.
   Thirteen percent of the purchasing managers said employment was
up at their companies, 72 percent said it was the same and 15
percent said it was down. The previous month, 10 percent reported
higher employment, 80 percent said it was the same and 10 percent
said it fell.
   The National Association of Purchasing Management is an education
and research organization of purchasing executives. It polls
purchasing managers in more than 250 industrial firms for its
economic survey.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890306-0276 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-06-89 2049EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-ElectronicsTrade     03-06 0322</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Electronics Trade,0332</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Electronics World Trade Deficit Decreased 25 Percent in 1988</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTA CLARA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. electronics trade deficit
with the world shrank about 25 percent in 1988 to $9.6 billion but
the deficit with Japan grew 2 percent, the American Electronics
Association reported Monday.
   U.S. exports increased more than 28 percent to $58 billion from
$45.2 billion in 1987, while imports increased 17 percent to $67.6
billion from $58 billion.
   U.S. electronics companies' exports to Japan shot up, but a small
percentage increase in imports was still enough to cause the deficit
to swell.
   The electronics trade deficit with Japan grew to $20.5 billion
from $20.1 billion. U.S. exports to Japan grew more than 43 percent,
to $6.3 billion in 1988 from $4.4 billion in 1987. Imports from
Japan increased 9.4 percent to $26.8 billion.
   ``This significant reduction in our trade deficit with the world
is the result of a surge in U.S. electronics exports,'' said J.
Richard Iverson, AEA president and chief executive officer.
   ``Unfortunately, the same progress wasn't achieved with our trade
problems with Japan,'' he added. ``The Japanese electronics industry
must realize that trade is a two-way street and that the open
markets in the United States must be matched by the same in Japan.''
   The fourth-quarter U.S. electronics trade deficit with the world
decreased by almost 20 percent to $3.0 billion from $3.7 billion in
1987. Exports rose to $15.7 billion from $12.7 billion and imports
to $18.6 billion from $16.4 billion.
   The U.S. electronics trade deficit with Japan for electronics
products and services slowed its rate of growth in the 1988 fourth
quarter to 1.5 percent to $5.6 billion from $5.5 billion. U.S.
exports to Japan improved to $1.8 billion in the 1988 quarter from
$1.3 billion in 1987 and imports from Japan rose to $7.4 billion
from $6.9 billion.
   The AEA represents more than 3,500 companies in the United States.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
