<FIRST>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   03-06 0208</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0217</SECOND>
<HEAD>Most Crop Futures Gain On Weather, Technicals</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices closed mostly
higher Monday on the Chicago Board of Trade with the wheat market
posting solid gains amid weather concerns and new export activity.
   The key winter-wheat states of Kansas, Oklahoma, Texas and
Nebraska received far less precipitation over the weekend than many
traders had expected, spurring brisk buying Monday of new-crop wheat
futures _ contracts for delivery in July or later.
   Wheat for near-term delivery was supported by reports that China
was seeking to buy 400,000 metric tons of U.S. wheat at subsidized
prices for April or May delivery.
   The soybean complex was boosted by heavy speculative buying of
soybean meal futures, although analysts could cite no new
supply-and-demand developments to account for the late surge.
   Corn futures finished narrowly mixed.
   At the close, wheat was 2\ cents to 7{ cents higher with the
contract for delivery in March at $4.35 a bushel; corn was 2 cents
lower to 1} cents higher with March at $2.80 a bushel; oats were 2{
cents to 4{ cents higher with March at $2.10 a bushel; soybeans were
3\ cents to 8{ cents higher with March at $7.71 a bushel.
</TEXT>
