<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices rose today in activity dominated by
buying of communications and entertainment issues.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials climbed 10.17 points to
2,284.46 by 3 p.m. on Wall Street.
   Gainers outnumbered losers by about 8 to 5 in nationwide trading
of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 855 up, 530 down and
529 unchanged.
   The big news of the session was the weekend merger agreement
between Time Inc. and Warner Communications.
   Analysts said the deal immediately touched off speculation that
other companies in the entertainment and publishing industries might
be candidates for mergers or takeovers.
   Warner stock led the active list and jumped 2} to 48|, while
Time's shares dropped 1} to 107]. Analysts said Time's decline in
part reflected disappointment among traders who had been reckoning
that the company might have itself become a takeover candidate at a
higher price.
   Chris-Craft Industries, which owns a 17 percent interest in
Warner, gained 3| to 33].
   Elsewhere in the group, Gulf &amp; Western rose 2 to 45]; MCA 1} to
52|, and Columbia Pictures Entertainment 1 to 18].
   Brokers also said the overall market benefited from a monthly
report by a purchasing managers' group that suggested a slowing of
economic growth.
   That was interpreted as a favorable portent for the inflation
outlook and a possible slackening of upward pressure on interest
rates.
   Ohio Mattress rose 2~ to 24|. The company agreed to a
$25.50-a-share buyout by the investment firm of Gibbons, Green, Van
Amerongen.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks rose
.82 to 164.72. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was up .99 at 327.21.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 126.16 million shares with an
hour to go.
