<FILEID>AP-NR-03-06-89 2059EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Honda-Steel     03-06 0230</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Honda-Steel,0238</SECOND>
<HEAD>Three U.S. Companies to Supply Steel Bar Products to Honda</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MARYSVILLE, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Honda of America Manufacturing Inc.
announced Monday it will purchase specialty bar steel products from
three U.S. steelmakers for use in engine, drive-train and suspension
components.
   The purchase of the domestic steel bar products, as well as
purchases from other U.S. sources, will bring domestic content for
automobiles produced by Honda of America to 75 percent by 1991, the
Japanese automaker said. Domestic content of such vehicles is
currently 62 percent.
   Honda said a total of five steel bar materials will be supplied
by LTV Steel, Copperweld Steel and Timken Co., with up to 1,400
metric tons per month to be purchased by the end of 1990. The steel
will be supplied by Ohio mills: LTV, from Massillon; Copperweld,
from Warren; and Timken, from Canton.
   Yoichi Harada, a spokesman for Honda of America, said the company
currently purchases assembled engine, drive-train and suspension
components from Japan. Under the new arrangement, the assembly will
be done with domestic steel bar products at Honda's engine plant in
Anna, Ohio.
   All of the body stampings currently produced at Honda's
Marysville auto plant are manufactured from domestic steel supplied
by Inland Steel, Bethlehem Steel and Armco.
   The auto plant at Marysville began production in November 1982,
and the engine plant at Anna began production in July 1985.
</TEXT>
