<FILEID>AP-NR-03-06-89 2105EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-PlasticWrap     03-06 0374</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Plastic Wrap,0388</SECOND>
<HEAD>Reynolds Introducing Colored Plastic Wrap</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HILARY APPELMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RICHMOND, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Colored plastic wrap introduced Monday by
Reynolds Metals Co. will ``make the mundane task of wrapping
leftovers fun,'' the company says.
   Skeptical?
   Reynolds says consumers responded with even more enthusiasm than
expected when the company tried out the red, green, blue and yellow
plastic wrap in focus groups and simulated test markets.
   ``The addition of color gives an emotional appeal to plastic
wrap, which in its clear form is considered purely a functional
product,'' said Jane D. Nims of Reynolds' consumer products
division. ``Adding color to plastic wrap makes a useful product
exciting.''
   The new product, called ``Crystal Color Plastic Wrap,'' is
intended to liven up the kitchen . . . make things more
interesting,'' said spokeswoman Anne F. Waring.
   Marabel Morgan, author of ``The Total Woman'' and proponent of
the idea that women spice up their marriages by greeting their
husbands at the door wearing only plastic wrap, says the colored
wrap ``is a great idea. It would really add a lot of zip,'' she said
Sunday in a telephone interview from her home in Miami.
   The Richmond-based company will promote use of the colored wrap
in crafts as well as food storage, Ms. Waring said. Reynolds will
have several special promotions around the holidays for the product,
which is manufactured at its plant in Grottoes, Va.
   The colored wrap is unlikely to have a significant impact on the
company's sales, Reynolds analysts said.
   ``It's a tempest in a teapot,'' said William G. Siedenburg of
Smith Barney, Harris Upham &amp; Co. in New York. ``Reynolds is
principally and always will be an aluminum producer.
   ``Does it matter what color you use to wrap the meat you didn't
finish at dinner?'' he added.
   But Michael Via of Anderson &amp; Strudwick Inc. in Richmond said the
innovation is part of the company's movement away from aluminum,
which has a cyclical market, toward plastic products and consumer
packaging, which have higher profit margins.
   In 1988, Reynolds reported a record net income of $482 million,
or $8.35 per share, on revenues of $5.6 billion.
   Ms. Waring said the consumer products division accounts for 10
percent of Reynolds' sales.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
