<FIRST>r f AM-ConstructionContracts     03-06 0254</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Construction Contracts,0266</SECOND>
<HEAD>Orders For New Construction Off 5 Percent in January</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release 6:30 p.m. EST.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Contracts for new construction fell 5 percent in
January from the high level of December, when public works projects
had surged, F.W. Dodge Group said Monday.
   F.W. Dodge, a division of McGraw-Hill Information Services Co.,
said fluctuations in contracting for public works projects have been
a big influence on the building sector for several months.
   Commercial and industrial construction showed renewed strength in
January while residential building slowed.
   Contracting for public works and utilities in January was 20
percent lower than December's unusually strong level. The January
decline brought the annual pace of contracting in this sector to a
more normal level, F.W. Dodge said.
   The value of all newly started construction in January declined
to an annual rate of $243.6 billion from December's annual rate of
$256.2 billion.
   George A. Christie, F. W. Dodge's vice president and chief
economist, said the construction sector entered 1989 on a weak note
and could deteriorate as the year goes on if the Federal Reserve
Board becomes increasingly aggressive in its battle against
inflation.
   The building business is very sensitive to interest rate
movements and interest charges have been rising lately as the
central bank pursues a tight-money policy.
   ``One month hardly sets a trend, but if the Federal Reserve
stands firm in its determination to tighten credit further as
inflationary pressures continue to mount, the coming months could
make January look good,'' Christie said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
