<FIRST>u f AM-ChannelOne-Mich     03-06 0397</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Channel One-Mich,0410</SECOND>
<HEAD>Controversial News Show Gets High Marks At Detroit School</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: With AM-Channel One, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JUSTIN BURKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   To Jennifer Dickson, commercial television is as
welcome in the classroom as it is in the living room.
   ``The people against the commercials should wake up and smell the
coffee,'' the 12th-grader at Detroit's Mumford High School said
Monday after viewing the first edition of Whittle Communications'
Channel One news program. ``This is the 1980s and commercials are a
way of life.
   ``They're just trying to create the image of `Leave It To Beaver'
and it's just not that way anymore,'' Dickson said of the show's
critics.
   Students and administrators at Mumford gave high marks to Channel
One, a 12-minute daily program being tested in six schools around
the country by Whittle, a Knoxville, Tenn.,-based media company.
   The launch of Channel One came amid growing criticism by some
children's advocates and educators, including the National
Parent-Teachers Association, of the inclusion of 30-second
television ads.
   Commercials for Snickers candy bars, Head and Shoulders shampoo,
Levi's 501 jeans and the Partnership for a Drug-Free America were in
the initial show.
   ``I enjoyed the program,'' said LaMesa Williams, a 12th-grader.
``Not a lot of kids go home and watch the news on television, so
it's good that they have the opportunity to see it at school.''
   About 20 students viewed the premier show with members of the
media in the high school's library on Monday. The program contained
features on students' reactions to the continuing death threats
against Salman Rushdie, author of the book ``The Satanic Verses;''
life for a teen-ager in the Soviet Union; and the controversy
involving the launch of Channel One.
   ``The story about the Soviet Union was especially interesting
because I got to see how teen-agers over there live, what they wear,
what music they listen to,'' 12th-grader Tammy Warren said.
   Students appeared to watch the program closely, with some taking
notes, while others at times were distracted by the lights of
television cameras from local stations covering the program's first
showing.
   Detroit Schools Superintendent Arthur Jefferson, on hand for the
debut of Channel One, said the program would be monitored carefully.
   ``We take very seriously the responsibility of educating young
people,'' Jefferson said. ``We have to be very careful about the
intrusion of commercialism upon a captive audience.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
