<FILEID>AP-NR-03-06-89 1703EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-OilPrices     03-06 0306</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Prices,0318</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oil Prices Rise</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Energy futures prices began the week slightly
higher Monday, aided by the Soviet Union's reaffirmation of oil
production cuts and a report showing a drop in OPEC output last
month.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the April contract for West
Texas Intermediate, the benchmark U.S. crude, settled 11 cents
higher at $18.67 a barrel, after falling 16 cents in volatile
trading Friday.
   The April contract had risen as high as $18.86 a barrel Monday,
but declined on profit-taking, analysts said.
   Among refined petroleum products traded on the exchange, the
April contract for wholesale home heating oil settled 0.63 cent
higher at 51.43 cents a gallon, after falling 1.07 cents Friday.
   April unleaded gasoline, which declined 0.68 cent the previous
session, settled at 51.59 cents, up 0.60 cent.
   ``The confirmation of the Soviet cutback on production was the
principal issue in the market,'' said William Byers, an energy
analyst with Bear, Stearns &amp; Co.
   Top Soviet energy officials said Monday that the Soviet Union is
prepared to cooperate closely with OPEC to stabilize world oil
markets. The statements follow a Tass announcement Friday that the
Soviets will cut oil exports by about 5 percent in the first six
months of 1989, as part of an effort by non-OPEC producers to shore
up world oil prices.
   Byers said the oil market also got a boost Monday by a report
shoing daily oil production among the Organization of Petroleum
Exporting Countries declined to 19.4 million from 20.2 million
barrels.
   The 13-nation cartel agreed in November to slash output starting
Jan. 1, to try to boost prices to $18 a barrel. Since then, analysts
say, the oil nations have cut crude flow to meet their daily quota
of 18.5 million in the first six months of the year.
</TEXT>
