<DOCNO> AP890306-0290 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-06-89 1708EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-American-Planes     03-06 0456</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-American-Planes,0471</SECOND>
<HEAD>American Plans Up to $3.5 Billion Purchase of Smaller Planes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American Airlines is about to follow up
last month's order for up to $7.5 billion worth of McDonnell Douglas
jets with the purchase of up to $3.5 billion more in smaller
commuter airplanes from undisclosed manufacturers, a newspaper
reported Monday.
   An American spokesman, though, said the company has yet to make
any decisions about commuter plane purchases.
   The small commuter jets, which would seat about 100 and together
cost up to $2 billion, would fly under the American Airlines name,
the Fort Worth Star-Telegram reported.
   Turboprop planes that seat between 35 and 50 passengers and
together cost up to $1.5 billion would be flown by American's
commuter airline subsidiaries that operate collectively as American
Eagle, the newspaper said.
   Bob Baker, American's senior vice president for operations, told
the newspaper the airline expects to order both types of aircraft
within the next 30 to 45 days.
   ``We'd like them yesterday,'' Baker said. ``We are units short.
We'd love to have 50 more airplanes Monday morning, simply because
we have the chance to use them productively now. And there are some
closing windows of opportunity.''
   The story did not say what company might supply the new planes.
   Baker was attending a daylong meeting Monday and was unavailable
for comment, his secretary told The Associated Press.
   Calls to Baker were referred to Al Becker, a corporate
communications spokesman for American. Becker said reports about
plans for airplane purchases are ``speculative'' and said although
American is reviewing its needs for new commuter airplanes,
decisions about purchases have yet to be made.
   With 475 airplanes, American already operates the biggest
commercial fleet in the Western world. Last month, American ordered
eight MD-11s with the option to buy another 42. MD-11s are
three-engine, wide-body jets that can carry 405 passengers
long-range and are designed to replace the older DC-10. American
also took options on 100 MD-80s, smaller twin-jet planes designed to
replace the Boeing 727.
   American's commuter airline subsidiaries operate 128 commuter
planes, and six are on order. That does not include the 58 planes
operated by Metro Airlines Inc. of Grapevine, an independent company
that flies as the American Eagle franchisee at American's
Dallas-Fort Worth Airport hub, and Executive Air, the American Eagle
operator at American's hub at San Juan, Puerto Rico.
   Baker said American wants to use some 100-seat jets to replace
its 39 Boeing 727-100s, which seat 118 and are the oldest planes in
the fleet. The oldest 727-100 is nearly 25 years old.
   American also sees the 100-seat jet as a vehicle for expansion
into small-city markets. Baker said American has identified 80 to
100 such markets around the country.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
