<FILEID>AP-NR-03-06-89 2308EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-DuPont-Ozone     03-06 0491</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Du Pont-Ozone,0505</SECOND>
<HEAD>RETRANSMITTING for all needing.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Du Pont Announces Long-Term Alternatives To CFC Cleaning Agent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Du Pont Co. says it has developed two products
that could become long-term replacements for a chemical commonly
used as a cleaning agent that is suspected of damaging the Earth's
ozone layer.
   The products are intended as substitutes for CFC-113, a
chlorofluorocarbon used by the electronics and other industries
requiring high standards of cleanliness in such equipment as wiring
assemblies.
   Cleaning agents account for about 20 percent of the world market
for CFCs, which also are used in refrigeration, aerosols, and
blowing agents, including for insulation and cushioning.
   Du Pont, which accounts for about half of the U.S. production of
CFCs and is the world's largest producer, plans to stop making the
chemicals, and has been researching possible alternative products.
   With the latest two products, Du Pont has developed candidates to
replace CFCs in each of the four major areas in which the chemicals
are used, said Archie W. Dunham, a Du Pont group vice president. He
made the announcement Sunday at an international conference on ozone
protection in London and a summary of his remarks was released in
the United States.
   The 120-nation conference has focused attention on the chemical
compounds that scientists say are destroying the ozone shield that
protects the Earth from the sun's cancer-causing ultraviolet rays.
   The compounds are blamed for creating an ozone hole roughly the
size of the continental United States over the Antarctic every
winter. A smaller hole has also been spotted over the Arctic.
   One of Du Pont's long-term cleaning agent substitutes is a
fluorocarbon-based blend that has about 90 percent less ozone
depletion potential. Laboratory tests show it might be a superior
cleaning agent in removing residue from wiring assemblies in the
electronics industry.
   The other candidate contains a mixture of solvents and
surface-active agents and it is designed to remove residue in a
process using a final water rinse. It has no potential to deplete
the ozone layer.
   Du Pont has applied for patents on both blends and limited
quantities of each are available for evaluation.
   The company said that depending on market reaction and further
testing, the fluorocarbon-based product could be ready for
commercial use in several years and the other product could be ready
by the end of this year.
   Du Pont plans to introduce a series of product alternatives to
CFCs over a three-year to five-year period beginning in 1990. The
company expects to phase CFCs out of several major market segments
in the early to mid-1990s, but complete phaseout may take until the
turn of the century.
   The company said it has spent or authorized nearly $100 million
on developing substitutes for CFCs and plans to spend $45 million
more this year. An investment of more than $1 billion would be
needed to completely restructure its U.S. CFC business to produce
alternative products, Du Pont said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
