<FIRST>u f AM-Eastern-Continental     03-06 0596</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Eastern-Continental,0616</SECOND>
<HEAD>Continental Employees Unsympathetic to Strikers at Sister Airline</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Eastern, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF AWALT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Continental Airlines employees showed little
sympathy Monday for the walkout at Eastern, saying many of them earn
less money than the strikers at the troubled sister carrier.
   Pilots for Continental, itself the target of wage cuts and job
actions during a tumultuous 1983 reorganization under Texas Air
Corp. Chairman Frank Lorenzo, predict their Eastern counterparts
will suffer for honoring picket lines. Texas Air owns both airlines.
   ``My personal opinion is that the pilots _ or for that matter
anyone else _ should not have gone out on strike. I think they're
going to lose their jobs and they're probably going to lose the
airline,'' said one pilot, who spoke on the condition of anonymity.
   ``I think Frank Lorenzo's going to shut that thing (Eastern) down
and either sell parts of it or bankrupt it,'' he said, adding that
Eastern pilots he talked to in advance of the strike had hoped to
keep flying. ``I don't see how they can continue.''
   Of more than a dozen Continental employees interviewed, none
expressed misgivings about aiding Eastern management by accepting
additional passengers bumped from the sister carrier's flights.
   However, some Continental laborers suggested their comments were
restricted by management.
   ``It's going to be tough to try to find anyone to talk to,'' said
one worker. ``They're really cracking down on us.''
   With only four daily Eastern flights through Houston airports,
Continental workers say they have seen only a slight rise in
passengers and shipping since the strike began. Continental is based
in Houston and Eastern is in Miami.
   Despite increased security and fears that striking Eastern
workers may target Continental because of its relationship to Texas
Air, there have been no reported attempts to block Continental's
Houston operations, union and airline officials said.
   Many of the pilots, flight attendants and other workers at
Houston's Intercontinental Airport, the airline's main hub, said
they considered the labor strife unrelated to their operations, and
uncalled for when compared with salaries at Continental or in other
industries.
   Nearly all of them, however, said they hoped to see an end to the
strike and the ultimate survival of Eastern.
   ``What Lorenzo did is look at their salaries and then compare
them to salaries in the marketplace _ what those people would make
working somewhere else,'' said another Continental pilot, who asked
not to be named.
   ``Let's face it _ throwing a bag is throwing a bag no matter
where you do it,'' he said. ``This is a supply and demand business
and they're in business to make a profit. They have to answer to
their shareholders.''
   The sentiments apparently spread through the ranks at Continental
on Monday, although many employees refused to be interviewed.
   ``The problem isn't really the mechanics, it's the baggage
handlers,'' said one worker. ``They outnumber the mechanics and
they're the ones who pushed this thing, and they're making a lot of
money for what they're doing.''
   He said that his wife, a nurse, makes about $6 per hour less than
an Eastern baggage attendant who may have no advanced education.
   Teresa White, who was laid off after Continental filed for
bankruptcy protection in 1983 but later was rehired and rose to a
supervisory position, said union members at Eastern apparently
missed a valuable history lesson.
   ``I think they should have foreseen what was taking place and
know what he (Lorenzo) would do _ get rid of their jobs,'' she said
of the possible response to the strike.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
