<FIRST>u f AM-CommoditiesRdp     03-06 0667</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodities Rdp,0693</SECOND>
<HEAD>Platinum Rallies On Japanese Buying, Technical Strength</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Platinum futures prices gained strongly Monday after a modest
rally led by Japanese jewelry makers pushed prices through key
resistance levels, triggering widespread buying.
   On other markets, gold and silver futures also advanced; copper
futures declined; energy futures gained; grains and soybeans were
mostly higher; and livestock and meat futures were mixed.
   Platinum settled $7.40 to $8.30 higher on the New York Mercantile
Exchange with the contract for delivery in April at $546.70 a troy
ounce.
   Japanese commercial traders, who recently had been absent from
the platinum market, began buying futures early in the session,
which encouraged others to enter the market.
   The rally slowly gathered steam, then accelerated rapidly in
afternoon trading after the April contract's price surpassed $544 a
troy ounce, analysts said.
   ``We hit buy stops right over that, ran up to $548, then pulled
back,'' said Bette Raptopoulos, a metals-market analyst with
Prudential-Bache Securities Inc. in New York.
   Observers noted an easing of concern about the possibility that a
strike in the base-metals section of South Africa's Rustenburg
metals complex would spread to the platinum refinery, which
processes about half of the world's platinum.
   ``That's definitely a contributing factor but it's not as
prominent as it was last week,'' said James Steel, an analyst with
Refco Inc. in New York.
   Trading volume in precious metals futures was thin, both on the
New York Merc and on New York's Commodity Exchange, where gold and
silver futures are traded.
   Gold settled $1.10 to $1.20 higher with April at $390.50 a troy
ounce; silver was 0.6 cent to 0.8 cent higher with March at $5.809 a
troy ounce.
   Copper futures retreated on the Commodity Exchange after five
straight days of gains.
   The decline was linked to the London Metal Exchange's report of a
relatively large, 4,500-ton increase last week in its warehouse
stocks of copper, and to a 337-ton increase over the weekend in
warehouse stocks registered with the Commodity Exchange.
   Copper settled 1.4 cents to 3.1 cents lower with May at $1.42 a
pound.
   Oil futures climbed moderately higher on the New York Merc
following an International Energy Agency report showing a reduction
in OPEC crude-oil output last month.
   Meanwhile, Soviet energy officials said Monday they were willing
to extend a previously announced 5 percent cutback in crude-oil
production beyond the original 6-month deadline in a bid to help
boost prices.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 11 cents to 21 cents
higher with April at $18.67 a barrel; heating oil was .32 cent to
.63 cent higher with April at 51.43 cents a gallon; unleaded
gasoline was .06 cent to .87 cent higher with April at 51.59 cents a
gallon.
   Wheat futures made solid gains on the Chicago Board of Trade
following a weekend of drier-than-expected weather in the Great
Plains, the heart of the winter-wheat country.
   Wheat also was supported by reports that China was seeking to buy
400,000 metric tons of U.S. wheat at subsidized prices.
   Wheat settled 2\ cents to 7{ cents higher with the contract for
delivery in March at $4.35 a bushel; corn was 2 cents lower to 1{
cents higher with March at $2.79} a bushel; oats were 2{ cents to 4\
cents higher with March at $2.09} a bushel; soybeans were 2} cents
to 8{ cents higher with March at $7.70{ a bushel.
   Livestock futures settled mixed in lackluster trading on the
Chicago Mercantile Exchange. Frozen pork bellies finished sharply
higher, erasing about half the losses sustained in last Friday's
steep sell-off.
   Live cattle were .15 cent lower to .12 cent higher with April at
77.80 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .15 cent to .43 cent lower
with March at 82.10 cents a pound; live hogs were .28 cent lower to
.52 cent higher with April at 43.87 cents a pound; frozen pork
bellies were 1.85 cent lower to 1.38 cent higher with March at 38.95
cents a pound.
</TEXT>
