<FIRST>r f AM-LuxuryInflation     03-06 0268</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Luxury Inflation,0274</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cost of Living Very Well up 8.7 Percent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The cost of living outrageously well leapt 8.7
percent in 1988, and Petrossian beluga caviar led the way with an
increase of more than 41 percent, according to survey released
Monday.
   A survey commissioned by Moet &amp; Chandon champagne tracked the
cost of a dozen luxury items and services in New York City, and
found they went up in price at twice the 4.4 percent rate of the
government's Consumer Price Index.
   A round-trip ticket on the Air France Concorde from New York to
Paris cost $4,876, up 10.2 percent from $4,424 in 1987. A
Rolls-Royce Corniche convertible cost $205,500, up 12 percent from
$183,500; the caviar cost $47, up from $33.25; a bottle of Hennessy
X.O. cognac cost $78.95, up 7 percent from $73.79, while a bottle of
Dom Perignon cost $69.97, up 8.5 percent from $64.50; and a men's
Rolex Oyster perpetual day-date watch with President bracelet could
be had for $11,700, 12 percent more than last year's $10,450.
   Some items registered price increases that were near or lower
than the overall CPI increase: a ticket to ``Cats,'' $50, up 5.3
percent from last year's $47.50; a wash, cut and blow dry in one of
New York's more exclusive salons cost $70, up 4.5 percent from $67;
and a full-length mink, $17,000, up $500 or 3 percent from last
year's $16,500.
   The prics of three items remained unchanged: a one-hour limousine
rental at $40, a pound of imported chocolate truffles at $36, and
maid service for a day, at $88.
</TEXT>
