<FILEID>AP-NR-03-06-89 2332EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-PillsburyLayoffs     03-06 0333</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pillsbury Layoffs,0345</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pillsbury To Lay Off 550 in Minneapolis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BAENEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pillsbury Co., acquired by Britain's Grand
Metropolitan PLC for $5.68 billion two months ago, announced plans
Monday to lay off 550 of the company's 2,350 employees in its
Minneapolis headquarters.
   An ``overlap of functions'' since the food and restaurant company
was acquired by Grand Met was cited as a reason for the
across-the-board layoffs, and one analyst expressed surprise about
the amount of fat on the Doughboy.
   ``These guys (Grand Met) are obviously looking to become low-cost
producers,'' said Craig Carver, an analyst at Dain Bosworth Inc.
   The layoffs over the next several weeks will leave Pillsbury with
about 1,800 employees in Minneapolis and 100,000 worldwide.
   ``The decision to eliminate these positions was necessary to make
Pillsbury a stronger, more profitable company, prepared to compete
successfully in the world marketplace,'' Ian A. Martin, chairman and
chief executive officer of Pillsbury and head of Grand
Metropolitan's worldwide foods group, said in a statement.
   Pillsbury spokesman Larry Haeg said the layoffs affect all job
classifications, from clerical support employees to managerial and
staff-level functions.
   Last month, Pillsbury announced the closing of two plants, in
Grand Forks, N.D., and Joplin, Mo., which will result in 334
layoffs. The shutdowns, effective the end of March, are because of
surplus production capacity resulting from acquisitions and were in
the works before the takeover.
   After a three-month fight, Pillsbury in December agreed to accept
a sweetened $5.68 billion takeover offer from Grand Metropolitan.
The acquisition was completed in January.
   Grand Met is a British real estate, liquor and gambling
conglomerate. Its U.S. holdings include Alpo dog food and Pearle
Vision Centers.
   Pillsbury makes Pillsbury flour, Green Giant vegetables, Haagen
Dazs ice cream and a variety of other products. Pillsbury also owns
the Burger King, Bennigan's and Steak &amp; Ale restaurant chains.
   Grand Met reported sales of more than $11 billion in fiscal 1988.
Pillsbury had sales of $6.2 billion.
</TEXT>
