<FILEID>AP-NR-03-06-89 2157EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-ExxonChairman     03-06 0309</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Exxon Chairman,0323</SECOND>
<HEAD>Exxon Chairman Might Accept Gas Tax Increase</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM S. BERGSTROM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Exxon Corp. Chairman Lawrence G. Rawl said Monday
he might be willing to accept a gasoline tax increase of 5 cents a
gallon if the money was used to repair aging roads and bridges.
   ``There's a lot of money needed for infrastructure,'' Rawl said.
``The U.S. highway system needs a great deal of work done on it.''
   Rawl spoke at a news conference preceding an Economic Club of
Detroit luncheon.
   Rawl said he disagreed with proposals that would use the
increased tax receipts for uses other than roads and bridges. ``A
large increase in the fuel tax is not an easy option for fiscal
relief,'' he said later in his formal address.
   On another matter, Rawl said Exxon expects stable crude oil
prices in the coming year with no marked increases for more than two
years.
   Rawl predicted that the price of North Sea Brent crude oil will
average $15 to $17 a barrel this year, with West Texas Intermediate
crude about $1 a barrel more.
   The predictions represent no change from the current price of
$16.50 for Brent crude and slightly over $18 for West Texas
Intermediate.
   ``After two or three years, we see some growth in prices,'' Rawl
told reporters.
   The Exxon chief executive officer said he wouldn't dispute
predictions of $25- to $30-a-barrel prices by 2000. But he said, ``I
wouldn't bet a nickel on it either.''
   Rawl said he didn't know how long the Organization of Petroleum
Exporting Countries' December agreement to limit the countries'
total production to 18.5 million barrels a day would last.
   Such agreements ``all hold up for a while,'' he said.
   He refused to forecast Exxon's earnings for the year, but said
they would depend heavily on crude oil prices.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
