<FIRST>u f AM-Knight-Ridder     03-06 0258</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Knight-Ridder,0269</SECOND>
<HEAD>Knight-Ridder Seeks Journalism Charter Amendment</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Knight-Ridder Inc. on Monday asked its shareholders
to adopt a charter amendment requiring 80 percent shareholder
approval for any merger or sale that might threaten its newspapers'
journalistic goals.
   The ``super-majority'' would also apply to any merger putting
more than 20 percent of the company under foreign ownership.
   ``Our board believes the company's newspapers serve a unique and
vital public interest in our society,'' said James K. Batten,
president and chief executive officer of Knight-Ridder. ``The
proposed charter amendment is directed at preserving their
journalistic excellence, integrity and independence ....''
   He said the company's newspapers have won 50 Pulitzer prizes,
including 22 in the past four years.
   The proposal is to be voted on at Knight-Ridder's April 28 annual
meeting.
   Batten said he was not aware of any threatened or rumored
takeover effort against Knight-Ridder, which owns 30 newspapers. He
noted that more than half of the company's shares are in the hands
of the current directors, officers, employees and members of the
founding families.
   The ``super-majority,'' as management called it, would be avoided
only if the board studied the merger or buyout plan, and determined
it did not threaten the company's journalistic mission,
Knight-Ridder said.
   The company wants to extend the rule to cases involving foreign
ownership, noting that ``restriction on foreign ownership of our
country's media are not uncommon.''
   The proxy statement says that federal law already prohibits
foreign ownership of more than 20 percent of the stock of any
licensee of any broadcast station.
</TEXT>
