<SECOND>AM-Lotus Suit,0163</SECOND>
<HEAD>All Claims Dismissed Against Lotus</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lotus Development Corp. announced Monday
that a federal judge has dismissed all claims made by SAPC Inc.
against Lotus and its founder, Mitchell D. Kapor.
   In November, U.S. District Judge Robert E. Keeton dismissed
SAPC's claim of copyright infringement, ruling that SAPC gave up its
right to sue when it sold most of its assets to Lotus in 1985.
   Keeton dismissed all remaining charges against Lotus and Kapor
last Wednesday. Those claims included charges of breach of contract,
misappropriation of trade secrets and confidential secrets and
unjust enrichment.
   SAPC's motion for an immediate appeal was denied. A hearing has
been scheduled for March 29 to consider whether to proceed with
Lotus counterclaims seeking full compensation for expenses related
to the suit.
   SAPC's telephone number at its Cambridge headquarters was
disconnected. A spokesman for Lotus said SAPC was still incorporated
but was not doing business.
