<FIRST>r f BC-EEC-Television     03-06 0177</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-EEC-Television,0185</SECOND>
<HEAD>Twelve Disagree On Strategy To Promote High-Definition TV</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The 12 European Economic Community
countries could not agree Monday on a strategy to defend their
high-definition television system and have it adopted worldwide.
   The EEC's ministers of industry differed on the role to be given
to the executive European Commission in promoting the European HDTV
system. A single world system will be adopted next year by the
International Consultative Council of Radiocommunications.
   The ministers were scheduled to agree on a declaration asking for
the adoption of their system worldwide and setting up a special body
to coordinate the action of their governments, the commission and TV
equipment industries.
   Some countries wanted to give the commission a leading role in
the strategy, while West Germany and the Netherlands balked at
handing too much power to the executive.
   HDTV should make TV films as sharp as movies, allowing projection
of the same films on either screen.
   The issue was pased to the EEC's ministers of telecommunications,
who will meet in Luxembourg next month.
</TEXT>
