<HEAD>Japanese-Controlled Company Buys Chip Materials Business</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cincinnati Semiconductor Inc., subsidiary of a
company controlled by a Japanese manufacturer, announced Monday it
has purchased a semiconductor materials business from Cincinnati
Milacron Inc.
   Cincinnati Semiconductor said it has purchased the assets and
business of Cincinnati Milacron's wholly owned subsidiary,
Cincinnati Milacron Semiconductor Materials Inc. The materials
company produces silicon epitaxial wafers, a material used in making
semiconductor devices.
   Terms of the deal were not disclosed.
   Milacron announced in December that it was negotiating to sell
its semiconductor materials business to a subsidiary of Osaka
Titanium Co. Ltd. of Japan. Cincinnati Semiconductor is a subsidiary
of OTC Semiconductor Corp., a California company in which Osaka
Titanium holds a majority interest.
   Osaka Titanium said it plans to continue all operations at the
southwestern Ohio semiconductor materials plant in the Maineville
community, where Cincinnati Milacron has been operating the
business. The Japanese manufacturer said it ultimately plans to
expand the facility to make it more internationally competitive.
