<FIRST>u f AM-Eastern-Money     03-06 0260</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Eastern-Money,0269</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eastern's Bank Account Shrinking; It's Facing $70 Million Debt Payment
Soon</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Eastern Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastern Airlines' roughly $400 million in cash
will drain fast because the strikebound carrier must pay competitors
to fly waylaid passengers and it's facing a $70 million debt
repayment within weeks, a leading debt-rating agency said Monday.
   ``The strike poses a serious threat to Eastern's survival, and
management may choose to cease operations or seek bankruptcy
protection if more pilots don't return to work soon,'' Standard &amp;
Poor's Corp. said in a bulletin about the finances of the
Miami-based airline.
   Eastern was struck by its Machinists union Saturday and pilots
and flight attendants have been honoring picket lines.
   S&amp;P said the airline began the year with $402 million in cash but
the reserve fell slightly in January and February because of
operating losses. Eastern has said it is losing about $1 million a
day.
   ``Refunds and payments to other airlines flying passengers
ticketed to Eastern will dissipate most of its cash reserves within
several weeks,'' S&amp;P's bulletin said.
   Under so-called interline agreements among airlines, passengers
ticketed on Eastern may use their tickets on competitors, which get
a reimbursement from the airline later. Eastern has been forced to
transfer thousands of passengers from canceled or delayed flights to
seats on other airlines.
   S&amp;P also said Eastern may have to repay $70 million worth of
unspecified secured debt at the end of March. Secured debt is a loan
backed by assets of the borrower, which in Eastern's case could
include aircraft.
</TEXT>
