<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Entertainment and communications issues set the
pace as the stock market staged a broad advance Monday.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials rose 20.53 points to
2,294.82.
   Advancing issues outnumbered declines by better than 2 to 1 in
nationwide trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed stocks, with
995 up, 475 down and 486 unchanged.
   Volume on the floor of the Big Board came to 168.88 million
shares, up from 151.79 million in the previous session. Nationwide,
consolidated volume in NYSE-listed issues, including trades in those
stocks on regional exchanges and in the over-the-counter market,
totaled 200.72 million shares.
   The big news of the session was the weekend merger agreement
between Time Inc. and Warner Communications.
   Analysts said the deal immediately touched off speculation that
other companies in the entertainment and publishing industries might
be candidates for mergers or takeovers.
   Warner stock led the active list and jumped 2] to 48\, while
Time's shares dropped 1| to 107{. Analysts said Time's decline in
part reflected disappointment among traders who had been reckoning
that the company might itself have become a takeover candidate at a
higher price.
   Chris-Craft Industries, which owns a 17 percent interest in
Warner, gained 3} to 33{.
   Elsewhere in the communications and entertainment group, Gulf &amp;
Western rose 2{ to 45~; MCA 2[ to 53; Walt Disney 1\ to 77|; Orion
Pictures 1[ to 16~, and Columbia Pictures Entertainment 1 to 18].
   Brokers also said the overall market benefited from a monthly
report by a purchasing managers' group that suggested a slowing of
economic growth.
   That was interpreted as a favorable portent for the inflation
outlook and a possible slackening of upward pressure on interest
rates.
   The news got a warm welcome in the credit markets. Prices of
long-term government bonds, which move in the opposite direction
from interest rates, rose as much as $5 for each $1,000 in face
value.
   Ohio Mattress gained 2~ to 24|. The company agreed to a
$25.50-a-share buyout by the investment firm of Gibbons, Green, Van
Amerongen.
   Shaklee, subject of a $40-a-share bid from a group led by invest
Irwin Jacobs, rose 4} to 38}.
   Takeover rumors and speculation prompted gains in such other
issues as Longview Fibre, up 4} at 68|, and Reebok International, up
| at 14\.
   As measured by Wilshire Associates' index of more than 5,000
actively traded stocks, the market increased $28.32 billion, or 0.98
percent, in value.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks added
1.73 to 165.63.
   Standard &amp; Poor's industrial index rose 4.04 to 340.39, and S&amp;P's
500-stock composite index was up 3.63 at 294.81.
   The NASDAQ composite index for the over-the-counter market gained
2.27 to 406.26. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index closed at 327.99, up 1.77.
