<FILEID>AP-NR-03-06-89 1943EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>b f AM-Eastern-Pilots Bjt   03-06 0526</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Eastern-Pilots, Bjt,0546</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eastern Shutdown, Air Slowdown Show Power of Pilots</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 17-month labor dispute at Eastern Airlines, capped
by the virtual shutdown of the strike-torn carrier Monday, displays
the power of pilots over their employers.
   The decision by most of the 3,600 Eastern pilots to join the
working-class Machinists' strike dealt a crushing blow to Eastern
after a long history of financial losses and labor-management
tensions.
   And ``pilot power'' is poised to expand its reach Tuesday, when
pilots across the country planned a job action that could delay
every flight on every major airline.
   Eastern on day three of the strike said it was shutting down
nearly all operations and idling 5,000 to 6,000 workers. The company
was quick to blame the pilots, saying it could not afford to
continue operating because they had honored the Machinists' picket
lines.
   ``The pilots are conducting their own economic strike against the
company,'' Eastern spokesman Robin Matell said.
   Why did Eastern pilots, who earn an average $80,000 a year, cast
their lot with mechanics and baggage handlers who make about $19 and
$15 an hour respectively?
   ``The older pilots don't have a chance to go to another
airline,'' said Gordon Lane, an Eastern pilot. ``We're going to lose
our profession.''
   ``The fact that we're out here (picketing) is Frank Lorenzo,
period,'' said Lane, 47, who has flown for Eastern for 22 years.
   Lorenzo, who controls Eastern through parent Texas Air Corp., has
been a lightning rod for the pilots' anger. He is widely mistrusted
by pilots and other Eastern workers because of what they call his
triumphant union-crushing campaign at sister carrier Continental
Airlines.
   They also accuse Lorenzo of diverting precious Eastern assets to
Continental.
   The Eastern pilots have been torn between their dislike for
Lorenzo and reluctance to quit the airline and sacrifice years of
seniority.
   A shortage of pilots nationwide means they could easily find jobs
at other airlines, but they would have to relinquish seniority and
accept lower pay and benefits, said Kit Darby, executive vice
president of Future Aviation Professionals of America in Atlanta.
   ``The job market (for pilots) is extremely good,'' Darby said,
noting that the airline pilots earn an average $82,500 a year plus
substantial benefits.
   Eastern had said about 200 pilots out of 3,600 were flying during
the strike, but the pilots union put the number at 88. Eastern has
operated only a fraction of its customary 1,040 daily flights during
the strike.
   Air Line Pilots Association President Henry Duffy has asked all
pilots nationwide to strictly follow aviation rules Tuesday ``to
ensure the safety of the (air traffic) system,'' which he said had
been weakened by the Eastern disruptions.
   Duffy said the action would slow air traffic, but insisted that
was not the intent.
   ``We expect a very good response from pilots at all carriers,''
ALPA spokesman John Mazor said. ``Pilots are going to recognize that
there are problems generated out of the Eastern strike that have a
ripple effect throughout the system.''
   Delta Air Lines pilots prepared to join the slowdown, and pilots
at United Airlines also expressed support.
</TEXT>
