<FILEID>AP-NR-03-06-89 2311EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-SoftwareSuit     03-06 0137</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Software Suit,0143</SECOND>
<HEAD>Software Company Wins Violated Copyright Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge has ruled in favor of a
Massachusetts software company in a copyright infringement case that
may protect software manufacturers against what is called the ``look
and feel'' of clones.
   The judge, in Bridgeport, Conn., ruled recently that three
competitors infringed on the copyright of the Costimator program
made by Manufacturers Technologies Inc. of West Springfield.
   The Costimator helps users to estimate the time and cost of
manufacturing parts.
   The competitors did not copy the mechanics of the Costimator
software but duplicated its on-screen appearance, what is commonly
called the ``look and feel'' of the program.
   The ruling was made in late January, but Manufacturers
Technologies officials said Monday that they delayed publicizing the
decision until the 30-day appeal period had expired.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
